<FIRST>u a AM-RoseInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0719 06-26 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rose Investigation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0719,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose Bet on Games Beginning in '85, Investigator Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more details from report. No pickup.
A version moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY78</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   and=
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BEN WALKER</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Sports Writers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pete Rose bet on Cincinnati Reds games over a
three-year span beginning in 1985, and once accumulated a $400,000
gambling debt over a three-month period, the sport's investigator
concludes in a 225-page report released Monday.
   The report by baseball investigator John M. Dowd was publicly
released Monday by a state judge who had kept it private until after
he ruled on Rose's request for a temporary restraining order.
   ``Between May and July 1987, Rose bet ... $2,000 per game on
baseball, including Reds games,'' the report said.
   Hamilton County Common Pleas Judge Norbert A. Nadel released the
report Monday under pressure from the Ohio Supreme Court, which said
he had no reason to keep it sealed.
   Nadel on Sunday granted Rose's request to block a hearing that
was scheduled for Monday in New York with baseball Commissioner A.
Bartlett Giamatti.
   Rose, Cincinnati's manager, could be banned from the game for
life if it is determined that he bet on the Reds. Dowd's report said
there was much evidence that he did, although it noted that Rose has
denied under oath he ever bet on major league baseball.
   ``The accumulated testimony of witnesses, together with
documentary evidence and telephone records, reveal extensive betting
activity by Pete Rose with professional baseball and, in particular,
Cincinnati Reds games, during the 1985, 1986 and 1987 seasons,''
Dowd said in the report.
   The report quotes Rose associate Paul G. Janszen as saying
``within a three-month period of time, Pete Rose was in debt over
$400,000 to the bookie in New York.'' It does not indicate if the
debt was due to baseball debts or wagers on other sports.
   Rose bet 52 times on the Reds _ and won 29 _ from April 8-July 5,
1987, according to gambling records cited in Dowd's report.
   Dowd cited telephone records and betting slips supplied by
Janszen, who claims to have run bets for Rose, as supporting
evidence. He also said that evidence supports the testimony of
bookmaker Ronald Peters, who claims he took perhaps more than $1
million in bets on behalf of Rose over a two-year period.
   ``The evidence revealed that in order to protect his stature as
one of the most famous baseball players in major league history,
Pete Rose employed middlemen to place bets for him with bookmakers
and at the raetrack and to pay gambling losses and collect gambling
winnings, thereby concealing his gambling activity,'' Dowd wrote.
   Despite the $400,000 debt, the report said, Rose had been
successful early in the 1987 season in bets with Peters, Rose's
chief accuser.
   David Morgan, an associate of Peters, recalled being told by
Peters during the 1987 season that he was ``getting murdered'' by
Pete Rose on baseball.
   ``Morgan stated that Peters advised him that Rose had him
`hooked' for `about seventy-five thousand,' '' the report said.
   In addition, the report says that Rose owned half of a $47,646
Pik-Six ticket at Turfway Park on April 6, 1989. Thomas P. Gioiosa,
Rose's former housemate, ``falsely represented to the IRS that he
was the sole winner,'' the report said. Gioiosa has been indicted
for that and Rose is under investigation by a federal grand jury in
Cincinnati.
   After the Reds beat Los Angeles 5-3 Monday night, Rose was asked
if he believed the report was balanced.
   ``I can give you an outline,'' he said. ``There's 225 pages and
there's two paragraphs positive about me. It's such a biased report
it's unbelievable. But we will face that because there's not a thing
we can do about it.''
   Robert G. Stachler, a Rose attorney, said he was not bothered
that the report was made public. He declined further comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
