<FIRST>r a AM-Helmsley     06-26 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helmsley Tax Evasion Trial Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hotel queen Leona Helmsley went on trial Monday
on federal charges that she evaded income taxes by disguising about
$4 million in renovations to her mansion as business expenses.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 68, watched as potential jurors were questioned
about their impartiality and how much they knew about the highly
publicized case.
   By late afternoon, U.S. District Judge John Walker had
interviewed 18 potential jurors and dismissed four.
   Walker said he would screen the pool of 160 prospective jurors
this week and allow attorneys to make their final peremptory
challenges July 5 before opening arguments.
   One man was excused because he said he was upset about being
asked his salary and because he was mad at judges in general for
allowing the flag to be burned, referring to last week's Supreme
Court decision.
   The other potential jurors who were dismissed were a man who had
read an article about Mrs. Helmsley in Monday's New York Post; an
accountant who once did work for a company that will be named at
trial; and a man who said he was angry with the Internal Revenue
Service for the way it handled a tax problem.
   Mrs. Helmsley was named in a 47-count indictment in April 1988
with her husband, Harry, and two former Helmsley executives.
   The Helmsleys, who head a $5 billion hotel and real estate
empire, were accused of evading personal income taxes by concealing
about $4 million in renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion
as business expenses.
   Helmsley, 80, has been found incompetent to stand trial because
of his memory lapses.
   The other defendants, Frank Turco and Joseph V. Licari, are
charged with helping create bogus invoices to make it appear the
renovations on the 28-room mansion were tax-deductible improvements
on business properties.
   Many potential jurors said they knew the Helmsleys from media
reports and Mrs. Helmsley from advertisements for her hotels that
portray her as the ``queen'' of Helmsley-owned hotels.
   Walker allowed jurors to remain in the pool if they said they
could be impartial.
   One answer given by a 28-year-old architect's intern prompted a
cold stare from Mrs. Helmsley.
   The juror was asked what he knew of the Helmsleys from the media.
``He's old and feeble, and Leona runs things,'' the man said.
</TEXT>
