<FIRST>u w AM-German-Chemicals     06-26 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German-Chemicals,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germany Moving Against Firm in Iran Chemical Weapons Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government is taking action
against a German firm that has arranged the sale to Iran of
chemicals that make poison gas, U.S. officials confirmed Monday
night.
   The officials said Secretary of State James A. Baker III
discussed the sale with Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher
during Genscher's visit to the United States last week.
   ``We've been very happy'' with the German response, said one
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Both officials said they did not have precise details of just
what the German government was doing in the case.
   The New York Times said in Tuesday editions that a Dusseldorf
firm, which U.S. officials did not identify, had acted as a broker
in arranging the sale to Iran of hundreds of tons of thionyl
chloride, a chemical that can be used to make mustard gas, by an
Indian manufacturer.
   The bulk of the chemicals was said not to have been delivered.
   Iranian troops were the targets of several gas attacks by Iraq in
the eight-year war between those two countries.
   Last winter, U.S. officials accused German firms of helping Libya
built a plant that could be used to produce chemical weapons, though
Libya insisted the plant would be used for pharmaceuticals.
   In response, the German government has proposed legislation to
stiffen export controls and penalties for violating them.
</TEXT>
