<FIRST>r a AM-UnisysDocuments     06-26 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unisys Documents,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Again Extends Sealing Order On Unisys Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday extended a sealing
order on several documents seized by government agents who were
looking for evidence that Unisys Corp. bought information to help it
win defense contracts.
   Judge Diana E. Murphy extended until July 27 the sealing order
affecting documents taken from the offices of Unisys employees Ralph
Hughes, Bob Elfering and Bill Geiger.
   The three were among those searched on June 14, 1988, in a
nationwide sweep by federal agents investigating possible bribery of
public officials, conspiracy and fraud in the defense department's
procurement system.
   A number of documents relating to searches of the Minnesota
facilities of Unisys have been sealed at the government's request
since June 16, 1988. Other documents have been made public since the
initial sealing order was filed.
   On May 17, the court had extended the sealing order for several
of the documents until June 26, when the government had believed
that its need for continued sealing of the documents would end.
   However, because of scheduling conflicts, the government moved to
extend the order until July 27 because it had been unable to proceed
as quickly as expected.
</TEXT>
