<DOCNO> AP890626-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-GrenadaTrial     06-26 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grenada Trial,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Those Accused of Killing Caribbean Leader Wait and Wait</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly six years after an army
firing squad killed Prime Minister Maurice Bishop after a military
coup, 17 people accused in the slaying still await a final verdict.
   Bishop's death in a factional struggle within his ruling party
helped lead to the U.S. invasion of the island in 1983. The
prisoners claim they were convicted in a U.S.-backed show trial to
justify the invasion and eliminate the remaining inner circle of
Bishop's Marxist regime.
   Of the 16 men and one woman, 14 are condemned to hang for murder.
Three soldiers charged with the actual shooting face decades in
prison for manslaughter.
   However, the prisoners are asking the Court of Appeal, Grenada's
highest court, to throw out their December 1986 convictions for the
killing of Bishop and several supporters.
   Their appeal has been dragging on since May 1988, straining the
tiny island's treasury and the patience of many of the nation's
90,000 residents, who have little sympathy for the prisoners.
   ``The people are fed up with it,'' said Leslie Pierre, editor of
the Grenadian Voice, an independent weekly newspaper. ``It's been
going on and on and on. ... They want it finished with.''
   The original High Court trial lasted nearly eight months, and it
took a year to produce a 9,000-page court record. The 13 defense
lawyers won a six-month delay to prepare the appeal.
   Seven months into the appeal, the president of the three-judge
court died, and the appeal had to start again with a new president.
   At the current pace, it will go on through fall because the
six-lawyer prosecution team hasn't even started its case.
   Meanwhile, the Grenadian government is paying court costs as well
as the fees and expenses of the 10 Jamaican lawyers representing
those prisoners who claimed indigency.
   So far, the case has cost the government $2.7 million, or 5
percent of the nation's annual $55 million budget.
   ``It's bleeding us, but we're prepared to spend that sort of
money ... so that we can say, `Look at the sacrifice we're prepared
to make,''' to give the defendants a fair trial, said Justice
Minister Danny Williams.
   The killing of Bishop, a popular prime minister, resulted from a
dispute over leadership of his radical People's Revolutionary
Government. A hard-line Revolutionary Military Council, led by
Bernard Coard, took control and placed the prime minister under
house arrest.
   On Oct. 19, 1983, hundreds of Bishop supporters converged on his
residence and set him free.
   However, troop reinforcements rushed in, allegedly on orders of
the military council.
   Bishop, three members of his Cabinet _ including his pregnant
mistress, Education Minister Jacqueline Cleft _ and four other
people were lined up against a wall and shot by three soldiers. A
witness said one assailant slit Bishop's throat long after he was
clearly dead and also cut off a finger to steal a ring.
   President Reagan ordered the invasion involving 1,900 U.S. troops
and small forces from other Carribean island nations. He said he
wanted to protect the lives of about 1,000 U.S. citizens in Grenada
and help restore democracy.
   Those on death row include Coard, Grenada's former deputy prime
minister; his wife, Phyllis; the former armed forces commander, Gen.
Hudson Austin; and the former ambassador to Cuba, Leon Cornwall.
   The prisoners have accused authorities of human rights abuses
ranging from withholding of sheets, blankets and underwear to
beatings, bread-and-water diets and long periods of solitary
confinement.
   Mrs. Coard, a former member of the ruling Central Committee who
wrote a book in prison called ``U.S. War on One Woman,'' claims she
has been held in solitary confinement for the past 4{ years and
allowed to see her husband only in court.
   Prime Minister Herbert Blaize scoffed at the prisoners'
allegations, and Terrence Marryshow, leader of the opposition
Maurice Bishop Patriotic Movement, called them ``only the victims of
a situation that they themselves created.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
