<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill'sReach 2Takes   06-26 1205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill's Reach, 2 Takes,1235</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Three Months, Blot of Oil Still Spreads Across Alaska Coastline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Sunday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Spill Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three months have passed, and the sea still
coughs up dead birds with every change of the tide.
   Three months have passed, and an army of workers 9,000 strong has
yet to completely clean even one heavily oiled beach.
   Three months have passed, and the biggest oil spill in U.S.
history gets bigger every day, spreading its slime farther across
Alaska's wild southern coast, pushing its poison deeper and higher
along the food chain.
   ``We keep hoping for some kind of closure, some sign that this is
all the damage we have and we can deal with it,'' says Anne
Castellina, superintendent of Kenai Fjords National Park. ``But we
can't. The oil disappears one day when the waves clean a beach, only
to wash up on another beach the next day.''
   Prince William Sound's bountiful waters and mountainous islands
were the first to be fouled after the tanker Exxon Valdez rammed a
reef March 24 and spilled almost 11 million gallons of North Slope
crude oil.
   But the damage didn't stop there. Streamers of oil and tar balls
leaked out between the sound's barrier islands and were pushed by
Gulf of Alaska currents to beaches 450 miles away.
   Oil now has tainted more than 700 miles of shoreline, from the
glacier-carved cliffs of Kenai Fjords to the clamoring bird
rookeries of Katmai National Park, from lonely Cook Inlet beaches to
the mouths of Kodiak Island salmon streams.
   Cleanup workers have found the oil-soaked bodies of about 26,000
sea birds, 784 sea otters and 57 bald eagles. The spreading oil has
other victims. Fishermen and other coastal residents who make their
living from the ocean cringe each week at news of more beaches
polluted and more fishing grounds closed.
   The wreck of the Exxon Valdez created an environmental
catastrophe that unfolds in one little tragedy after another:
   _A wildlife official filming damage on a beach sets a video
cassette down on a black rock, and the rock crawls away. It turns
out to be an oil-smeared duck.
   _A burly fisherman breaks into tears as he describes steering his
boat through the slick: no water lapping, no birds crying, just the
sickening silence of oil slipping past the hull.
   _At a bird rescue center in Seward, some of the patients are
failing. They have been washed clean, but not before swallowing
fatal doses of oil. They don't cry out; instinct tells them not to
advertise their distress to predators. ``They just get real quiet,
sit in a corner and die,'' says rescue coordinator Jay Holcomb.
   Like a candy bar in the hands of a 2-year-old, crude oil from the
Exxon Valdez has gotten onto everything.
   Rainbow sheens on the water stream from suffocating mats of black
goop on beaches. Wind and waves whip oil into a sticky froth that
workers call ``chocolate mousse.'' Tar balls bob in the surf,
washing ashore to melt in the sun and sink into the sand. Oil
splatters driftwood logs high above the tide line and sinks as much
as 3 feet into gravel beaches. Undulating blobs of oil hang below
the water's surface, ready to foul fishermen's nets.
   At first, Exxon boldly promised to clean it all up.
   ``We're going to pick up _ one way or the other _ all the oil
that's out there,'' Exxon spokesman Don Cornett told reporters one
week after the Exxon Valdez ran aground.
   The promise didn't keep for long.
   Exxon was too slow and the spill was too big for booms to contain
the oil immediately after the accident. And the company missed its
chance during the first few days to burn off large quantities of oil
or disperse it with chemicals. Some oil was skimmed up, but for the
most part Exxon had to wait for oil to wash up on shore, where the
goo could be scraped, wiped or flushed painstakingly from rocks and
gravel.
   By May 1, the clean-it-all promise had been modified. Exxon
proposed to clean 364 miles of coastline by mid-September, noting
that it might have to leave 191 additional miles of lightly oiled
shore to be washed by nature.
   The Coast Guard approved Exxon's plan, but even the limited
cleanup may prove beyond the company's capability, despite an
investment of more than $200 million to date.
   The cleanup effort now includes more than 9,000 workers, 800
boats, 45 oil skimmers, and 60 airplanes and helicopters. Hundreds
of workers clad in rain slickers and hard hats crowd into coves that
in most years might see a few fishermen or recreational boaters, if
anyone at all.
   Barges nose up to shore, carrying generators and boilers to heat
the water sprayed from hoses on the beach. Skimmers just offshore
pick up oil as it flushes off the beach, while yet more vessels tend
containment booms to keep the washed-off oil from spreading.
   Where there isn't enough machinery, workers hit the beaches with
shovels, absorbent pads and plastic bags, scooping and scraping and
wiping by hand.
   ``It has become pretty labor-intensive,'' says Exxon spokesman
Amos Plante.
   The Coast Guard, which is overseeing Exxon's cleanup effort, has
``signed off'' on about 50 miles of shoreline along Prince William
Sound. But that doesn't mean a beach is clean _ it just means Exxon
can move on. Even the most intensive scrubbing cannot touch oil
imbedded deep within a beach.
   The word ``clean'' is now taboo on official forms used to track
Exxon's efforts. Workers don't clean beaches anymore. They ``treat''
them.
   The difference is more than semantics, as a visit to a Prince
William Sound beach with a state environmental official shows.
``This,'' says Steve Provant as he kicks an oily rock, ``is a
treated beach.''
   Provant, the on-scene cleanup coordinator for the Alaska
Department of Environmental Conservation, is standing on a Green
Island beach known to officials as GR-1A. The Coast Guard signed off
on this beach May 29, declaring that Exxon crews had ``completed
removal of gross contamination.'' Provant saw it back then, and it
looked pretty good, he says.
   But now the oil is back. Globs of mousse litter the cobbled
beach. Rainwater beads up on the rocks as it would on the waxed hood
of a car. Provant digs into the sand, and his hand comes up greasy
brown.
   ``If you dig, you find oil down quite a ways,'' Provant says.
``You can see how much oil has been washed back in or has percolated
up from below. We're really not through with this beach.''
   Provant's agency hounds Exxon, suggesting ways the cleanup could
run more efficiently. Exxon, state and federal officials spend hours
each day arguing over how deeply to clean particular beaches, or
whether cleaning them will do more harm than good.
   ``Everybody wants a clean beach, us included,'' says Exxon's
Plante. ``The definition of clean is subject to interpretation. What
we're obviously going to do is work as hard to do the best job we
can. We may have some disagreements over whether it's sufficiently
clean.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill'sReach-1stAdd     06-26 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill's Reach - 1st Add,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>VALDEZ: sufficiently clean.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   While the arguments rage onshore, the death toll mounts at sea.
   Stymied by vast distances and stormy weather, bird rescuers have
been able to capture, clean and release only about 500 sea birds.
For every surviving bird, more than 50 dead ones lie in freezer vans
_ more than 26,000 in all. And that's just a fraction of total
mortality. Some biologists say that for every dead bird collected,
perhaps 100 have died unnoticed.
   Sea otters appear to be the hardest-hit marine mammal. The 784
dead sea otters collected so far represent about one-tenth of Prince
William Sound's total population. Harbor seals may be suffering,
too, but few carcasses have been found. ``Dead seals sink like lead
balloons,'' explains state marine biologist Kathy Frost.
   The oil's lethal reach extends down the food chain. On some
beaches, mats of oil have wiped out all life, suffocating intertidal
creatures such as limpets, mussels, crabs and starfish.
   And the oil reaches upward, to the tops of tall shoreside spruce
trees where bald eagles roost. Oiled sea birds have become a fatal
attraction for scavenging eagles, killing 57 of the birds of prey.
Biologists have collected lifeless eggs from 30 abandoned eagle
nests in the spill area.
   Hungry brown bears on the shores of Katmai National Park have
feasted on oily bird carcasses until they could eat no more, digging
holes in the sand to cache the leftovers.
   Bears are hardy creatures, but biologists have radio-collared 30
of them to study their reaction to swallowing so much oil. ``We
haven't determined what effect it has on them. But I can imagine
what it would do to me,'' says Katmai National Park Superintendent
Ray Bane.
   At the very top of the food chain are the humans who live close
to nature in coastal villages. When Aleut natives complained that
the oil spill kept them from gathering food through fishing and
seal-hunting, Exxon flew in cases of beef, chicken and diced ham. It
gave the villagers stomachaches.
   Many commercial fishermen have been idled by the spill, though
some have landed jobs with Exxon, leasing their boats at rates of
$3,400 a day and more.
   Most of the salmon and halibut swimming beneath the oil appear to
be surviving. But fisheries worth more than $110 million have been
canceled or postponed by Alaska officials worried that surface oil
might taint fish as they are hauled from the water in fishermen's
nets.
   As spring turns to summer, even Exxon officials are starting to
waver on the question of finishing the cleanup by mid-September, a
deadline long dismissed as unrealistic by some state and federal
officials.
   ``It's always a hope,'' says Exxon's Plante. ``But it's tougher
to predict whether we'll do it by then. That's our plan. We've
always said we will not leave it uncleaned, and if that means coming
back, so be it.''
   The sooner the better for all concerned _ particularly for 120
frisky sea otters now swimming restlessly in floating pens. They've
beaten the odds, thanks to rescuers at an otter hospital in Seward.
The animals are clean, healthy and ready to return to the wild.
   But they must stay put, biologists say, because the wild is not
ready for them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
