<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Massacre 1stLd-Writethru a0428 06-26 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Massacre, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>About 30 People Massacred On Mindanao Island</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT to guerrillas, sted villagers, SUB 6th graf, `Villagers
exchanges ...' Picks up 7th, `Maralit ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels raided a mountain
village in a remote area of Mindanao island and massacred about 30
people as they worshipped in a Protestant church, the military said
Monday.
   The raiders beheaded three people, including a Protestant
minister, before fleeing, the report said.
   Lt. Col. Cresencio Maralit, spokesman for the Philippine
Constabulary, said the incident occurred early Sunday in the village
of Rano, about 640 miles southeast of Manila.
   Maralit said many of the villagers had joined an anti-Communist
vigilante group and had refused to pay ``revolutionary taxes'' to
the communist New People's Army.
   According to Maralit, about 40 members of the Ubo and Bagobo
tribes had gathered inside a United Church of Christ chapel for
morning worship when about 100 guerrillas arrived.
   Guerrillas exchanged gunfire for about 15 minutes with members of
the congregation, who were armed, Maralit said.
   Maralit identified the dead pastor as Abadi Ayap. But a
denomination official in Manila said records indicated no such
pastor by that name.
   Bishop Erme Camba, secretary-general of the denomination, said
the victim could have been a lay pastor. The bishop said he was
still trying to verify the report.
   The United Church of Christ has been widely criticized by the
military for alleged links with Communist rebels because of the
denomination's outspoken stand on human rights.
   In the past, most beheadings in Mindanao have been carried out by
religious fanatics who are frequently used by the military to fight
the Communists.
</TEXT>
