<FIRST>r w PM-KochIndustries     06-26 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Koch Industries,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Investigates Kansas Company Accused of Stealing Oil From
Indians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kansas-based company faces a criminal
investigation based on allegations that it stole oil from
Indian-owned wells, according to a spokesman for a Senate committee.
   The Justice Department probe stems from information about Koch
Industries Inc. gathered by a special investigating committee of the
Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs, spokesman Sam Hirsch said.
   ``This has been referred to the U.S. attorney,'' George Pearson,
a spokesman for Koch, based in Wichita, Kan.
   Pearson said Koch officials and representatives of the U.S.
attorney in Oklahoma City will meet before a formal investigation
begins, although no date has been set for the meeting.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Nancy Jones, in Oklahoma City, said her
office can ``neither confirm nor deny the existence of an ongoing
investigation.''
   The special Senate committee focused on Koch, the country's
largest independent oil purchaser, at a May 10 hearing in which
witnesses said Koch employees purposely mismeasured oil from wells
on Indian lands.
   In a 57-page statement issued June 8, Koch said the committee
``unjustly defamed Koch and caused severe damage to its reputation
and business.''
   The 49-year-old company said the figures the committee used in
its allegations were inaccurate, and that comparisons with other
companies were based on noncomparable statistics.
   The committee used ``anecdotal evidence which was misleading at
best and false at worst'' at the hearing, the Koch statement said.
   But Hirsch said the committee stands by its findings.
   ``The committee's investigators caught Koch employees in the act
of stealing oil on six separate occasions,'' he said. ``Koch gaugers
and supervisors also admitted to committee investigators that it was
company policy to mismeasure oil.''
   Hirsch said documents the committee subpoenaed from Koch and
almost 30 other companies corroborated the committee's findings. He
said the committee will review Koch's June 8 statement before making
its final report, sometime this fall.
   The special committee has been investigating all areas of Indian
affairs and came upon the Koch case while probing federal agencies
assigned to protecting Indian lands.
</TEXT>
