<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     06-26 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA, States Help Promote Organic Farming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates of organic farming are generous in
their praise, saying it is a way for crop producers to make money
and save the environment at the same time.
   Even the Agriculture Department, which had been rather stodgy
about producing wheat, corn, soybeans, vegetables and other crops
with reduced or eliminated doses of chemicals has adjusted.
   Numerous conferences and research efforts have marked USDA's new
journey into organic farming, but it was Congress in the 1985 farm
law that really gave the department its marching orders, along with
a $4 million appropriation later on.
   The department even used a new term _ Low Input Sustainable
Agriculture, or LISA _ to include what had been loosely referred to
as organic, sustainable or alternative methods of farming.
   Comparatively, USDA is doing much more today in programs to help
small farmers and to assist both large and small producers find
alternative methods of production. By using less commercial
fertilizer and pesticides, it is hoped that producers can reduce
costs and thereby improve profits.
   But a Washington-based, non-profit advocacy group, the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, says organic and low-chemical
farming ``is flourising at the state level'' while the federal
effort is moving slowly.
   A new study by the center found that half the states have
``significant activities to promote sustainable agriculture,''
including strong efforts in California, Iowa, Maine, Minnesota,
Texas and Wisconsin.
   ``Here in Washington, proponents have to scratch and claw just to
hang on to a tiny $4.45 million sustainable agriculture program that
the Bush administration and the chemical lobby want to kill,'' said
Dan Howell, author of the center's report.
   ``In contrast,'' he said, ``states are spending more money on a
greater variety of ambitious programs to increase the production and
marketing of foods grown with few or no synthetic pesticides and
fertilizers.''
   Other studies by advocates of low-input agriculture support
claims that crop yields often are comparable to those from
chemically treated land after a practice has been established and
crop rotation carried out.
   But Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm Bureau
Federation, said, ``If it were as simple as reducing purchased
inputs and reaping the rewards, it would have been in practice years
ago.''
   Farmers are willing to adopt proven methods that result from the
low-input concept, he recently told a Senate agriculture
subcommittee. But the technology must be based on more than a whim
and a promise.
   ``Farmers cannot afford to take big risks with a new and unproven
technology,'' Kleckner said. ``As we see it, LISA programs represent
a long-term goal for agriculture.''
   Kleckner said some aspects of LISA have shown good results, such
as ``integrated pest management'' to reduce the amount of pesticides
on crops by being more selective and careful about timing during the
season.
   In New York, he said, pest management reduced the amount of
pesticide used on apples by 38 percent and on onions by 31 percent.
Texas farmers were able to reduce pesticide use on carrots by 66
percent and on cabbage by 44 percent.
   At present, Kleckner said, low-input farming ``is still more a
philosophy and spirit of farming than an easily defined set of
principles.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has some summer
advice about dogs and cats.
   ``That old bromide about hot weather discomfort tells us that
horses sweat and men perspire, and ladies gently glow,'' says the
department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service. ``If you're
a pet owner, however, you should know that dogs and cats do none of
the above.''
   Instead, they pant. And agency experts say that can lead to
deadly consequences if left unchecked.
   ``Each year, hundreds of pets die of heat, usually because their
owners just aren't aware of how quickly heat can kill,'' said
veterinarian Dale Schwindaman, who heads the agency's animal care
staff.
   ``If you leash your dog outside, make certain it can move easily
to a shady spot. Make plenty of water available to it as well,
especially if you'll be away from home for long periods.''
   Pets should never be left unattended in a vehicle, he said. And
cracking a window an inch or two will not adequately protect an
animal. Heat in a car can rise to 160 degrees in a very short time.
   As for car trips, Schwindaman said that for a highly nervous
animal even a brief ride can be a severe strain in hot weather.
   ``This is especially true if your pet is an indoor cat or dog who
would be frightened simply by the surroundings and noise of an
unfamiliar environment,'' he said. ``In this case, if the trip is
absolutely necessary, the pet owner should make every effort to
transport the animal in an air-conditioned vehicle.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department report shows that
catfish production continues to rise unabated, with May production
up 42 percent from a year earlier to 28.9 million pounds.
   Through the first five months of 1989, production was 141.2
million pounds, a 15 percent increase from the same period of last
year, the report said.
   Despite the larger output, catfish farmers are getting more for
their product, averaging 76 cents per pound in May, up a penny from
a year ago.
</TEXT>
