<FIRST>r w PM-Mitchell-Contra     06-26 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mitchell-Contra,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Majority Leader Sees No Need To Reopen Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some questions about the Iran-Contra affair may
never be answered, although new details may come out in the upcoming
trials of John Poindexter and Gen. Richard Secord, says Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell.
   The Senate Intelligence Committee's report on why some White
House documents on the Iran-Contra affair were not turned over to
Congress does not warrant reopening the overall inquiry, Mitchell
said Sunday.
   ``There is no basis at this time, in my judgment, for a
resumption of the investigation or for the creation of a new
investigation,'' Mitchell said.
   ``Obviously, there are loose ends,'' he said in an interview on
NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
   ``Not every single question has been answered and every one may
not be answered,'' said the majority leader, who served on the
special Iran-Contra investigating committee. ``But there comes a
question of balance in terms of whether one should or should not
reopen the investigation.''
   Mitchell said more about Reagan's role in the funneling of
proceeds from arms sales to Iran to the Contras likely will surface
during the trials of Poindexter, who succeeded Robert McFarlane as
national security adviser, and Secord, a former Air Force general.
   The Maine Democrat had asked the Senate panel to examine why
congressional investigators never saw the six previously undisclosed
White House memos when copies surfaced during the trial of former
national security aide Oliver North.
   The intelligence panel reported Friday that the White House
sometimes handled documents in a chaotic and haphazard manner when
Congress sought them for its Iran-Contra hearings two years ago. But
the committee said there was no evidence of a calculated cover-up by
the Reagan administration.
   Among those documents was a Feb. 19, 1985, memo to former
President Reagan from then-National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane.
   The memo recommended that Reagan write Honduran President Roberto
Suazo to reaffirm U.S. support for Contra rebels in Nicaragua and
pledge U.S. help in defending Honduras if Nicaraguan troops crossed
its border.
   Located in an informal ``heads of state'' file in a box of papers
at Reagan's presidential library in California, the document
suggested a ``quid pro quo'' arrangement with Honduras that has been
denied by President Bush. At the time, Congress had banned direct
U.S. aid to the Contras.
</TEXT>
