<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CongressRdp     06-26 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress Rdp,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Getting Down to Business on Defense Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Armed Services Committee members are
looking for money in the Pentagon budget to keep a new helicopter
and a new fighter, and lawmakers say funds intended for the B-2
bomber and Star Wars are likely targets.
   The Armed Services Committee will be working this week on the
$295.6 billion Pentagon budget, and Rep. Albert G. Bustamante,
D-Texas, said some of the money ``has to come out of the system.''
   He predicted B-2 funds will be cut and that ``SDI (Strategic
Defense Initiative) will take a big hit _ $1.6 billion to $1.8
billion.''
   Several committee members are seeking restoration of money for
the V-22 Osprey helicopter and the F-14D Tomcat fighter jet, both
slated for burial in Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's proposed budget.
   Reps. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., and Marvin Leath, D-Texas, plan
to introduce an amendment Tuesday that would provide an additional
$1.2 billion for the National Guard and reserves. The current $69
billion procurement budget earmarks about 3 percent for reserve
forces, Montgomery said.
   Reps. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., and Thomas Foglietta, D-Pa., meanwhile,
have convinced members of the Armed Services research and
development subcommittee to save the Marine V-22 Osprey with $351
million that had been earmarked for the B-2 bomber.
   In closed session, the panel voted 11-7 to approve the amendment,
according to Weldon and Foglietta.
   The Osprey, the Marine Corps' revolutionary tilt-rotor aircraft
that takes off like a helicopter but can fly like a plane, has
widespread support in Congress, especially among former Marines and
members from Pennsylvania and Texas where the Osprey is built by
Boeing Helicopter Co. and Bell Helicopter Textron Inc.
   Opponents of the stealth bomber, considered the most expensive in
history at a cost of between $500 million and $650 million a copy,
sounded off against that program last week.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, appealed to Cheney to suspend production because the B-2
has yet to undergo flight testing.
   The estimated fiscal 1990 cost for the B-2 is $4.7 billion and
over a three-year peak spending period the pricetag is $24 billion.
   ``The Department of Defense has produced a B-2 program that won't
fly financially,'' said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the
House Armed Services panel.
   The Pentagon has invested about $22.4 billion in the B-2 program,
which is expected to cost about $70 billion to complete. Cheney
indicated last week that initial flight tests of the bomber will be
conducted by the end of the summer.
   In addition to focusing on B-2 funds, members are looking at the
proposed $4.9 billion for Star Wars, formally known as the Strategic
Defense Initiative.
   Bennett and Rep. Tom Ridge, R-Pa., joined with 31 Republicans and
Democrats earlier in this month in calling for $3.1 billion for Star
Wars in fiscal 1990 rather than the $4.9 billion proposed by the
administration.
   ``Our amendment will help restore that balance. It will mean more
tanks, more planes and more ships while providing for a robust SDI
program,'' Ridge said.
</TEXT>
