<FIRST>r w PM-HUDInsurance     06-26 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Insurance,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Reportedly Halts Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development
has reportedly halted or is reviewing payments to nine mortgage
companies that finance federally backed housing in its coinsurance
program.
   The action is part of an attempt to head off another potential
scandal for the agency, which is the target of congressional
investigations involving allegations of influence-peddling in HUD
housing contracts, The Washington Post reported today.
   Coinsurance permits private lenders to earn lucrative fees by
making mortgage loans to federally backed housing programs. But HUD
assumes most of the losses if a project defaults. The program is
designed to encourage the preservation and rehabilitation of
moderately priced housing.
   HUD has approved a four-month moratorium on new participants for
the program, the Post said, after a recent review by the HUD
inspector general found mismanagement and alleged fraud in the
program. Almost $700 million worth of mortgages are in default, it
said.
   Three lenders were thrown out of the program in March and six
others were put on six-month probation, the Post said.
</TEXT>
