<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0408 06-26 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0408,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, dollar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen Monday,
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange moved slightly higher.
   The dollar closed at 140.18 yen, down from Friday's close of
140.35 yen. It opened at 139.80 yen and ranged between 139.75 yen
and 140.50 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
205.74 points Friday, added 95.11 points, or 0.28 percent, to close
at 33,625.82.
   Currency traders said trading was generally inactive and
directionless during morning trading, lacking fresh market-affecting
news.
   ``Market players sitting on the sidelines are unable to determine
which direction they should move,'' said Masafumi Koyama of the Bank
of Tokyo.
   Koyama said some institutional investors were buying back dollars
following the loss of a conservative party candidate in a
by-election for a seat in the parliament's upper house Sunday.
   A socialist who campaigned by criticizing Japan's new 3 percent
consumption tax and attacking the governing Liberal Democratic party
over an influence-peddling scandal won the election in Niigata,
northwestern Japan, for the House of Councillors.
   Local news media said the result would be a blow to the
pro-business Liberal Democrats, whose popularity has been damaged by
the consumption tax and a number of scandals. Elections for half the
seats of the 252-member upper house are scheduled for next month.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the share prices at first
rose over expectations of lowering interest rates in the United
States, but market participants then took a wait-and-see position,
observing the exchange rate fluctuations and reactions to Sunday's
election.
</TEXT>
