<FIRST>u i AM-SovietSub 4thLd-Writethru a0463 06-26 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Sub, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0463,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Sub on Fire off Norway</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: UPDATES thruout with sub steaming at half-speed for Murmansk.
No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet submarine was on fire off Norway's
northern coast early Monday, spewing thick smoke but sailing east at
half-speed toward the the Soviet naval base at Murmansk, Norwegian
officials said.
   The Soviet news agency Tass initially reported that the vessel
was sending distress signals. But Norwegian officials said later
that crewmen on deck waved away Norwegian rescue helicopter and
appeared ``relatively relaxed.''
   It was not immediately known if the vessel was nuclear-powered or
carrying nuclear weapons.
   ``A Norwegian F-16 fighter ... reported a submarine of unknown
type that was billowing heavy smoke 110 kilometers (70 miles)
northwest of South Island in (the province of) Finnmark,'' Defense
Minister Johan Joergen Holst said on state radio. He said alerted to
the fire at 3:30 a.m. (1:30 a.m. EDT).
   Holst said the submarine was probably carrying nuclear weapons.
   Tass, in its initial report on the fire, did not say what type of
submarine was involved. It said a Soviet reconnaisance plane had
been dispatched.
   Gunnar H. Angletweit, a Norwegian Defense Ministry spokesman,
said later that the submarine was sailing east at half-speed toward
the Soviet Northern Fleet Base at Murmansk.
   A Norwegian rescue helicopter dispatched to the area spotted
several crewmen on deck, but they waved the Sea King helicopter
away, said Terje B. Lien, an official of the Rescue Coordination
Center at Bodoe, Norway.
   He said that the helicopter's crew had apparently mistaken for an
emergency flare a signal that the submarine did not want help. The
rescue center said it canceled orders to Norwegian merchant marine
vessels to sail to the area.
   Col. Gullow Gjeseth, Norwegian Supreme Defense Command spokesman,
said the Soviets appeared to have the situation under control with
rescue efforts from Murmansk.
   ``The crew who were on deck were reported to be relatively
relaxed,'' he told NRK, the state broadcasting company.
   Gjeseth said earlier that the Norwegians had dispatched coast
guard vessels, some equipped to test for radiation.
   ``We must reckon on there being nuclear weapons on board,'' said
the defense spokesman, adding that it is impossible to tell what
armaments are being carried from surveillance photographs.
   It was the second Soviet submarine reported in distress near
Norway since April 7, when a Soviet MIKE class nuclear submarine
caught fire and sank in the Norwegian Sea, killing 42 Soviet seamen.
</TEXT>
