<FIRST>r a PM-Swastika-Stabbing     06-26 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swastika-Stabbing,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivor of Auschwitz Slain Over Swastika</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Auschwitz survivor was beaten and stabbed to
death after confronting a man he had accused of scrawling a swastika
on his door, police said.
   Max Kowalski, 72, was found dead Saturday in the second-floor
apartment of Ruben Martinez Zucarino, 36, who was charged with
second-degree murder, said police spokesman Sgt. Maurice Howard.
   An arraignment was scheduled for today.
   A popular man known as ``the mayor of Brighton Beach,'' Kowalski
spent his days in a rented room at the Brooklyn boarding house
tinkering with old televisions and radios and talking with friends
about his native Poland.
   ``This isn't the way God wanted it,'' said Philip Solsky, a
72-year-old neighbor.
   ``He was a friend in a Jewish neighborhood who should never have
died with a swastika or violently.''
   Kowalski, a Jew whose family perished at Auschwitz, came to the
United States in 1949 and worked as a carpenter. He survived the
Nazi death camp and his wife also is a Holocaust survivor.
   ``She figures that he survived everything else, and then for this
to happen,'' said Kowalski's 38-year-old son, Lenny.
   ``The guy might have stabbed him, but the war still killed him,''
the son said. ``It was the insignia that did it. If it hadn't been
there, this never would have happened.''
   The younger Kowalski said he was visiting with his father
Saturday morning in the workshop when he noticed the swastika and a
skull and crossbones scrawled in blue felt-tip pen on the door.
   His father quietly washed the marks from the door, the younger
Kowalski said.
   The son complained to the landlady, Tuey Chin, who said that when
she asked Zucarino about the graffiti he was holding a marker of the
same blue color in his hands. But he told her he knew nothing about
the drawings.
   A short time later, the elder Kowalski went to Zucarino's
apartment, where he confronted him about the swastika and grabbed
him by the throat, police said.
   A fight ensued. Zucarino stabbed Kowalski repeatedly with a
scissors and a fork and smashed a religious statue over his head,
killing him, police said.
   Ms. Chin said Zucarino may have attacked Kowalski with a
5-inch-high metal Statue of Liberty. She said he showed her the
statue after the attack.
   ``I'm not sure if he hit Max over the head later with the Statue
of Liberty or a religious statue,'' she said. ``But there was a
Statue of Liberty all right. Brass, bronze, whatever.''
</TEXT>
