<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Drugs     06-26 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Drugs,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief AIDS Researcher Calls for Expansion of AIDS Drug Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for AIDS patients hailed a
proposal by the chief of federal AIDS research to allow for greater
distribution of experimental drugs.
   Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the National Institute for Allergy
and Infectious Diseases, recommended the development of ``parallel
track'' testing under which patients would have access to promising
drugs as soon as they are proved safe, even while tests for
effectiveness were under way.
   ``It's a great step forward,'' said Dr. Mathilde Krim, a founder
of the American Foundation for AIDS Research. ``It represents a new
consensus on how to handle drug development for AIDS and
life-threatening diseases in general.''
   Martin Delaney, co-director of Project Inform, a group of AIDS
activists, said he planned to ask a committee of the National
Academy of Science today to endorse Fauci's idea.
   In a speech Friday, Fauci called for the ``compassionate
distribution'' of trial drugs to ineligible applicants.
   ``It's clear to me that we cannot just rely on the traditional
approach of clinical trials,'' Fauci said during a talk at the HIV
Treatment Awareness Week conference. HIV stands for human
immunodeficiency virus, which causes acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   Clinical trials are designed to test the effectiveness of drugs
that have been proved non-toxic. Test subjects must meet strict
requirements that typically exclude many applicants.
   ``We've got to rethink the rigidity with which we exclude
people,'' he said.
   Fauci said drug companies, the federal Food and Drug
Administration, and AIDS patients must consider the possibility of
parallel track testing.
   ``It's not something that any one person or organization has the
ability to make happen because you're involving the public and
private factions,'' he said. ``The critical thing is this can't
happen by fiat. It's a concept.''
   Fauci, a staunch advocate of clinical trials as the only means to
discover definitive scientific answers, emphasized the continued
need for rigorous studies.
   Part of the need for parallel tracking stems from the limited
availability of drugs to treat AIDS, Fauci said. Similarly, the drug
trial process is slow and limited and leaves out many patients who
are eager to try experimental drugs.
</TEXT>
