<FIRST>r a PM-SiameseTwins-People     06-26 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Siamese Twins-People,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conjoined Twins Celebrate Fifth Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of Siamese twins who just celebrated
their fifth birthday says there is no tragedy in her two girls being
joined together.
   Marlene Cady wrote in this week's People magazine that when a
stranger walks up to Verena and Ruthie and laments the youngsters'
fate, ``I always tell those people that the only tragedy is in their
interpretation of the girls' situation, because obviously Ruthie and
Verena are happy kids.''
   The girls, born April 13, 1984, are joined from the collarbone to
the waist and share a heart, liver and parts of the intestines.
   Sharing a heart makes the girls tire easily and they are more
susceptible to infection than most children.
   Mrs. Cady, whose family lives near Providence, R.I., said that
when the girls had pneumonia at age 9 months, she and her husband,
Peter, found themselves talking about their lives as ``now or after
the girls die.''
   ``But when we celebrated their first birthday, we realized that
we could wait for things to change until we were 105 years old, but
then we would have spent the time waiting instead of living,'' Mrs.
Cady wrote.
   She said the children have distinct personalities _ Ruthie is
stubborn while Verena likes to make sure she's doing the right thing.
   The girls have mastered feats that doctors thought impossible.
When they perfected riding a special tricycle, ``they rode up and
down the street for three days, knocking on doors and ringing bells
to make sure everyone knew about their new treasure.''
   The twins' older sister, Maria, had been upset at all the
attention the twins got but then realized they are special, their
mother said.
   ``Sometimes I feel sorry for my sisters being attached because
they don't always want to do the same thing. But when they aren't
arguing, I think they're very lucky to be together,'' Maria said.
   Conjoined twins occur about once in 100,000 births. About half
die within 48 hours of birth.
   Mrs. Cady said that when she thinks ``about how long they might
live, it's in terms of a couple of years. We live for the present.''
</TEXT>
