<FIRST>r a PM-SeabrookShutdown     06-26 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook Shutdown,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Spurned by Three Seabrook Officials on Shutdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal inspectors told three Seabrook
nuclear plant officials to shut down the reactor before the
directive was obeyed, according to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   But Noel Dudley, senior NRC inspector at the plant, denied that
agency officials had to grab anyone to get a response, as alleged by
a Seabrook critic.
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., said Friday NRC Chairman Lando Zech
and other commission officials told him an NRC inspector grabbed a
plant operator before Thursday's unplanned shutdown.
   The Boston Sunday Globe reported details of the shutdown based on
interviews with Dudley, plant officials and others. The shutdown, on
the 10th day of low-power tests at the $6 billion plant, prompted
the NRC to suspend further tests pending a review.
   Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon said he will ask an
NRC appeal board to stop the tests until safety issues for
full-power operation are reviewed.
   ``The NRC pointed to those same problems a year ago after a mock
evacuation exercise,'' Shannon said.
   Plant spokesmen said neither the plant nor the public was
endangered.
   But Markey said the results could have been much worse at higher
power.
   ``It's very frightening to think what would have happened if this
plant had been operating at 70 to 80 percent of full power and there
had been no NRC people in the control room,'' he said.
   Thursday's events, plant officials say, began when a
malfunctioning valve on the non-nuclear side of the operation
produced changes in readouts from a part called a pressurizer on the
nuclear side. The change was sufficient to warrant a shutdown,
spokesman Ron Sher said Sunday.
   One NRC inspector and then Dudley approached three plant
officials pointing out the problem, but got no immediate results,
the Globe said. Minutes later, an operator did shut down the plant.
   ``They were making a conscious decision to attempt to regain
pressure control'' even though plant procedures called for a
shutdown, Dudley said.
   An unidentified NRC inspector first approached Seabrook's startup
manager about the pressure reading, the Globe said.
   When the manager did not respond, the NRC inspector approached
the test director, who was closer to the scene in the control room,
and the director agreed the plant should be shut, the paper said.
   But according to the newspaper, the test director then talked to
the shift supervisor, a higher-ranking official, who said that
pressure problem was being corrected on its own and there was no
need to turn off the plant.
   Dudley stepped in at that point, approaching a still higher
Seabrook official, the assistant operators manager, said NRC
spokesman Steve Horwitz.
   The assistant manager consulted the operations manager, who
acknowledged the information and deferred to the decision of the
shift supervisor to continue to operate, Horwitz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
