<FIRST>r a PM-Helmsley     06-26 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection in Hotel Queen's Tax Evasion Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Prenoon EDT lead expected with jury selection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Potential jurors in the federal trial of
billionaire Leona Helmsley's tax evasion case must reveal their
income, what they think about rich people and whether they believe
the hotel queen is an ogre.
   Jury selection was to begin today in the trial of the 69-year-old
Mrs. Helmsley and two former aides.
   She and her husband, Harry, are accused of evading federal taxes
by billing personal luxuries, including a marble dance floor for
their mansion, as business expenses.
   Her 80-year-old husband has been found incompetent to stand trial
because of loss of memory.
   The Helmsleys head a $5 billion real estate and hotel empire,
mostly in the New York City area.
   In April 1988, the Helmsleys were indicted on charges they evaded
personal income taxes by disguising about $4 million in renovations
to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as a business expense.
   Mrs. Helmsley is portrayed in advertisements as the ``Queen of
the Helmsley Hotels.'' The ad campaign calls Manhattan's Helmsley
Palace ``the only palace in the world where the queen stands guard.''
   Joseph Brodsky, lawyer for Helmsley aide Frank Turco, planned to
hand potential jurors a questionnaire asking their incomes and
attitude toward the wealthy.
   He said he wants to know if the potential jurors are ``biased
against rich people ... or whether they've seen Mrs. Helmsley's ads
in the newspapers and they think she's an ogre.''
   Turco and Joseph V. Licari are charged with helping create bogus
invoices to make it appear that the costly renovations on the $8
million, 28-room mansion were tax-deductible improvements on
business properties.
   Among the renovations listed in the 47-count indictment were a
marble dance floor installed above a swimming pool; a breakfast
room; an indoor-outdoor stereo system; more than $370,000 in
landscaping; and an assortment of furniture and paintings.
   The indictment said a $45,000 silver clock in the shape of the
Helmsley Building _ a gift for Harry Helmsley _ was billed to and
paid by the Park Lane Hotel. Four jade art objects worth half a
million dollars were paid for by four hotels as furniture purchases,
the indictment said.
   Last fall, the Helmsleys' lawyer, Gerald Feffer, said the false
invoices were a device used by Turco and Licari ``to enable them to
steal blindly from the Helmsleys. That's crucial to our defense.''
   The case was going to court after a lengthy pretrial period
during which defense lawyers filed many motions to overturn the
indictment or to remove one or both of the Helmsleys from the case.
   The U.S. Supreme Court in April rejected a motion to dismiss the
indictment. The motion said prosecutors engaged in misconduct
because of grand jury leaks to the news media.
   Earlier this month, a federal judge found Helmsley unable to
assist in his defense because of memory lapses and reasoning
difficulties.
   The ruling did not dismiss the charges against Helmsley but
indefinitely delayed his trial.
   The judge noted that doctors believed Helmsley's mental
deterioration, cause by several mild strokes, would continue and
that it was unlikely he would be tried.
</TEXT>
