<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0654EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-26 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Nebraska, Tropical Storm in Gulf of Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms moved across Nebraska early today toward the
upper Mississippi Valley, while a tropical depression off the Gulf
Coast brought high tides and heavy rains to Texas and Louisiana.
   The Nebraska storms spawned tornadoes, which on Sunday night
destroyed or damaged several buildings and overturned cars in North
Platte.
   Tornadoes also were reported 20 miles south of North Platte and
15 miles west of Maywood. Three-quarter-inch hail fell at Taylor,
Neb., and winds blew down trees near Chambers, Neb., early today.
   The tropical depression brought tides 3 feet above normal along
the upper Texas and Louisiana coasts. Forecasters said rainfall
could reach more than 10 inches along the Texas coast, with lesser
amounts in Louisiana.
   Tropical-storm and flash-flood watches were in effect for the 470
miles from Baffin Bay, Texas, to Morgan City, La.
   Elsewhere, heavy rain fell in eastern South Dakota, with about an
inch in an hour at Huron.
   Thunderstorms weakened late Sunday across the eastern states, but
scattered showers continued in portions of the mid-Atlantic states
near the Chesapeake Bay. Earlier thunderstorms resulted in flooding
in Clearfield County in central Pennsylvania.
   In Iowa, showers dumped up to 3.4 inches of rain over the weekend.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
eastern half of Texas across the lower Mississippi Valley and the
Gulf Coast region into Florida, with a concentration of
thunderstorms across south-central and southeast Texas; showers and
thunderstorms, some locally severe, extending from the upper Great
Lakes across the upper Mississippi Valley to Nebraska and Kansas;
and widely scattered thunderstorms from Vermont and New York across
Pennsylvania and the middle Atlantic Coast states to the Carolinas.
   Predicted highs: in the 60s and 70s from the northern and central
high Plains across northern Minnesota to upper Michigan and along
the Pacific Coast; over 100 degrees in the desert Southwest and near
the Rio Grande River of Texas; and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming to 87 degrees at
Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 fair; Boston 66 fair; Buffalo 69 foggy;
Charleston, S.C., 70 fair; Cincinnati 70 hazy; Cleveland 69 fair;
Detroit 71 foggy; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New York 71 fair;
Philadelphia 71 hazy; Pittsburgh 72 foggy; Portland, Maine, 61 fair;
Washington 77 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 59 partly cloudy; Chicago 77 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 75 foggy; Denver 60 partly cloudy; Des Moines 72
partly cloudy; Indianapolis 77 hazy; Kansas City 76 fair;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 70 partly cloudy; Nashville 77 hazy; New
Orleans 75 cloudy; St. Louis 81 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 74 fair; Anchorage 61 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
80 fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake City 57
fair; San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 56 rain; Seattle 58 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 70 partly cloudy; Toronto 66 foggy.
