<FIRST>r a PM-SubmarineRaces     06-26 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Submarine Races,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Naval Academy Takes Overall Award in Sub Races</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swirling, murky water forced judges to
cancel the First International Submarine Races after giving the
overall performance award to Squid, the U.S. Naval Academy entry.
   The Navy's teardrop-shaped sub was awarded $5,000 in the
first-ever, human-powered submarine races, based on a combination of
speed, innovation and cost-effectiveness.
   ``We're having a used-sub sale tomorrow,'' said Navy Lt. Cmdr.
Pat Poole, champagne bottle in hand.
   Awards were presented after a second day of stormy weather forced
cancellation of a nine-sub race around a 1-kilometer loop course.
   The Subversion, the entry from California Polytechnic in San Luis
Obispo, won the speed award, beating the Navy's sub by eight seconds
in a 100-yard time trial Saturday.
   All the subs were ``wet'' designs that fill up with water and
require racers to wear scuba gear.
   Those propelling the subs said the biggest challenge was to
maintain a steady pace and not breathe too quickly, which can lead
to light-headedness or blackout.
</TEXT>
