<FIRST>r a PM-NavyDeath     06-26 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Death,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Sailor Dies in Navy Training Pool</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has ordered an investigation into
the death of a second sailor in little more than a year at a
training pool.
   Michael J. Fedie, a 22-year-old flight officer candidate from
Altoona, Wis., died Friday after a drill at the Pensacola Naval Air
Station in which he jumped off a tower and swam a short distance
under water, the Navy said.
   ``He had completed an abandon-ship drill and was walking out of
the pool when he collapsed,'' said Chief Warrant Officer Robert
Tyler.
   A preliminary autopsy indicated Fedie died from acute cerebral
edema, said Kay Esty, a Navy spokeswoman. Edema is an abnormal
accumulation of fluid; its causes include a blow to the head, a
tumor and deprivation of oxygen.
   Final autopsy results will not be available for several weeks,
she said.
   Chief Warrant Officer Robert Tyler said an investigation has been
ordered.
   ``He was one of the best physical specimens you've ever seen,''
said Chris Jones, a high school friend. ``He called last Sunday to
say that the class had started out with 65 guys and over half quit.
But Mike never would have quit. Being a pilot is just something he
always wanted to do.''
   Fedie's father, Felix, said his son was an excellent swimmer.
   Fedie's death comes 16 months after Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki,
19, of Appleton, Wis., drowned at the naval station during a rescue
swimming drill.
   A officer was found guilty of negligent homicide at a
court-martial for holding Mirecki's head under water.
   Five officers were disciplined, the commander of the Naval
Aviation Schools Command was reprimanded and four other supervisors
were given warning letters.
   Mirecki's death prompted changes in procedures at the Navy Rescue
Swimmer School, including a ban on instructors touching students.
</TEXT>
