<DOCNO> AP890626-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Dissidents     06-26 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dissidents,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Leader, Two Intellectuals Reported to Have Fled China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``underground railroad'' to help dissidents
flee China has brought a key student leader and two prominent
intellectuals to safety, sources said today.
   Wu'er Kaixi, 21, the Beijing Normal University student who was at
the forefront of the crushed pro-democracy movement in China, fled
safely even though Communist authorities issued a bulletin for his
arrest, a local student activist said.
   The activist, who spoke on condition of anonymity, refused to
divulge details of Wu'er's reported escape, saying he did not want
to jeopardize future efforts to bring dissidents from China.
   A diplomatic source said he believed Wu'er Kaixi had fled the
country. ``If I had $100 I'd put it down'' on the student's
succesful escape, he said, adding that it was not ``100 percent''
certain.
   Wu'er is on the wanted list of 21 students sought by Communist
Chinese authorities for leading pro-democracy protests, which the
government has labeled a ``counterrevolutionary rebellion.''
   Wu'er, a member of China's Turkish minority, is from northwest
Xinjiang province. His compelling speeches and a television
appearance with Premier Li Peng during the movement made him famous
throughout China.
   In the television appearance, Wu'er interrupted the premier
several times, told him to ``stop beating around the bush'' and
respond to student demands for sweeping political change.
   Two other dissidents, intellectuals Yan Jiaqi and Wan Runnan,
were smuggled to the West through Hong Kong by the underground
railroad, the diplomatic source said. They are among seven
intellectuals on another wanted list issued by Chinese authorities
as part of the crackdown on the pro-democracy movement.
   Yan Jiaqi is reported to be in France after fleeing to Hong Kong
last week. Wan Runnan also came through Hong Kong and eventually
will travel to the United States, the diplomatic source said.
   Yan was a leader of the Beijing Independent Intellectuals
Association, which played an important role in the movement for
freedom and was banned by the Chinese government when martial law
was declared May 20.
   Wan, general manager of China's first private high-technology
company, the Stone Corp., had called for a meeting of the national
congress to discuss the demands put forth by students who were
demonstrating for a freer and less corrupt society.
   ``During the student movement, Stone and the students kept close
relations,'' the independent Ming Pao newspaper in Hong Kong
reported.
   The diplomatic source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
``a lot of dissidents (and) opposition people have gone out''
through the underground railroad operated by students and other
activists in this territory on the southeastern coast of China.
   He said he did not know how many people have fled China through
Hong Kong and refused to give details about how they were smuggled
out of the country.
   Since June 3-4, when the Chinese army moved into Beijing to crush
the protest movement, China has arrested at least 1,800 people and
27 people have been executed.
   Many student leaders and dissidents fled underground to avoid
detention.
   The Asia Television network in Hong Kong on Sunday broadcast what
it said was a statement made by Yan Jiaqi in which he leveled a
withering attack at China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping, Premier Li
Peng and President Yang Shangkun, who were behind the crackdown.
   ``China's political situation today is in the midst of a white
terror,'' according to a copy of the statement made available by the
network. He accused the three leaders of ``using the inhuman
policies of fascism to take all of those who support democracy, the
real Chinese people, and wipe out the whole lot.''
</TEXT>
