<DOCNO> AP890626-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SharewareProphet 1stLd-Writethru a0433 06-26 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shareware Prophet, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0433,0821</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Making a Living, Not a Killing' _ PC-Write's Bob Wallace</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to RESTORE full name of software; PICKS UP
3rd graf pvs, ``I encourage ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's an unwritten law of American business: You
can't sell computer software on the honor system and expect to be a
success.
   Unless you're Bob Wallace, president, owner and ex-chief
programmer of Seattle-based Quicksoft, publisher of PC-Write, the
acclaimed ``shareware'' word-processor for personal computers. Then
you break the unwritten law.
   ``I encourage people to copy the software and then encourage them
to pay for it after using it. It's like public television,'' the
40-year-old Wallace said last week.
   Users who pay and register get extra benefits: the printed
manual, telephone support, Quicksoft's newsletter and updates of the
program.
   ``But then there are intangible benefits: You're doing the right
thing, you're helping us out, keeping us in business,'' he said. And
that leads to newer and better versions of PC-Write.
   ``I don't worry about the people who don't register. I worry
about the people who do register,'' he said. ``I want to make sure
they're happy. ...
   ``If they're happy and we're making a reasonable profit, that's
good.''
   It's good enough for Quicksoft, with about 30 employees, to
expand its product base, too. On Tuesday, the company announced its
new file-search and ``hypertext'' information-linking utility
scheduled for late-summer shipping.
   Quicksoft also has published its first catalog of third-party
software it selects and supports for use with PC-Write.
   Wallace, whose catch-phrase is ``making a living, not a
killing,'' chose his profession at age 11. ``I read a Reader's
Digest article, `The Man Who Talked to Machines,''' he said. ``I was
one of the people that just knew, then, I would be a programmer.''
   He found computers to work on with an Explorer Scout troop
sponsored by Control Data Corp. in Bethesda, Md., then at the
University of Maryland, Brown University, and the University of
Washington.
   ``I got kind of discouraged because computers were so expensive.
I couldn't own one and I really wanted to own one, so I kind of got
distracted and went off. I was living on an island in Puget Sound
for a while,'' he said.
   The first personal computers appeared about the time he founded
the Northwest Computer Club in 1976. He went to work for The Retail
Computer Store in Seattle.
   In 1978, he was the 10th employee hired by Microsoft Corp., the
software company that created the IBM-standard personal computer
operating systems.
   ``Sometime in '82, I found myself thinking, `Gee, Microsoft is
getting huge and I'm kind of getting lost here,''' he said.
Microsoft had 300 employees then; it now has about 3,800 worldwide.
   He started writing a program for word processing.
   ``I thought I could do something people would really like and
really felt right, but I didn't know if I could explain that. I
couldn't really run an ad saying, `Buy my word processor: It feels
good.''
   He could, however, share his word processor using the electronic
bulletin boards of computer hobbyists. That eliminated distribution
and advertising expenses.
   The first version, 1.0, was introduced in August 1983, with 150
copies sent to the press and 150 to bulletin boards. A PC Magazine
reviewer suggested changes. Wallace made them. By February 1984,
Wallace had written version 1.3 and the reviewer liked it.
   ``That review pretty much started us out. It generated enough
interest and revenue so that I could hire our first employee, uh,
who I later married.''
   Megan Dana Wallace, an artist, draws Quicksoft's trademark
``office cat'' on the company's literature.
   PC-Write typically is rated as good as or better than other
full-featured word processors costing five times more than its $89
registration fee.
   It's anybody's guess how many copies of PC-Write are out there.
Wallace says the best estimates come from magazine surveys, which
typically estimate that 6 percent of their readers use PC-Write.
   ``I discount that down to maybe 4 percent, and that's somewhere
between half a million and 1 million users. And that's real
exciting,'' he said.
   ``Working from the other end, we know we have paid users of about
125,000, of which 45,000 are full, registered users and the other
80,000 are on group licenses _ corporations and universities,'' he
said.
   He expects revenues this year to be between $2 million and $3
million. Sales declined to $1.7 million last year from $2 million in
1987. He blames the slump on himself, for putting off the decision
to step down as chief programmer to take up exclusively the
presidency of Quicksoft.
   A final thought from Bob Wallace:
   ``Our business is based on people being honest and people are.
That's why we're successful.''
</TEXT>
