<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary     06-26 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Reformer Says He's Nominated For Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reformer Imre Pozsgay said the communist
party's Central Committee has decided to nominate him to be
Hungary's president, a government newspaper reported today.
   Pozgary, a Politburo member, was one of three well-known
reformers promoted on Saturday to a newly created four-man presidium
of the party.
   The Central Committee named economic reformer Redzoe Nyers party
chairman. It said he, Pozgary and Premier Miklos Nemeth will run the
party along with Karoly Grosz, the party's general secretary.
   The creation of the presidium seriously undercuts the power of
Grosz, a centrist who has come under heavy criticism by reformers.
   The presidium is to lead the party on a provisional basis until a
crucial party congress set for Oct. 7, when communists will choose
who will lead the party as Hungary prepares for its first free and
competitive elections next year.
   The choice of a leader at the congress is considered crucial to
the party's attempts to hold power when the elections are held.
   The reformers believe that only their more democratic policies
can give the party hope of emerging as the strongest force in next
year's elections.
   Pozsgay said the Central Committee nominated him for the new top
state post pending approval of Parliament, the daily Magyar Hirlap
reported.
   The newspaper printed a transcript of an hourlong television talk
show with the four presidium members on state television Sunday
night.
   ``I have been greatly honored at the session when they agreed
that when the office of president of the republic is created by
Parliament I'll be the nominee,'' Pozsgay said.
   Pozsgay previously had been named a likely candidate to replace
the current largely ceremonial post of ``president of the
presidential council'' held by Bruno F. Straub.
   Parliament is scheduled to go into session on Tuesday, but its
agenda was not made public. It was not known whether the issue would
be discussed.
   Knowledgeable sources said the new office will be created in
1990, when legislative elections are due to be held.
   Under constitutional changes being considered, the office of
state president would be vested with much greater powers than the
present figurehead role.
</TEXT>
