<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-26 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Leader Goes on Trial, Supporters Battle Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading dissident accused of making
an illegal trip to Communist North Korea went on trial today, and
supporters chanted anti-government slogans and battled with police.
   About 500 radical students brandishing metal pipes, clubs and
rocks hurled hundreds of firebombs at riot police as the Rev. Moon
Ik-hwan went on trial for making a trip to North Korea to discuss
unifying the nations.
   ``Release unification fighter Moon Ik-hwan!'' students yelled,
``Down with (President) Roh Tae-woo!''
   Several hundred police with shields defended themselves by
swinging captured metal pipes. Some students and police were
injured, but numbers were unavailable on arrests or injuries.
   Students from at least four colleges took part in the clash,
which occurred on a city street in front of Seoul's Sogang
University.
   About 1,500 police guarded the courthouse where Moon's trial
opened.
   Police arrested 13 radical students, chanting anti-government
slogans, who seized the rooftop of a nearby six-story building and
erected a large banner saying ``immediately release patriotic
unification fighter Moon.''
   Moon was brought to the courthouse in prison garb under heavy
security. His hands were tied with rope, but he smiled and waved at
supporters.
   The trial opening was delayed when about 200 Moon supporters
mounted a sit-in outside the courtroom demanding they be allowed to
use courtroom seats occupied by 50 police officers.
   No arrests were reported. The judge asked some officers to leave
so that more Moon supporters could be seated.
   Moon is charged with violation of the National Security Law for
his nine-day trip to the north in March. He talked to North Korean
leader Kim Il Sung about national unification, a popular issue with
student protesters in the capitalist south.
   South Korea's anti-communist government forbids unsanctioned
trips to North Korea, its bitter enemy, and maintains that dialogue
on unification must be carried out through government channels. If
convicted, Moon could face the death penalty, although that is not
considered likely.
   Also today, arrest warrants were issued for three radical
students the government says have encouraged people to participate
in the World Youth Festival, which is to be held in North Korea July
1-8. The government has banned participation.
   The students have been charged with violation of national
security laws, prosecutors said.
   Moon, 71, and his traveling companion Yoo Won-ho, a 59-year-old
businessman, were arrested April 13 when they returned to Seoul
after stops in Beijing and Tokyo. They have been in jail since then.
   Defense lawyers argued that the prosecution should drop charges
against Moon and Yoo on grounds the indictment is unconstitutional.
Repeating his earlier statements, Moon told the court that he
visited the north to seek reunification.
   The Korean peninsula was divided after World War II. In 1950, the
north invaded the south and started the three-year Korean War.
</TEXT>
