<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels 2ndLd-Writethru a0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Rebels, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0504,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Slaughter Anti-communist Villagers at Church, 39 Reported
Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead to reflect that rebels attacked villagers; picks
up 2nd pvs: ``Two of ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels attacked anti-Marxist
villagers at a church in a remote village and killed at least 39
people, including women and children, officials said today.
   Two of the dead _ a Protestant lay leader and his brother _ were
beheaded during the incident, which occurred Sunday at a United
Church of Christ chapel in Rano, on Mindanao island about 640 miles
southeast of Manila.
   At least eight people were wounded, officials said. The military
said the death toll could be higher because the rebels carted away
their casualties. A survivor claimed two rebels were killed.
   A church official in Manila said the 39 confirmed dead were
congregation members.
   Lt. Col. Jose Maneja, deputy commander of Davao del Sur province,
said about 100 New People's Army guerrillas entered the village
looking for the leader of a group of local anti-communist vigilantes.
   Maneja said details were unclear, but apparently someone
indicated that vigilante leader Ruben Ayap was inside the church and
shooting broke out. Ayap was killed along with his two brothers,
Abadi and Clemente.
   Abadi Ayap, head of the laymen's group at the church, and his
brother Clemente were beheaded, the military said.
   Regina Dominguez, 41, whose daughter was killed in the shooting,
said the rebels were angry because villagers had formed an
anti-communist group.
   ``They took revenge,'' Mrs. Dominguez said by telephone from
nearby Digos. ``They just fired.''
   Mrs. Dominguez said she was not in the village when the shooting
began but heard from survivors that villagers hacked to death at
least one guerrilla with long ``bolo'' knives.
   Lt. Col. Cresencio Maralit, spokesman for the Philippine
Constabulary in Manila, said the villagers had made the rebels angry
by refusing to pay ``revolutionary taxes.''
   Arnold Endar, 22, a vigilante who survived the attack, told
reporters he and about 70 others were crowded into the bamboo-walled
church when the rebels opened fire with M-16 rifles and two machine
guns.
   He said vigilante members ran from the church to get their
weapons and killed at least two guerrillas.
   ``I was hit when I ran out of the church to get my bolo,'' said
Endar, who was wounded in the leg. ``I saw many people dead, and I
pretended to be dead. As I ran from the church, I stepped on many
bodies.''
   Endar said he rode by horseback for two hours to alert a military
garrison. He said 20 members of his vigilants group and 12 children
were among the dead, including a one-year-old.
   In Manila, Samuel Briones, human rights coordinator for the
United Church of Christ, said the battle broke out after Sunday
school as the congregation was preparing for services.
   He said it was unusual for rebels to attack his denomination's
churches.
   The United Church of Christ has been widely criticized by the
military for alleged links with communist rebels because of the
denomination's outspoken stand on human rights.
   Sunday's incident occurred in an area of southeastern Mindanao
where the military has organized armed anti-communist vigilante
groups to counter rebels in remote areas.
   Various church organizations have accused the vigilantes of
widespread human rights abuses.
   The New People's Army has been waging a 20-year insurgency to
establish a communist state in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
