<FIRST>r i PM-Japan     06-26 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Geisha Allegations, Election Loss Troubling New Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno promised political
reforms to win back public trust today after his beleaguered party
was badly beaten in an election seen as a barometer of voter
sentiment.
   On Sunday, Socialist Party candidate Kinuko Ofuchi won a
by-election in northern Japan for a seat in parliament's upper
house, defeating a candidate from the governing Liberal Democratic
Party.
   A Socialist previously held the seat, but Uno told reporters
today, ``I never expected that we would lose so badly'' in the
traditionally conservative district of Niigata.
   Uno acknowledged a new 3 percent sales tax, a huge stock scandal
and farm issues contributed to his Liberal Democratic Party's defeat.
   But he again refused to comment on the governing party's latest
scandal: allegations that he paid a geisha to be his mistress for
four months in 1985.
   ``I have respected political ethics for 30 years and I have not
done anything unethical,'' he told a news conference.
   But he added: ``I think it is regrettable that I caused trouble.''
   A weekly magazine had reported the geisha link, without naming
the woman.
   After the polls closed Sunday night, a 40-year-old woman appeared
in a national television interview, saying she was the former geisha
and that Uno had paid more than $21,430 to her and her geisha house.
   Mitsuko Nakanishi's allegations have sullied the reputation that
led to Uno's selection as prime minister just a month ago. His
predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, resigned to take responsibility for a
scandal in which the giant information and publishing conglomerate,
Recruit Co., is accused of trying to influence government policy
with excessive donations and sales of bargain-priced, unlisted stock
to public officials.
   Support for Uno's new Cabinet was at only 16.7 percent in a
telephone survey of 10,000 people conducted June 16-19, the Nihon
Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading financial newspaper, reported today.
   Although this was an improvement from the 13.1 percent rating for
Takeshita's Cabinet in March, 52.8 percent of those questioned in
the latest poll said they do not support Uno's government, Nikkei
said. The remaining 30.5 percent did not respond.
   Both polls and by-elections are being watched closely ahead of
next month's elections for parliament's upper house, where Uno's
party holds 143 of 251 seats.
   Ms. Ofuchi, Sunday's election winner, campaigned against the
sales tax that took effect April 1 along with income tax cuts,
criticized Uno's party fpr the scandal, and apparently won favor
with rural voters displeased with a greater opening of Japan's farm
market to imports.
   With 99.6 percent of the vote counted, Ms. Ofuchi had 559,603
votes to 482,245 votes for Hideo Kimi of Uno's party and 47,064 for
Kazuo Murata of the Japan Communist Party.
   ``We intend to listen attentively to the people's voices,'' Uno
said today.
   He said his party will work to restore public confidence by
promoting political reforms.
   ``I understand that following the Watergate scandal, the United
States made various political reforms, including election reform and
other tougher regulations to prevent recurrences of the same
wrongdoings,'' Uno said.
</TEXT>
