stable condition after undergoing three hours of blood dialysis.
   Dr. Magdi Yacoub, who performed triple bypass heart surgery on
the premier September 30, flew in from London on Sunday with a team
of heart specialists for a two-hour visit, to examine Papandreou.
   A hospital announcement said British and Greek doctors agreed on
the necessary treatment and that Papandreou's heart was in steady
condition while his kidney problem was being dealt with.
   Papandreou is heading a caretaker government because no party
received a majority in elections on June 18 to the 300-seat
Parliament.
   The two-term premier, whose socialist Panhellenic Socialist
Movement was defeated in the elections, faces a Tuesday deadline to
form a new government. He received the mandate Friday from President
Christos Sartzetakis after conservatives, who finished first in the
balloting, were unable to forge a coalition.
   Papandreou planned to meet with leaders of a communist-dominated
alliance to build a coalition.
   The communist-dominated alliance, the Coalition of the Left and
Progress, is next in line to attempt to form a government when
Papandreou's mandate expires.
   New elections will be held if that party can't form a coalition.
