<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     06-26 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Strike Brings Island Life to Standstill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded, traffic halted
and shops closed today during a nationwide strike called by
Sinhalese extremists in support of 40,000 striking bus drivers.
   Two bombs exploded in the Colombo suburb of Mount Lavinia and
another was detonated in the suburb of Narahenpitiya, said a senior
police official, who cannot be identified under briefing rules. The
blasts caused no casualties or damage and appeared intended to
frighten people into staying home, the officer said.
   The People's Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group,
called the daylong strike and ordered people to stay inside their
homes as a show of support for bus drivers who have been striking
since June 12 for higher wages.
   ``We warn anti-national elements they will be shot or fall victim
to explosive devices if they fail to heed our warning,'' said
handwritten posters plastered throughout the capital and signed by
Keerthi Wijebahu, commander of the front.
   The government ordered the bus drivers to either report for work
on Monday or lose their jobs. But the ultimatium was ignored and
soldiers were driving the government-owned buses.
   A few private vehicles plied the roads, bearing white flags
indicating they were attending a funeral or on an urgent errand.
   Downtown Colombo, which is usually bustling by 9 a.m., was
virtually deserted except for a few police officers. Businesses,
banks and markets all closed their shutters.
   ``I cannot find a shop to even buy a cigarette,'' said one
policeman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Sinhalese extremists oppose an Indian-brokered peace accord
aimed at ending the 6-year-old conflict with the Tamils. It contends
the accord grants too many concessions to the Tamils, who make up 18
percent of the island's 18 million people.
   Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population and control the
government and military.
   Since the accord was signed in July 1987, Sinhalese extremists
have been blamed for killing more than 3,500 people. Most of the
victims have been government officials and security personnel.
</TEXT>
