<FIRST>r i PM-BoyPilot     06-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Pilot,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young American Pilot Arrives in Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old Californian flying a single-engine
plane around the world arrived in Moscow today after collecting
signatures of nearly 1,000 Soviet children to present to President
Bush.
   Tony Aliengena landed his blue-and-white Cessna 210 at
Sheremetevo airport after a two-hour flight from Leningrad, the
first Soviet stop on his attempt to become the youngest person to
pilot a plane around the globe.
   A contingent of Young Pioneers, a Communist youth group, welcomed
him with the traditional Russian offering of bread and salt.
   ``It wasn't a difficult flight,'' he said. ``It's just like
flying anywhere.''
   The youth, who has about 1,000 hours of flying time, is to spend
five days touring Moscow. Among stops will be Red Square, where West
German teen-ager Mathias Rust gained worldwide fame by landing a
single-engine Cessna in May 1987 after evading Soviet air defenses.
   The young pilot brought a friendship scroll signed by 250,000
American children that he hopes to present to President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   However, it is not certain the Soviet leader will have time to
meet the boy before he takes off Friday on a hopscotch journey
across the Soviet Union and then on to Alaska.
   ``I am not sure if I will get to meet him, but I sure want to,''
siad the youngster.
   Bush already has agreed to meet him at the end of his planned
47-day journey, to accept a friendship scroll signed by Soviet
youth. On Sunday night, the scroll was signed by 987 children in
downtown Leningrad, where the pilot touched down Friday and spent
the weekend.
   The American, from San Juan Capistrano, began his flight on June
5 from California. It should take him 19,000 miles around the world
in short hops averaging three hours each.
   In the Soviet Union, he is accompanied by a Soviet navigator
because air controllers on many domestic routes do not speak
English, as required on international routes.
</TEXT>
