<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Politics     06-26 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Calls For Brezhnev Award to be Revoked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legislator today suggested the nation withdraw
its highest military order from former Soviet leader Leonid
Brezhnev, who was given the honor 33 years after the end of World
War II, Tass news agency reported.
   Brezhnev, who rose to major general serving as a political
officer in the war, was given the jewel-encrusted Order of Victory
in 1978, the official agency said. He died in 1982.
   Supreme Soviet deputy Albert Likhachev said many people see the
decoration as one of Brezhnev's undeserved rewards. Tass noted,
however, that the legislature has no power to revoke the award.
   Such a move would further discredit Brezhnev, who now is
condemned widely for plunging the economy into a crisis and
stagnating the rest of Soviet society. His name has been stripped
off cities and ships, and his relatives have lost some benefits
given to family members of a Soviet leader.
   The Supreme Soviet, the nation's first full-time lawmaking body,
convened today to confirm Cabinet members and organize writing bills
and ratifying treaties, Tass said.
   These are new powers for the legislature, a division of the
larger Congress of People's Deputies that began work May 25. In
closed hearings last week, legislative committees rejected at least
four of more than 60 nominees to ministerial and other senior posts.
The fight now moves to the full 542-member body.
   One chamber, the Council of Nationalities, decided today that
committees in both houses should consider bills before publication
in the press, Tass reported.
   Several deputies objected to the large number of military and
defense industry representatives on a committee to oversee defense
and the dreaded KGB secret police. But they were told experts were
assigned deliberately to committees in their area of professional
expertise, Tass said.
   Izvestia, the government daily, reported today that the
committee's hearings will be behind closed doors despite calls for
more openness in those areas.
   The chamber approved the composition of its committees after
changes, Tass said without elaborating.
   The legislature also is to consider bills on raising pensions and
the rights of deputies, and to set priorities for tackling the
nation's economic and social problems, Tass said.
   The Soviet of Nationalities elected Ukrainian poet Boris Oleinik,
a reformer from Kiev, as one of its deputy chairmen, and the Soviet
of Unions elected Moldavian Alexander Mokanu to a similar job.
   Monday's separate sessions of the two chambers, originally to be
televised nationally, did not appear on the air or in the broadcast
schedule. A spokeswoman at the state Gostelradio said officials
decided there was no need to televise the session.
</TEXT>
