<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Miranda     06-26 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Miranda,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Police Can Stray From Warning Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today gave police permission
to stray from the precise wording of the famous Miranda warnings
given to criminal suspects.
   The decision, reached by a 5-4 vote, reinstated an Indiana man's
conviction and 35-year prison sentence for attempted murder.
   The warning, familiar to every fan of television police shows,
was created by the high court in a 1966 decision called Miranda vs.
Arizona. It was designed to bolster criminal suspects' Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination.
   Under the court ruling, police must warn suspects in custody of
their right to remain silent, that anything they say can be used
against them and that they have a right to a lawyer's help before
answering any questions.
   Suspects also must be told that a lawyer will be provided to them
if they cannot afford to hire one and that the warnings must be
given before any police interrogation begins.
   In the case decided today, Hammond, Ind., police questioned Gary
Eagan in 1982 about an attempted murder after reading him a warning
that included this paragraph:
   ``You have a right to the advice and presence of a lawyer even if
you cannot afford one. We have no way of giving you a lawyer but one
will be appointed for you, if you wish, if and when you go to
court.''
   Eagan subsequently confessed to the crime, and did so again 29
hours later after being read a Miranda warning that did not include
the ``if and when'' language.
   Like some other states, Indiana does not provide pennyless
criminal suspects with free lawyers until their first appearance in
court. The Miranda right to a lawyer's help is accommodated by
police not initiating any contact with a suspect who has asked for
legal help.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in Eagan's case that
the ``if and when'' language of the warning Hammond police gave him
was confusing. The wording could lead someone to think he properly
may be questioned by police without a lawyer, the appeals court said.
   Other federal appeals courts have allowed warnings containing
such wording.
   Today, the justices said the 7th Circuit court was wrong.
   ``In our view, the court of appeals misapprehended the effect of
the inclusion of the `if and when you go to court' language in
Miranda warnings,'' Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote.
   ``This instruction accurately described the procedure for the
appointment of counsel in Indiana,'' he said.
   The court also ruled that the 1966 Miranda decision does not
require that lawyers be provided as soon as they are requested _
only that police halt their questioning.
   Justices Byron R. White, Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and
Anthony M. Kennedy joined Rehnquist in the majority.
   Justices Thurgood Marshall, William J. Brennan, John Paul Stevens
and Harry A. Blackmun dissented.
   In a 1981 decision, the court said ``talismanic incantations'' of
a defendant's rights are not required so long as the right to a
lawyer's help is not linked to ``a future point in time after the
police interrogation.''
   Both Indiana prosecutors and Eagan cited the 1981 ruling as
favorable to their side.
   Eagan telephoned Chicago police on May 16, 1982 and told them he
had found a dead, naked woman along the Lake Michigan shore in
Indiana.
   When he led police to her, the still-alive woman looked at Eagan
and exclaimed, ``Why did you stab me?''
   The woman later testified that Eagan and two other men had taken
her to the Indiana beach from Chicago and that she had sex with the
two other men. When she refused Eagan, she said, he stabbed her.
   Chicago police turned the case over to Hammond police.
   The case is Duckworth vs. Eagan, 88-317.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0072 </DOCNO>
