<FIRST>u i PM-Afghan-Prisoners     06-26 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan-Prisoners,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Say Soviets Agree To Exchange Prisoners En Masse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghan government will free rebel
prisoners in exchange for Soviet soldiers captured by guerrillas
during the 10-year-old war, rebel sources said today.
   Soviet diplomats, however, said final approval of the prisoner
swap must come from the Soviet-backed government in Kabul.
   An exchange agreement was reached at a fourth round of talks
today between Moslem guerrilla representatives and the Soviet
Embassy in Islamabad, a guerrilla spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   He said both sides will exchange lists of prisoners at talks to
be held within the next week.
   He said the Soviets endorsed the principle of exchanging
prisoners at one time, en masse, as previously demanded by the
insurgents.
   A Soviet Embassy statement, however, said Moscow will open talks
with Kabul on the proposed exchange.
   ``If the Russians agreed then Kabul will also,'' the guerrilla
spokesman said.
   The guerrillas claim 40,000 of their people are missing in action.
   They say they are holding between 50 and 75 Soviet soldiers
inside Afghanistan. Moscow says 311 of its troops have gone missing
since its sent troops to bolster the Kabul government's fight
against the anti-communist guerrillas nine years ago. The last Red
Army troops withdrew in February under a U.N.-brokered agreement.
   This latest round of prisoner negotiations comes while an
eight-member Soviet delegation is visiting Pakistan, including three
mothers and a father of Red Army soldiers missing in Afghanistan.
They insist their group is unofficial.
   Delegation spokesman Iona Andronov said that over the past two
days, ``We spoke with the proper people in Moscow and Kabul'' and
received assurances that ``we can arrange for this exchange.''
   The Soviet parents sought information about their children during
a meeting last week with guerrilla leaders in Pakistan's frontier
city, Peshawar.
   Andronov said the delegation promised to reciprocate with
information about missing Afghan guerrillas.
</TEXT>
