<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Yonkers     06-26 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Yonkers,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Appeal in Yonkers Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected arguments by
citizen groups in Yonkers, N.Y., that a federal judge illegally
ordered construction of 1,000 low-cost homes to help desegregate the
city.
   The justices, without comment, threw out an appeal by Save
Yonkers Federation Inc. and others. It contended that U.S. District
Judge Leonard B. Sand exceeded his authority in ordering the
desegregation plan.
   The Yonkers case attracted national attention a year ago when
four Yonkers councilmen refused to obey Sand's orders to adopt the
plan and were fined $3,500 each for contempt of court.
   Faced with massive layoffs of city workers, the city council
reversed itself on Sept. 10, 1988, by voting to comply with the
judge's order to build the low-cost homes.
   The Supreme Court last March agreed to decide whether Sand had
the power to fine the councilmen. A ruling in that case is expected
sometime in 1990.
   But the high court previously left intact Sand's 1985 ruling that
Yonkers officials intentionally and unlawfully promoted racial
segregation through their housing and school policies.
   The suit against the officials was begun by the federal
government in the waning days of President Jimmy Carter's
administration in 1980.
   In the case acted on today, the citizens groups said Sand's order
to build the homes in middle-class areas would leave untouched
racial segregation in the city's predominantly black Hispanic area.
   The case is Save Yonkers Federation vs. Sand, 88-1767.
</TEXT>
