<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-RICO     06-26 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-RICO,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Eases Use of Racketeering Law in Civil Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, broadly interpreting a key
federal anti-racketeering law, made it easier today to use the law
in civil lawsuits against businesses accused of fraud.
   The court said unanimously that the law applies to more than what
is traditionally described as organized crime.
   Also, Justice William J. Brennan said for the court that to prove
a pattern of racketeering activity under the law, a private
plaintiff or a prosecutor must show at least two criminal acts
``within a single scheme that were related and that amounted to, or
threatened the likelihood of, continued criminal activity.''
   Brennan rejected arguments that a plaintiff or prosecutor must
prove ``separate illegal schemes'' to demonstrate a pattern of
racketeering activity.
   Moreover, he continued, the law is designed to apply to more than
traditional organized crime.
   ``The occasion for Congress' action was the perceived need to
combat organized crime,'' Brennan said. ``But Congress for cogent
reasons chose to enact a more general statute, one which, although
it had organized crime as its focus, was not limited in application
to organized crime.''
   The court unanimously reinstated a lawsuit against Northwestern
Bell Telephone Co. by Minnesota consumers. The suit was based on
alleged violations of the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act, or RICO.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals dismissed the suit, which
accused Northwestern Bell of bribing state public utility officials.
   The consumers say the phone company in 1980 began trying
illegally to win rate increases by offering gifts, employment and
other favors to members of the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission.
   The appeals court ruled that the phone company's customers failed
to prove ``a pattern of racketeering activity'' required to make a
case under RICO.
   The 8th Circuit court said a single fraudulent scheme is
insufficient, ruling that at least two schemes must be alleged.
   Other federal appeals courts have allowed civil RICO suits based
on numerous acts advancing only one fraudulent scheme.
   It is not unusual nowadays to find at least one RICO claim in
lawsuits involving virtually any business dispute. The stigma
attached to being linked in public court documents to alleged
racketeering can be powerful leverage for out-of-court settlements.
   Winners of RICO lawsuits may collect triple damages and lawyer
fees, both of which generally are not available under state
anti-fraud laws.
   Justice Department lawyers, in a friend-of-the-court brief
submitted last year, sided with the phone customers in urging the
justices to interpret the RICO law broadly and reinstate the lawsuit.
   Also backing the customers were 14 states _ Arizona, California,
Connecticut, Idaho, Michigan, New Jersey, New Mexico, North
Carolina, Oregon, Texas, Washington, West Virginia, Wisconsin and
Wyoming.
   Other interests urged the high court to bar the lawsuit. For
example, the AFL-CIO said in a friend-of-the-court brief that
``private civil RICO actions have become a tool of harassment ...
against legitimate businesses and labor organizations.''
   During an oral argument session before the justices last
November, a lawyer for Northwestern Bell said the 1970 law is aimed
at thwarting organized crime, and should not be used against
otherwise legitimate businesses accused of fraud.
   But the lawyer representing the company's customers said
businesses that engage in fraudulent acts ``forfeit the right to
call themselves legitimate.''
   The case is H.J. Inc. vs. Northwestern Bell, 87-1252.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0075 </DOCNO>
