<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Italian-Americans     06-26 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Italian-Americans,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeals Saying Italian-Americans Unlawfully Barred
as Jurors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected appeals by
three convicted drug dealers who said Italian-Americans unlawfully
were barred from serving as jurors at their trial.
   The court, without comment, left intact the case of the three men
convicted in connection with the shipment of cocaine from Florida to
New Jersey.
   The three are Giacomo DiNorscio and Gerald Cohen, each sentenced
to 30 years in prison, and Anthony Truglia, sentenced to 10 years.
   At their 1986 trial in Newark, N.J., federal prosecutors used
what are known as peremptory _ or automatic _ challenges to exclude
five potential jurors with Italian surnames.
   The defendants said elimination of those potential jurors
violated a 1986 Supreme Court ruling that said prosecutors never may
disqualify potential jurors based on their race.
   The 1986 case involved exclusion of black potential jurors, and
the justices said prosecutors must explain their reasons for
peremptory challenges if there is evidence the exclusions are
racially motivated.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last December ruled against
the defendants in the New Jersey case.
   The appeals court said they failed to show that ``persons with
Italian surnames ... are themselves an identifiable ethnic group
that shares common backgrounds and ideas linked to a single culture
and group loyalties.''
   The appeals court said there was no evidence ``this group has
been systematically excluded from jury service in New Jersey.''
   The 3rd Circuit court also said the defendants failed to prove
any actual prejudice against them, particularly since two jurors who
did serve at the trial had Italian surnames.
   Claims by DiNorscio and Truglia that five years was tacked on to
their prison sentences improperly also were rejected by the appeals
court.
   The five years were added under a federal law that permits longer
sentences for defendants who commit crimes while free on bail
awaiting trial.
   The defendants said they were not alerted to the possibility of
the additional prison sentences when freed on bail.
   The appeals court also rejected Cohen's argument that he was
indicted by a grand jury that lacked adequate representation by
blacks, Hispanic-Americans and people with less than high school
educations.
   The cases are DiNorscio vs. U.S., 88-1664, and Cohen vs. U.S.,
88-6875.
</TEXT>
