<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     06-26 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Sees More Deportations of Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Minister Dan Meridor today said Israel
should deport more Palestinian activists in its efforts to end the
18-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories.
   In the occupied West Bank, Arab reports today said the body of a
woman suspected of cooperating with Israeli security forces was
found in the city of Nablus. She had been beaten to death with clubs
and sharp objects.
   In Ramle, peace activist Abie Nathan today went on trial on
charges of violating an Israeli law that bans contacts with the
Palestine Liberation Organization. Nathan, 63, was indicted late
last year for meeting PLO chief Yasser Arafat and several of his
aides in Tunisia and France in September 1988.
   Meridor called for more deportations of Palestinians in an
interview on army radio, one day after the justice and defense
ministries formed a committee to devise tougher measures against
Palestinian protesters.
   ``I think deportation is serious but must be used, I would say
perhaps even more than what has been done until now,'' Meridor said.
``I think it's an effective punishment when we have appropriate
evidence.''
   Palestinians said the slain woman, Sabah El Khadi Kanaan, 30, was
accused of collaborating with Israel's secret police.
   At least 68 suspected collaborators have been killed by other
Palestinians since the uprising began in December 1987 in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. A total of 536 Palestinians and 23 Israelis
have died during the revolt.
   The new committee on putting down the uprising was formed Sunday
to examine proposals by Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin for speeding
deportations and the demolishion of houses of Palestinians suspected
of security offenses.
   Rabin also reportedly wants to lengthen the period for holding
Arab suspects without trial from six months t a year.
   The United States and human rights organizations repeatedly have
criticized all three methods of punishment because they are carried
out without due process of law or violate international conventions
on human rights.
   Israeli news reports said that Meridor had resisted some of the
steps proposed by Rabin. But Meridor told army radio that he
expected stronger measures, especially on deporations, could be
worked out ``in a few days.''
   Meridor said 50 deportations have been carried out since the
start of the uprising, and another five are being appealed before
Israeli courts. He said nearly 300 houses have been demolished or
sealed.
</TEXT>
