<FIRST>r a PM-Women'sHall     06-26 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women's Hall,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Hall of Fame Fund-Raising Comes up Short</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SENECA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An effort to raise $100,000 to save the
National Women's Hall of Fame fell short, and the 20-year-old
institution may close.
   The hall said its two-week emergency campaign collected only
about $37,000 by today, the group's self-imposed deadline.
   The institution's 21-member board was to meet tonight to decide
whether to close the museum, said Sally Parr, executive director.
   ``I truly don't know what's going to happen,'' she said. ``It
depends which board member you talk to.''
   The museum, which has been in and out of financial trouble for
years, honors 42 women including Susan B. Anthony, astronaut Sally
Ride and poet Gwendolyn Brooks, was started in 1969 and moved to its
current location in 1979.
   The first women's rights convention was held in Seneca Falls in
1848.
</TEXT>
