<FIRST>u a PM-SearsMove 1stLd-Writethru a0521 06-26 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears Move, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper: Sears To Stay In Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with company confirming employees' move to
suburbs. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. said today it will move its
6,000-employee retailing arm from the Sears Tower to the suburbs,
ending a bidding war that pitted the state of Illinois against the
Sunbelt.
   The Chicago Tribune said the nation's largest retailer was
offered $61 million in state incentives to stay in Illinois.
   Sears has been based in Chicago for more than a century.
   ``We believe this Chicagoland location will serve the best
interests of our company and its shareholders for decades to come,''
Chairman Edward Brennan said in a statement.
   Brennan said the move to Hoffman Estates, 20 miles outside
Chicago, will begin in 2{ to 3 years.
   Last fall, Sears announced a restructuring plan that included
selling the 110-story Sears Tower _ the world's tallest building _
and shifting Sears' Merchandise Group and its 6,000 employees to
less costly quarters.
   When the move is completed, only about 600 employees of Sears'
corporate staff will remain in the Sears Tower in space leased from
whoever buys the tower. Sears' huge catalog sales operation is
already based elsewhere.
   The Merchandise Group's move pitted Illinois against Sunbelt
states, especially North Carolina and Texas, which scrambled to
offer tax breaks and other incentives.
   The Chicago Tribune said Illinois offered an estimated $61
million, and local tax breaks will be worth about $178 million _ by
far the largest incentive package given to a business to move to or
stay in Illinois.
   ``The total proposal that was worked out is extremely competitive
with alternative sites,'' Brennan said. He said the Hoffman Estates
parcel was selected from about 50 sites in the Chicago area and
other states.
   Sears estimates that building a campus-style facility in Hoffman
Estates will cost $220 million.
   The Tribune and the Chicago Sun-Times said the deal was cemented
Sunday after talks between Gov. James R. Thompson and Brennan.
   Brennan thanked Thompson and legislative leaders for ``agreeing
to support the pending legislation which has enabled us to make this
decision.''
</TEXT>
