<FIRST>r w PM-DeadSeaScrolls     06-26 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dead Sea Scrolls,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Needless Delays Hurting Work on Dead Sea Scrolls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An article published today in an archaeological
review said an Israeli government timetable for scholarly work on
the Dead Sea Scrolls is a ``hoax and a fraud'' that will delay
publication of documents that may hold new insights on early Judaism
and Christianity.
   One member of the scroll publication team, Frank Moore Cross of
the Harvard Divinity School, conceded that publication of the
documets is proceeding slowly but said the ``fraud'' charge in the
magazine Biblical Archaeology Review is ``certainly incorrect.''
   The article by Hershel Shanks, editor of the review, said the
team of scholars assigned to the task, originally by the government
of Jordan and later by the government of Israel, ``has now become
more an obstacle to publication than a source of information.''
   Shanks called for opening the materials to research by ``any
scholar who so wishes.''
   The article included a copy of the timetable published by
Israel's Department of Antiquities, which calls for completion of
the work by the end of 1996.
   ``It is a hoax and a fraud,'' Shanks wrote. ``It is not a
timetable at all .. It doesn't specifiy what happens if the scholars
don't meet the timetable.''
   Cross, reached by telephone in Cambridge, said, ``The notion that
the timetable is a fraud, if that is the way it is put, is certainly
incorrect.''
   ``Timetables in scholarly work often are not kept precisely,'' he
said. ``They are sometimes beaten and they are sometimes delayed,
but the term fraud is wrong.''
   ``That the work has proceeded slowly is certainly true,'' Cross
said. ``And this is, if you wish, the norm rather than something
unusual in a find of this kind.''
   The first of the Dead Sea Scrolls, a set of ancient Hebrew texts,
were found in a cave in 1947. Some Biblical texts and a collection
of laws, stories and poetry were published soon after their
discovery. Even more of them, about 400 texts, have yet to be
released.
   ``The problem with these materials is not generally recognized,''
Cross said. ``These are not scrolls which were found intact, the
ones that have not been published, but are in literally hundreds of
thousands of pieces.''
   Shanks said some of the fragments ``are deteriorating so rapidly
that if the outside world cannot see them soon, it may never be able
to see them.''
   Cross, however, said that while the material is deteriorating it
is ``simply untrue'' that the documents will be lost if not speedily
published.
   ``The early photographs and the rephotographing that is going on
now are the way this material will be preserved,'' he said.
``Publication is not going to add anything to the original negatives
and the more recent ones.''
   The best place for them, he said, would be in a dry place deep
underground, like the caves in which they were preserved for
centuries.
   But, he added, ``We can't rebury them.''
</TEXT>
