<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-Commodores 1stLd-Writethru a0510 06-26 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Commodores, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Pop Group Cancels Visit Under Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS last graf, ``Mrs. Feldman ...'' to CORRECT with official
accusing South African organization of hypocrisy, not musical group; no
pickup. ^By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodores, a black
American singing group, has canceled a July concert in Sun City
because of pressure from anti-apartheid groups, concert organizers
said today.
   The South African Musicians Alliance warned last week that it
planned protests against the group's visit to Sun City, the capital
of the nominally independent black homeland of Bophuthatswana.
   None of South Africa's race discrimination laws apply in
Bophuthatswana, but anti-apartheid advocates object to the homeland
system that designates certain areas of the country for specific
tribes.
   A Sun City entertainment official said the musical group has
since decided not to make the trip.
   ``This action restricts cultural freedom in the same way that
apartheid abuses people's freedom of speech and choice,'' said Hazel
Feldman, entertainment director of Sun International, which runs the
hotel and entertainment complex at Sun City.
   She said 80 percent of 30,000 tickets sold for the July 7 concert
were bought by blacks.
   ``The Commodores, who have won awards in the States for their
commitment to the people by the NAACP, were deeply sincere in their
belief that their trip would bring joy to their thousands of fans,
while focusing on their commitment to the abolition of apartheid,''
she said.
   Mrs. Feldman said the Commodores, whose hits include ``Night
Shift'' and ``Three Times a Lady,'' plan to explain their action at
a Los Angeles news conference on Wednesday.
   One member of the group, Milan Williams, was quoted by South
Africa's Weekly Mail on Friday as saying he would not join the tour.
At that time, the other three members of the group and a backing
band still planned to come.
   Sun City, South Africa's version of Las Vegas, is the most
glamorous of the entertainment complexes in the homelands. It pays
premium prices and has attracted such music acts as Frank Sinatra,
Rod Stewart, and recently, Laura Brannigan and Irene Cara.
   Mrs. Feldman accused the South African Musicians Alliance of
hypocrisy. ``We respect many of their views, but feel that it is
totally hypocritical that their members will happily play Mmabatho
Independence Stadium (in Bophuthatswana) and other `homeland'
venues, while singling out Sun City as the sole target of their
campaign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
