<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Czech-Rights     06-26 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Czech-Rights,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial of Two Activists Opens in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two activists went on trial Monday in
Czechoslovakia on incitement charges for which they face a five-year
jail sentence, a human rights group said.
   Frantisek Starek, an underground publisher, and his companian,
Iva Vojtkova, went on trial in the town of Usti nad Orlice, 90 miles
east of Prague, according to the Vienna-based International Helsinki
Federation.
   Starek, 36, chief editor of the underground magazine Vokno,
already has served two prison sentences for his indepdenent
activites.
   Starek was arrested in February after police confiscated the
entire archives of the magazine. ``An important source of
information on independent culture in Czechoslovakia in the last 20
years was lost,'' the human rights group said.
   Vokno also publishes books and an information bulletin on various
events of independent groups in Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
