<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0450 06-26 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Links Crime Fight to Women's Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Bush speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today the battle against
crime in the streets is also a struggle to end violence against
women and to expand women's opportunities in the workplace.
   ``This war against women must stop,'' Bush declared to cheers at
a convention of the American Association of University Women.
   Making a pitch for his anti-crime package, the president said,
``All too often, violent crime also means crime against women.''
   ``I am angered and disgusted by the crimes against American women
and by the archaic and unacceptable attitudes that all too
frequently contribute to those crimes _ whether it involves spouse
abuse at home, or violence in the streets,'' said Bush. ``These are
evil acts that transcend racial and class lines. This war against
women must stop.''
   He said it was ``just unthinkable'' that his seven grandaughters
should not have the same opportunities in life as his four grandsons.
   ``No matter how equal the opportunities in our schools and
workplace, women will never have the same opportunities as men if a
climate of fear leaves them justificably concerned at walking to the
campus library at night, or reluctant to work late hours for fear of
getting out of some parking lot safely,'' the president said.
   ``Fundamentally, violence against women won't subside unless
public attitudes change. We must continue to educate police and
prosecutors, judges and juries, and we must engender a climate where
the message our children get, in teleivison and films, from schools
and parents, is that violence against women is wrong.''
   Bush received an honorary membership in the 140,000-member
organization. ``Technically that makes me the first AAUW member to
be president of the United States, but I know I won't be the last,''
he said to more cheers.
   The AAUW, founded in 1881, promotes equal opportunity and
advancement for women and girls at all levels of education.
   Bush was also meeting today with Japanese Foreign Minister
Hiroshi Mitsuzuka and Portuguese President Mario Soares.
   He was also holding a Rose Garden reception for former Democratic
state and local officials who have defected to the Republican Party.
   On Sunday, the president took visiting Australian Prime Minister
Bob Hawke out for a friendly game of golf at Andrews Air Force Base
in Maryland after entertaining him at Camp David.
   Bush insisted his golfing skills were ``just terrible.''
   ``I don't play golf,'' he said. ``I'm doing this just for good
will between Australia and the United States.''
   Bush will give Hawke a ceremonial greeting and host a state
dinner in his honor at the White House on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
