<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     06-26 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Sales Fail to Reflect Falling Mortgage Rates in May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospective homebuyers failed to take advantage
of falling mortgage rates in May when sales of existing homes fell
5.6 percent to their lowest level in 16 months, a real estate trade
group reported Monday.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of single-family
homes fell last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.21
million units, down from 3.4 million units in both March and April.
   The May resale rate was off 11.3 percent from a year ago, the
Realtors said, and was the lowest since 3.2 million units were sold
in January 1988.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said fixed-rate mortgage
interest dropped from 10.97 percent the first week of May to 10.48
percent at the end of the month.
   The Federal Reserve recently relaxed slightly the grip it has
held on the credit supply to restrain the economy and hold down
inflation.
   Fed Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson on Monday suggested the
possiblity of a further interest rate decline when questioned about
inflation after addressing the United Shareholders Association.
   ``Well, that's a never-ending process, the fight against
inflation,'' Johnson said. ``So, I don't think we can ever be
totally confident. But, I think we are more optimistic about the
upcoming period and I think conditions look pretty good.''
   Nevertheless, Realtors President Ira Gribin said of the lag in
response to May's falling intest rates:
   ``Buyers are not going to start flooding the markets the instant
mortgage rates start to go down. It takes time for the tide to
change.''
   But Gribin suggested the pace of existing home sales will pick up
in June as people begin to take advantage of lower mortgage rates.
   The Realtors said the median price of existing homes in May was
$93,100, up $200 from April. The median is the point at which half
of the homes sold for more and half for less.
   The decline in sales was sharpest in the Midwest, where there had
been steady activity earlier this year. Sales were down 10.1 percent
below April to a rate of 800,000 units.
   The West, which also had been largely unaffected by mortgage
rates earlier this year, also posted a notable resale decline to
570,000 units, down 8.1 percent below the April rate.
   Sales of 590,000 units in the Northeast were 3.3 percent below
April. Sales in the South dropped to 1.23 million units, down 3.9
percent from April.
</TEXT>
