<FIRST>u w PM-AIDS 2ndLd-Writethru a0506 06-26 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0506,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Underestimating Spread of AIDS, GAO Concludes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-11 pvs, Meanwhile, the ... Cytovene, with 5 grafs
to update with official FDA announcement on drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report today that federal officials are
underestimating the spread of AIDS raises questions about the
nation's ability to cope with the crisis, say congressmen who are
monitoring the epidemic.
   A General Accounting Office report says the number of AIDS cases
expected to be diagnosed over the next three years has been
undercounted by as much as one-third by the Centers for Disease
Control.
   ``The really frightening aspect of this report is it proves how
little we know about the AIDS epidemic,'' Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.,
said Sunday. He and Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., and Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., requested the study.
   ``When these projections of AIDS cases go awry, it undermines
research, destroys the validity of our plans for taking care of AIDS
victims and conveys a false sense of confidence to our fellow
citizens that the AIDS epidemic is under control,'' Wyden said.
   The GAO, in a report being released today, estimated that 300,000
to 480,000 Americans will have been diagnosed with AIDS by the end
of 1991.
   This compares with CDC's estimated range of 185,000 to 320,000
cases through 1991.
   ``The CDC has done the best they could but they've been
underfunded,'' Waxman said on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``We need a new
survey in this country about American sexual patterns, which we
haven't had for 40 years.''
   ``The United States has the best AIDS reporting system in the
world,'' Dr. James Mason, assistant secretary of health and former
director of the CDC, said on the same show. ``That's why more than
60 percent of the cases reported in the world have been reported by
the United States. ...We can always do better, however.''
   Meanwhile, the Food and Drug Administration today announced
approval of a drug to treat an eye infection in AIDS patients that
can lead to blindness. It is the fourth drug to be approved for
treatment of AIDS or an AIDS-related condition.
   The drug, ganciclovir, has been widely available for several
months to AIDS patients with the eye infection, cytomegalovirus
retinitis, under a special FDA category called ``treatment IND''
that allows distribution of promising drugs to the gravely ill while
safety and effectiveness research continues.
   About 20 percent of AIDS patients develop the eye infection.
Syntex Corp. of Palo Alto, Calif., will market the drug under the
name Cytovene.
   The FDA also announced ``treatment IND'' status for an
experimental protein, r-erythropoietin, to treat severe anemia that
weakens nearly half of the 20,000 patients taking the anti-viral
drug AZT.
   FDA Commissioner Frank Young said the two actions reflect the
agency's commitment to getting promising new drugs to AIDS victims
quickly. He said that while there still is no cure for the disease,
these two drugs and others recently approved for commercial release
and treatment INDs can extend and improve the lives of AIDS
patients, making early diagnosis more important.
   The GAO evaluated 13 national forecasts of the cumulative number
of AIDS cases through the end of 1991 and found a range of
predictions from 85,000 to 750,000 cases. The report looked only at
the number of potential AIDS cases, not the number of people who
test positive for the AIDS-causing human immunodeficiency virus but
show no symptoms of AIDS.
   Projections of the spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
are important because they are used in deciding how much money is
spent on AIDS education, research projects and public health care
services for AIDS patients.
   Also, if faulty forecasting is underestimating the heterosexual
spread of AIDS, as the report concludes, the result ``may be luring
a significant number of Americans into a false sense of security,''
Wyden said.
   Sunday editions of The Washington Post said CDC officials
acknowledged serious underreporting of AIDS cases but said GAO
projections were too high.
   The report blamed the undercounting on a variety of factors,
including the absence of data on the size of risk groups, the
definition of what constitutes an AIDS case, reliance on incomplete
surveillance data, and the undercounting of heterosexuals at risk.
   The report said CDC must get more up-to-date and accurate
information about the risk groups if it hopes to improve its
projections.
   Earlir this month, a University of Chicago study also said CDC
may be significantly underestimating the number of Americans with
AIDS. The study attributed some of the undercounting to affluent
victims who are treated discreetly by physicians who do not report
cases of the disease.
   AIDS is spread by close contact with blood, blood products or
semen from infected people. Its chief victims are homosexual men and
intravenous drug users.
   As of May 31, 1989, AIDS had been diagnosed in 97,193 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 56,468, have died since June 1, 1981,
according to the CDC. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
