<FIRST>u a PM-OilSpillRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0558 06-26 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0558,0956</SECOND>
<HEAD>R.I. Spill Dispersing; Cleanup Continues in Delaware, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with officials saying little oil off Rhode
Island; damage to Delaware River shoreline called minimal. PICKS UP 7th
graf pvs, `Hours after...'; SUBS grafs 15-17 bgng `Elsewhere, contractors
...' with 5 grafs with briefing on Delaware River.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BX1,PX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 420,000 gallons of oil spilled from a
tanker off Rhode Island had largely dispersed or evaporated by this
morning, officials said. Hundreds of people worked to clean up
spills in Delaware and Texas.
   Things were ``much, much better than yesterday,'' Stephen G.
Morin, a state environmental official, said after flying over the
stricken World Prodigy, which ran aground on a reef Friday at the
mouth of Narragansett Bay.
   In Delaware, officials also were optimistic, saying the much
heavier oil spilled in the Delaware River on Saturday was so
congealed in the cool water that shoreline damage was minimal.
Workers used rakes to remove football-size, tar-like gobs from the
river, where up to 800,000 gallons spilled.
   As a tropical storm approached Texas, crews there brought in
``supersucker'' vacuums to clean up a 250,000-gallon spill near
Houston.
   Morin, Rhode Island director of groundwater and wetlands, said he
and other officials flew more than 14 miles offshore and found only
one small patch of oil about four miles out that he said was
unlikely to reach shore.
   ``I haven't seen it anywhere on the beaches we've flown today,''
he said.
   Nevertheless, Gov. Edward D. DiPrete ordered beaches to remain
closed today, and a ban on shellfishing remained in effect.
   Since lobsters, flounders, cod and haddock _ important to the
region's fishing industry _ are now laying eggs, it is the worst
possible time for an oil spill, said Kenneth Sherman of the National
Marine Fisheries Service. Fish can swim away from the slick, but
larvae don't have that mobility, he said.
   DiPrete said the captain of the Greek-licensed World Prodigy,
Iakovis Georgudis, admitted he failed to wait for a pilot and
mistakenly changed course, sending the ship toward rocks.
   Hours after the accident, a tanker and an oil barge collided in
the Houston Ship Channel that connects the Texas city with Galveston
Bay, causing a spill. And early Saturday, heavy oil spilled in the
Delaware River after an Uruguayan tanker ran aground.
   Results of drug tests on Georgudis and a mate whose name was not
immediately available were expected by late today, although the
Coast Guard said drugs or alcohol were not believed to have been
factors in the accident.
   The crewmen's urine samples were mishandled, reportedly through
improper refrigeration, and new ones had to be taken 19 hours after
the accident, the Coast Guard said.
   A federal inquiry will be convened Tuesday, Coast Guard Adm.
Richard Rybacki said. State Attorney General James E. O'Neil said he
hopes to learn if Georgudis violated state law by approaching too
near the bay without a pilot.
   The Coast Guard reduced its estimate of the amount of oil spilled
to 420,000 gallons. Earlier estimates were as high as 1.6 million.
About 200 National Guardsmen, 120 prison inmates and 200 volunteers
fought the oil.
   The oil spread rapidly over nearly 30 square miles. At one point,
it threatened Block Island, a fashionable vacation spot, but this
morning officials said that worry had ebbed because the oil was
evaporating rapidly.
   ``You're reaching the point where you're running out of molecules
that can go anywhere,'' said a Coast Guard spokesman, Chief Warrant
Officer Rick Meidt.
   Most of Rhode Island's beaches reopened Sunday after overnight
winds pushed the oil offshore, but the governor today closed beaches
nearly to Connecticut.
   Elsewhere, contractors in the Delaware River hired 255 employees,
and Delaware agreed to provide 300 National Guardsmen to help remove
the heavy fuel oil floating in globs and occasionally washing ashore
in Delaware, New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   Federal officials said this morning that shoreline damage was
minimal. Coast Guard Capt. Larry Murdock said there won't be much of
a problem unless the oil was somehow warmed to 95 degrees or higher
and liquified.
   The tanker, refloated Sunday, was carrying 18 million gallons of
heating oil. Officials said that they were unable to account for at
least 800,000 gallons but that the actual spill was probably less.
   Shoreline contamination was reported from Ridley, Pa., on the
outskirts of Philadelphia, to New Castle, Del., about 30 miles to
the south.
   Wildlife officials worked to protect Pea Patch Island, home to
several species of nesting shorebirds. Crews laid 1,700 feet of
oil-retaining booms along the island, one of the mid-Atlantic's
largest rookeries. One oil-covered duckling died, but the Coast
Guard said wildlife deaths would probably be limited because the oil
is so thick it won't easily smear onto animals' bodies.
   ``These are important nursing grounds and this is an important
time of year,'' said Thomas Malone, acting head of the University of
Maryland Center for Environmental and Estuarine Studies.
   In Texas, crews aided by wind and waves from the approach of
Tropical Storm Allison used seven huge vacuum machines to try to
pick up the oil.
   By this morning, about a third of the oil had been sucked from
the Bayport Channel, where the oil was flowing, said Coast Guard
spokesman Bob Morehead.
   ``They're stepping up their cleanup efforts to try to get it out
before the storm comes in,'' Morehead said.
   The Coast Guard scheduled a hearing on Tuesday to investigate
Friday's collision of the tanker Rachel-B and a barge owned by
Coastal Towing Co. of Houston.
</TEXT>
