<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BurglaryVeteran     06-26 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Burglary Veteran,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owner 128, Burglars 27 in 20-Year Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a gas station and
convenience store caught a burglar breaking into his business over
the midsummer holiday, the 155th attempted break-in in 20 years.
   Owner William Hecktor has foiled 128 burglaries at the station,
according to the Dagens Nyheter newspaper.
   Break-ins are a rarity in a country that is regarded as having
little street crime.
   The station, near Eslov in southern Sweden, is in a remote area
20 miles from the closest police station. Police officer Soini
Haanpaa said Hecktor had learned to depend on himself because there
is little police can do to help.
   With the help of neighbors, a sophisticated alarm system and his
dog, he ``does a fantastic job'' of deterring crime, Haanpaa said.
   ``You would think that the word would get around that the station
is not such a good place for robberies,'' said Haanpaa.
</TEXT>
