<FIRST>u a PM-BoxOffice     06-26 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caped Crusader Drives Nation Batty, Propels All-Time Box Office Tallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moviegoers went batty over the Caped Crusader,
with ``Batman'' taking in a record $43.6 million and giving
Hollywood its biggest weekend ever.
   The film, starring Michael Keaton as Batman and Jack Nicholson as
the archvillian Joker, helped the nation's theaters over the weekend
gross a record $95 million-plus overall.
   ``Batman's'' debut on 2,193 screens surpassed the three-day
record $29.4 million set just a week earlier by ``Ghostbusters II,''
studio receipts showed today.
   ``This is tremendous. It is the biggest weekend ever in the
history of the business,'' said John Krier of Exhibitor Relations
Co., which tracks box-office performance.
   The previous overall box-office record for a three-day weekend
was $92 million, said Krier.
   ``Batman'' also broke every daily record.
   It took in $15.6 million on Friday to beat the $10.2 million by
``Ghostbusters II'' a week earlier, $14.8 million on Saturday to top
the record $11.2 million by ``Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade''
on May 27, and $13.2 million on Sunday to top the May 28 mark of
$10.2 million by ``Last Crusade.''
   In second place was Disney's ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids,'' which
grossed $14.2 million and broke all opening weekend box office
tallies for that studio, said Krier. ``Three Men and a Baby'' was
Disney's previous leader with $13.1 million over the 1987-88 New
Year's weekend.
   ``Ghostbusters II'' was third with $14 million, ``Indiana Jones
and the Last Crusade'' was fourth with $7.8 million and ``Dead Poets
Society'' was fifth with $7.6 million.
</TEXT>
