<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Algeria-Riot     06-26 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Algeria-Riot,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Algerians Riot Over Prolonged Water Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the southern Algerian town
of Sud-Aissa burned buildings in street riots to protest cuts in
water service, the Algerian Press Service reported.
   The most recent water cut, which lasted several days and extended
into the weekend, sent 1,500 demonstrators into the streets Saturday
to burn public and private buildings in the small town 125 miles
south of Algiers.
   Several vehicles, including two belonging to the police, were set
ablaze, the news agency reported Sunday. It did not indicate whether
there had been any injuries.
   In April, riots spread throughout Algeria because of
deteriorating economic conditions and price increases in the North
African country of 25 million. The demonstrations led to reforms in
Algeria's constitution and the government of President Chadli
Benjedid.
</TEXT>
