<FIRST>r w AM-Anderson-Reprimand     06-26 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anderson-Reprimand,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anderson Reprimanded by Committee of Journalists in Gun Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of journalists reprimanded
columnist Jack Anderson on Monday for his ``role in bringing a gun
into the Capitol'' for a television show on terrorism but did not
revoke his press credentials. He rejected the reprimand.
   Anderson has said he engineered the plan to smuggle the gun into
the Capitol last month to show a need for better security. He did
not carry in the gun himself.
   ``We believe that you abused your privilege as a credentialed
member of the daily press gallery, and needlessly jeopardized the
relationship reporters have with the Capitol police,'' Jeffrey
Birnbaum, of The Wall Street Journal, wrote in a letter to Anderson.
   He said the five-member committee, which provides credentials to
reporters who cover Congress, ``has voted unanimously to reprimand
you for your role in bringing a gun into the Capitol last month.''
   Anderson responded with his own letter, saying: ``With no
disrepect intended, I must reject the reprimand of the standing
committee.''
   He said he knew that several terrorist leaders were planning to
make the United States their target and that the political leaders
would be in danger.
   ``I'm appalled that the congressional leaders whose lives I
wanted to protect seem less concerned about the threat to their
security than the political embarrassment I apparently caused them.''
   During an interview May 24 with Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., in Dole's
private office, Anderson pulled from his pocket a gun that had been
concealed in his televison crew's equipment. The incident occurred
during taping for a segment of his TV program and Anderson claimed
it was to demonstrate security breaches in the building.
   But it is a felony to bring a firearm onto the Capitol grounds or
into any of the buildings, and Capitol police and the U.S. attorney
are investigating whether to press charges against Anderson, said
officer Dan Nichols.
   Anderson told the Standing Committee of Correspondents he would
not be at their meeting unless Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, and Dole, the minority leader, were there.
   They did not appear, though they had initiated the action by
asking Birnbaum in a June 6 letter to ``review this serious incident
and take sufficient action to deter any future repetition of this
act.''
   The committee, whose leaders are elected by journalists, was
established by Congress to decide who should work in the press
galleries and to allocate space in the galleries.
   Along with sending a letter of reprimand to Anderson, the
committee voted to revise its regulations so that any credentialed
member who disobeys security rules in the future would be subject to
suspension.
   ``When you used your position as a reporter to have a weapon
brought into the Capitol, and then produced it in the office of Sen.
Robert Dole on May 24, you violated the trust that our extension of
the credential to you implies,'' said Birnbaum's letter to Anderson.
``Therefore we admonish you in the strongest terms.''
   While Anderson is credentialed, he has not picked up his
identification tag and was using a visitor's pass at the time of the
incident. He said he entered the Capitol as an ordinary citizen and
``was afforded no special privileges or treatment because I am a
journalist.''
   Birnbaum said that he did not recommend suspending the
investigative reporter because he was not carrying the credential,
there was no precedent for such action and ``our own rules are
sufficiently unclear that so drastic a step might be misconstrued as
the rendering of a judgment by an official press body on the quality
of Mr. Anderson's journalism.''
   Other members of the committee are Charles Green of Knight-Ridder
Newspapers, Eliot Brenner of United Press International, Mary Deibel
of Scripps Howard News Service and Thomas Gorey of the Salt Lake
Tribune.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
