<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Malaysia-Koran     06-26 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Malaysia-Koran,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malaysia to Ban Koran With Roman Script</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will ban versions of
the Koran using Roman script, allowing only those in Jawi and Arabic
scripts, an official said Monday.
   Abdul Hamid Othman, director general of the Islamic Affairs
Division in the prime minister's department, said the ban would take
effect in about six months.
   Under the ban, anyone possessing the Koran in Roman script could
be imprisoned for up to three years or fined about $1,850, he said.
   The National Fatwa Committee, which rules on Islamic matters,
decided to impose the ban, because the Roman version did not give
proper pronunciations.
   The Jawi script looks like Arabic or Urdu script.
   Islam is Malaysia's official religion and about half of its 17
million people are Moslems. The others are mainly Buddhists, Hindus
and Christians.
</TEXT>
