<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Cars     06-26 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Cars,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea to Make 2 Million Cars Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's automakers will expand
production facilities to produce 2 million vehicles a year starting
in 1990, up from the current 1.6 million, news reports said Monday.
   Led by Hyundai Motor Co., the nation's largest automaker,
manufacturers will construct facilities to make another 350,000
units a year, according to the South Korean news agency Yonhap.
   Two other firms, Ssangyong and Asia, will manufacture vehicles
when the government lifts a ban on further production in July,
Yonhap said.
   Hyundai's current production capacity of 850,000 vehicles will
grow to 1 million by early next year, Yonhap said.
   Kia Motors Corp. will finish an assembly line with a 150,000-car
capacity next year, Yonhap said, increasing its annual capacity to
600,000 vehicles.
   Daewoo Motor Co. is to expand production of medium-sized cars and
expects to construct a factory to produce 50,000 cars, Yonhap said.
</TEXT>
