<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Hajj     06-26 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Hajj,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Israeli Moslems Leave For Mecca</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLENBY BRIDGE, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of white-robed
Israeli Moslems crossed this army checkpoint Monday for the annual
pilgrimage to Mecca, and Israeli officials urged them to help
mediate between the Jewish state and its Arab neighbors.
   ``There has been a lot of hatred, mistrust and enmity,'' Cabinet
member Ehud Olmert said at a ceremony marking the pilgrims' crossing
the bridge to Jordan for the trip to Saudi Arabia.
   ``You can serve as a bridge'' between Israel on the one side, and
Arab states and Palestinians on the other, said Olmert, the prime
minister's adviser on Arab affairs.
   But some of the 5,400 Israeli Arabs pilgrims said they identified
more with the Palestinians' 18-month uprising in the occupied lands
than with Israel.
   ``We are proud of the uprising. It has given us more respect
outside,'' said Hosni Nuseirat, 42, of the northern Israeli village
of Taibeh.
   ``We have deep ties to the Palestinians in the occupied
territories. It's religion that binds us together, and we are all
members of the same nation,'' Nuseirat said.
   There are 810,000 Israeli Arab citizens, from families who
remained in Israel when the Jewish state was founded in 1948.
   About 1.7 million Palestinians live in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, including those who fled Israel in 1948 and residents of
the occupied lands before they were captured in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   Nuseirat and about 1,400 other Israeli Arab pilgrims, most in
white robes and white prayer caps, sat in two dozen buses waiting
for a last security check before crossing the Allenby Bridge into
Jordan.
   Women wearing white scarves repacked their belongings after
searches by soldiers, reassembling bed rolls and plastic shopping
baskets filled with rice, sugar, olives, coffee and tea.
   About 5,400 Israeli Arabs, up about 400 from last year, are
leaving for Mecca via Jordan this week. They are scheduled to return
by July 21.
   Mecca is Islam's holiest site, and making the hajj, or
pilgrimage, is one of the chief religious duties of Moslems.
   Saudi Arabia and Jordan, both technically at war with Israel,
first permitted Israeli Arabs to join the hajj in 1977. Saudi Arabia
limits the number of pilgrims, and Israel only gives exit permits to
Moslems who are 30 years of age or older, citing security reasons.
   ``We are angry about this. In our religion, there is no such
thing as an age limit,'' said Yehiah Haj, 31, also of Taibeh.
   Haj made his first pilgrimage last year and said Israeli Arabs
attract much attention in Saudia Arabia. ``When we say where we are
from, people gather around. They want to know what's going on in
Israel,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
