<FIRST>r i AM-France-Iran     06-26 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Iran,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paris-Based Ayatollah Wants to Run for President of Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man considered the spiritual leader of Shiite
Moslems in Europe said Monday he wants to run for president of Iran
but is being refused a valid passport to return to his homeland.
   Ayatollah Mehdi Rouhani said he wrote a letter June 10 to
Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi to inform him of his bid for
the presidency. He said that on Friday, he was instructed to go the
Iranian Embassy to fill out the proper forms, but on Monday he was
told he could not get his passport validated.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani is the only official
candidate for the July 28 election. Wednesday is the last day to
file as a candidate.
   The Iranian Embassy was closed Monday and officials there could
be reached for comment.
   Rouhani, 53, has spent 25 years in Europe and is a resident of
France. He said he has been unable to get his Iranian passport
validated for four or five years.
   Rouhani, who holds a doctorate in philosophy from the Sorbonne,
said with his religious status and education he represents both the
intellectual and religious currents in Iran.
   ``There is no law to forbid me from running,'' he said, ``but
they found a pretext to stop me from returning to Iran.''
   Rouhani says he supports the 1979 Iranian revolution which
overthrew Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi but disagrees with the current
government. He said he decided to run for president following the
June 3 death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
</TEXT>
