<HEAD>West Virginia High School Yearbook Recognizes Student Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most yearbooks give space to students who
excel in sports and other extracurricular activities. Logan High
School's 1988-89 edition also recognizes students who have given
birth.
   ``Babies raising babies is something we are all having to deal
with these days,'' said yearbook sponsor Jimmie Sue Mazon.
   She said students decided to include a section on teen-age
parents as they searched for a theme involving student
responsibility.
   ``What could be more responsible? It might be a controversial
theme, and some may have negative thoughts about it, but it is such
a prevalent thing now, I don't expect any severe criticism,'' Mazon
said.
   As many as 40 teen-agers at the school reportedly are pregnant or
have had at least one child.
   Rhonda Spry, 17, of Verdunville, who designed the special
yearbook section, has twins who turned 1 on June 20. Spry, who has a
B-minus average and whose family helps care for her children,
included the following passage:
   ``Everyone needs to take a little time and open their eyes to
this very touchy subject. It can happen to you.
   ``Suicide is always a big question somewhere, but it is
definitely the wrong one. You know this when you are blessed with
holding your child.
   ``Babies can be the most wonderful thing in the world, if you are
ready to give up most of your time and take the responsibility of
another life coming before your own.''
