<FIRST>u a PM-TropicalWeather 3rdLd-Writethru a0533 06-26 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0533,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Season's First Tropical Storm Brings Heavy Rain to Texas Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with storm strength, position, evacuation.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first tropical storm of the season developed
in the Gulf of Mexico this morning, bringing heavy rain and flooding
to the Texas coast.
   The National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla., upgraded a
slow-moving tropical depression to a storm about 7 a.m. after its
sustained winds reached 39 mph.
   By late morning, Tropical Storm Allison had sustained near 50 mph
with gusts to 65 mph, the National Weather Service said. It was
moving north about 5 mph and was southwest of Freeport, about 55
miles south of Houston.
   A voluntary evacuation was issued for Quintana Beach, a small
island community of about 150 south of Houston. Sheriff's deputies
went door-to-door telling residents that rising waters could close
the bridge to the mainland.
   ``We're telling them if they want to get out, they'd better get
out now,'' Chief Deputy Charles Wagner said.
   Tides in Galveston were about three feet above normal.
   ``There probably will be some minor wind damage. The main thing
is the rain. It's a heavy rainmaker,'' National Weather Service
meteorologist Larry Vannozzi said.
   A tropical storm warning was issued from Freeport to Morgan City,
La. There were reports of flooding south of Galveston, Matagorda and
Brazoria.
   Rain drenched the coast, with as much as 6 inches reported from
midnight to midmorning. A flash flood watch was in effect for much
of the southeast Texas coast.
   In Louisiana, shrimp fishermen stayed home and tourists were
urged to avoid coastal areas. ``It's not really nasty here _ yet,''
Calcasieu Parish, La., Deputy Bradley Fontenot said. ``They say it's
going to be.''
   On Sunday, the Galveston County beach patrol banned swimming.
``It's got the gulf kicked up pretty nasty out there right now,''
patrol director Vic Maceo said.
   In Corpus Christi, some residents waited to take precautions.
   ``The surfing and wind surfing are real popular today _ they're
out there right now,'' police dispatcher Richard Diaz said Sunday.
   The tropical depression had its origins in Hurricane Cosme, which
moved from the Pacific Ocean across Mexico last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
