<FIRST>r w AM-Yeutter-Subsidies     06-26 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeutter-Subsidies,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>If All Aid Requests Honored, Deficit Could Triple: Yeutter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said
Monday that the federal deficit would double or triple if all
requests for farm aid were honored.
   Yeutter, speaking at a meeting of the American Seed Trade
Association, said about 75 percent of his mail comes from people
asking for more government assistance of some kind.
   ``Most of these letters are coming from members of Congress, of
course, reflecting concerns of their constitutents,'' he said.
   ``If the government were to honor all of those pleas for
additional funding, that ... $150 billion deficit that we have now
would probably double or treble, just based on agricultural requests
alone, aside from what the rest of the economy is asking for.''
   Yeutter said there are many views as to whether American farmers
have become addicted to federal subsidies.
   He said his home state of Nebraska last year had a net farm
income of ``something over $2 billion,'' of which more than $1
billion came from the government.
   ``That's pretty addictive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
