<NOTE>Eds: Version also moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston Celtics forward Larry Bird is back on
his feet and scoring following surgery seven months ago.
   Bird took the court against National Basketball Association
competition Sunday night for the first time since bone spurs were
removed from both heels. Lingering soreness in the left foot kept
him from returning to the court during the playoffs.
   He may not be back to full form, but he scored a reassuring 33
points in 29 minutes in the second Larry Bird Pro All-Star
Scholarship Classic, a charity game.
   ``Well, it's been a while but overall I was pleased with this
little test,'' Bird said. ``I really wasn't thinking about the
injury going out there. I was just worried about getting in the flow
and up and down the court.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UTICA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Oliver North read from
the Bible at the wedding of his brother, Timothy.
   ``I haven't granted an interview in two years and all I will say
is that I am glad to be here for my brother's wedding,'' North said
after Saturday's ceremony at Sacred Heart Church in west Utica.
   During the ceremony, North read from the book of Psalms in a
leather-bound Bible. ``The Lord is kind and merciful to those who
fear him,'' he said.
   Outside church, North joked with guests and obliged all who
wanted their picture taken with the former Marine lieutenant
colonel. That included a woman in shorts who ran over to him holding
up an Ollie North T-shirt and telling him he was her hero.
   North hugged her and said, ``God bless you ... thank you.''
   A federal jury in Washington last month convicted North of three
felonies and acquitted him of nine other charges in the scandal. He
faces up to 10 years in prison at sentencing July 5.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the music man behind the movie ``Batman,''
composer Danny Elfman's major challenge was to come up with a score
that wouldn't be drowned out by the film's multimillion-dollar sound
effects.
   ``It's hard to find something that will carry a scene, especially
when you know there's going to be a jet engine or machine gun fire.
Even the Batmobile had a jet engine,'' said Elfman, one of
Hollywood's hottest composers. He also leads the pop group Oingo
Boingo.
   Elfman has scored 10 films in the past four years, starting with
``Pee-wee's Big Adventure,'' in between writing songs for Oingo
Boingo and performing with the group.
   The ``Batman'' score took six weeks to complete, including two
songs contributed by rock star Prince. Elfman said last week that
the ``Batman'' score, at 75 minutes in length, was his most
challenging project.
   ``The scenes seemed to carry their own music,'' Elfman said. ``I
work visually. I don't know how to approach music on an intellectual
level.''
</TEXT>
