<FIRST>r e BC-JVCJazz     06-26 0992</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-JVC Jazz,1028</SECOND>
<HEAD>JVC Jazz Festival Opens Over Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz made its annual summer visit to New York
over the weekend, with the start of the JVC Jazz Festival.
   The dueling trumpets of Miles Davis and Wynton Marsalis launched
the hot music event at Avery Fisher Hall on Friday night. Marsalis,
a technically astute and rather mainstream musician whose background
is firmly based in classical music, opened the concert.
   Michael White joined him on clarinet during ``New Orleans
Function,'' a piece with marching band flare.
   Davis, one of the greatest trumpet players the jazz world has
ever known, stuck to his funky colorings of such contemporary pop
pieces as ``Human Nature,'' rather than breezing through his legacy
of music dating to the 1940s. He also did a lilting version of Cyndi
Lauper's ``Time After Time.''
   While Miles and Wynton blew the house down at Avery Fisher,
singer Joe Williams was saluted at Carnegie Hall.
   On Saturday afternoon, Marsalis introduced youngsters to jazz at
a concert titled ``Coolin' It With Snoopy.'' And, yes, the famed
``Peanuts'' doggy was there. Saturday night featured a salute to
Benny Goodman, starring Lionel Hampton and George Benson.
   A special concert of African and Caribbean music played at Avery
Fisher Hall on Sunday night.Featured were Haiti's Tabou Combo de
Petion-Ville and the Bhundu Boys from Zimbabwe.
   While the rhythms exploded at Avery Fisher, Ella
Fitzgeraldquietly stunned a Carnegie Hall audience.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Joe Williams, Basie Band Celebrate Singer's 70th Birthday</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobody loves family reunions more than jazz
people. And what more joyous reunion could there be than that of
singer Joe Williams and the Count Basie Orchestra.
   Williams became a star when he joined the Basie band in the
mid-1950s. Williams' 1955 recording with the band of ``Every Day I
Have the Blues'' made him internationally known. Eventually, in
1961, he struck out on his own and has had continued success.
   His 70th birthday seemed like a natural occasion for a
``reunion'' with the Basie bunch, led these days by saxophonist
Frank Foster. It also made for a splendid opening night Friday of
the JVC Jazz Festival, which first came to town 18 years ago as the
Newport Jazz Festival. It has changed sponsors and names a few
times, but it's still a premiere jazz bash. JVC is the Japanese
Victor Co., an electronics firm.
   The Carnegie Hall concert showed why Joe Williams has endured.
His voice ranges from a whisper to a shout, as comfortable with
gospel and ballad standards as with the lowdown blues.
   The first half of the concert, Williams and his trio, led by
pianist Norman Simmons, explored the singer's range. Ballads
alternated with some shouters' favorites; ``Embraceable You,'' for
example, followed by ``All Right, OK, You Win.''
   Several duets with Marlena Shaw ended the all-Williams part of
the evening.
   After the intermission, the 16-piece Basie band, spurred on at
times by dervish-like drummer Duffy Jackson, drove up the tempo. The
orchestra performed a memorable ``Count Basie Remembrance Suite'' in
honor of its jaunty founder. Carmen Bradford, the band's vocalist,
sang a powerful and exciting ``Young and Foolish.''
   Then came the highlight the audience had been waiting for.
Williams came back on stage and shouted several blues songs, his
voice welling up to match the power of the Basie bunch.
   Happy birthday, Joe Williams, and many more.
   _ By William Gillen, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Jazz Stars Salute the Late Benny Goodman</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a half-century after he joined the
Benny Goodman band, 80-year-old Lionel Hampton displayed the verve
of youth as he joined guitarist George Benson and the Loren
Schoenberg big band for a tribute to the late bandleader.
   Several other Goodman alumni, including pianist Dick Hyman,
trumpeter Joe Newman, and saxophone player Toots Mondello were on
hand Saturday night at Carnegie Hall for the affectionate salute to
Goodman, who died in 1987.
   With the effervescent Hampton leading the way, and clarinetists
Ken Teplowski and Kenny Davern alternating on Goodman's parts, the
band swung through a repetoire of tunes Goodman helped make great,
including ``Don't Be That Way,'' ``Soft Winds,'' ``Stompin' at the
Savoy'' and ``Body and Soul.''
   Benson added an updated interpretation of guitarist Charlie
Christian's role in the band, and rising stars Terence Blanchard on
trumpet and Ralph Moore on tenor sax gave a new wave spin to the
standards.
   The evening closed with Hampton switching from vibes to drums for
a hard-charging version of ``Sing, Sing, Sing,'' which brought a
cheering audience to its feet.
   _ By Mitchell Landsberg, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Loyal Fans Show Ella Their Love</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ella was hot. She repeatedly dabbed her brow with
a white hanky and complained about exactly how hot she was. Then she
went on to cook for nearly two hours.
   The sold-out crowd at Carnegie Hall was on its feet before the
first note came out of Ella Fitzgerald's mouth Sunday night at the
JVC Jazz Festival.
   At 71, Miss Fitzgerald's voice is still as smooth and sweet as
caramel sauce. And she dished it out with tributes to George
Gershwin, Burt Bacharach, Billie Holiday and finally, to ``my loyal
fans,'' with Stevie Wonder's ``You Are the Sunshine of My Life.''
   Miss Fitzgerald was backed by her trio of Keter Betts on bass,
Bobby Durham on drums and Mike Wofford on piano. She was at her best
in her second set when joined by guitarist Joe Pass. She hit the
high note of the evening in a scat duet with Pass on ``One Note
Samba.''
   The song stylist spent much of her time on stage performing on a
stool _ doctor's orders, she said _ and her infrequent steps seemed
unsteady. She made up a few lyrics and once interrupted a Pass solo.
   But for this audience, the elegant Ella could do no wrong.
   _ By Larry Ryckman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
