<DOCNO> AP890626-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1509EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-26 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he pulled into the row of little orange balls,
bus driver Donald Desmond closed his eyes and let the gods be his
guide.
   The rear tires of his yellow and white Massachusetts Bay Transit
Authority bus came within 1{ inches of the markers on either side.
But the 16-year veteran of Boston's snarled traffic and snarling
commuters kept his coach in the clear Sunday to win the ``Bus
Driver's Rodeo'' and claim the title of top jockey among the city's
2,200 bus drivers.
   His next stop: the national championships in Atlanta in September
where drivers from 65 cities in the United States and Canada are
expected to compete.
   ``My tongue is down in my gut somewhere,'' he said after taking
the 40-foot bus through 11 obstacles in 5 minutes, 36 seconds. ``I
feel like I can barely breathe.''
   The finalists in the 13th annual Boston bus rodeo negotiated
hundreds of orange pylons, rubber balls and plastic barrels spread
across a parking lot the size of two football fields.
   Some of the obstacles mimic maneuvers the drivers have to make
every working day, like making tight right-hand turns and squeezing
between parked cars to pick up passengers. Other tests, such as
backing up to a pylon or running the gauntlet of rubber balls,
require special practice.
   ``Whenever I see a can or a paper cup in the road, I try to hit
it with my right wheel,'' said Gus Swanson Jr., a 33-year veteran of
the transit authority. ``That way I get a feel for where my right
wheel is all the time, and when I go through the balls, I just
adjust by 3 inches, so I miss them instead of hit them.''
   The winner of the Boston rodeo gets a $200 gift certificate and a
reserved parking space at work.
   ``You can feel it click when you get a good run like that,''
Desmond said. ``When I go into the balls, though, I just close my
eyes and say, `God help me.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose hypnotized frogs lie on their
backs and lift tiny barbells might be called a ratbag in Australia.
In California, such eccentricity is nurtured.
   True eccentrics, have a sense of humor, intense curiosity, a high
sense of integrity and a desire to make the world better or at least
happier, said David Weeks of the Royal Hospital in Edinburgh,
Scotland.
   Weeks, who is doing a second book on eccentrics, has been
studying offbeat people for five years, and in an earlier book,
``Eccentrics: The Scientific Investigation,'' focused on Europeans.
About half his estimated 1,000 American subjects are from California.
   Weeks doesn't believe Californians are by nature flaky. But
California seems to take pride in its oddballs, he said in an
interview published Sunday.
   ``It's very tolerant and proud and nurturing of eccentricity,''
he said. ``In some parts of the world, by contrast, eccentricity is
denigrated. In Sydney, for example, they call them ratbags. Not in
California.''
   Among Weeks' subjects was Bill Steed, who lives in Emeryville
across the Bay Bridge from San Francisco and has toured the fair
circuit with 40 hypnotized frogs and many laughs.
   ``Are we a little kooky?'' asks Steed. ``Look at it this way. We
work when we want to work, we make a fairly decent living, we make
people happy and we're happy ourselves.''
   Diana Stoneberg is another Californian who became one of Weeks'
subjects.
   A former writer for Chicago's ``Bozo the Clown'' television show,
Stoneberg said being eccentric is ``quite complimentary.''
   ``I'd rather go down as an eccentric than as a routine, normal
person,'' she said.
</TEXT>
