<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-RoseInvestigation 3rdLd-Writethru a0597 06-26 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rose Investigation, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0597,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Baseball's Lawyers Say Ruling Threaten's the Game's Integrity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD quotes from request; PICKS UP 7th
graf pvs, `Robert Pitcairn ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CS1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball's lawyers today asked an appeals court
to suspend a judge's postponement of Pete Rose's hearing before the
commissioner of baseball, saying the ruling ``threatens the very
reputation'' of the game.
   Common Pleas Judge Norbert A. Nadel on Sunday delayed for at
least two weeks a hearing today at which Commissioner A. Bartlett
Giamatti was to consider allegations Rose bet on ballgames. Nadel
agreed with Rose that Giamatti had already made up his mind against
the Cincinnati Reds manager and could not judge Rose fairly.
   In a request today for the suspension of Nadel's temporary
restraining order, baseball called the ruling unprecedented.
   ``If every action of the commissioner to investigate and
determine matters affecting the integrity of the game were to be
subject to court intervention and delay, the commissioner's ability
to safeguard the integrity of the game would be destroyed,'' the
request said.
   ``The action of the court below threatens the very reputation of
major league baseball and deprives the commissioner of the power to
protect the integrity of the game.''
   A three-judge state appeals court panel will decide baseball's
request after receiving a response from Rose's lawyers, which is due
Wednesday morning.
   Rose could be banned from baseball for life if Giamatti accepts
evidence from a baseball investigator that Rose bet on his own team.
   Robert Pitcairn Jr., a lawyer for Rose, was said to be in a
meeting this morning and was unavailable for comment.
   Nadel on Sunday said the outcome of the baseball commissioner's
hearing was a ``foregone conclusion.''
   ``I think we got justice,'' said Rose's attorney, Reuven Katz.
   ``I'm just pleased that we get the next opportunity,'' Rose said
after his team lost 7-0 to Los Angeles. ``Obviously we're pleased
about this. That's it. Next things next.''
   Nadel's ruling set a collision course with federal court
decisions that have upheld the commissioner's broad authority to act
when the integrity of the game is at stake. Baseball team owners
Charles O. Finley and Ted Turner lost challenges of the authority of
then-Commissioner Bowie Kuhn in the 1970s.
   ``The judge has made a mistake, a big one,'' baseball lawyer
Louis Hoynes Jr. said Sunday. ``It's an erroneous ruling. It's a
problem, a serious mistake.''
   Giamatti said he'll fight Nadel's decision ``tooth and nail.''
   ``I regret the judge's decision. I have absolutely no prejudgment
or prejudice regarding Pete Rose,'' Giamatti said.
   Nadel, who is up for re-election in 16 months, agreed with Rose's
lawyers that the commissioner had already made up his mind that Rose
is guilty of betting on baseball games.
   The judge referred to a letter at the heart of Rose's case _ a
recommendation sent by Giamatti to a federal judge as part of the
sentencing of bookmaker Ronald Peters.
   The letter praised Peters for being ``candid, forthright and
truthful'' with special baseball investigator John M. Dowd, who
found evidence that Rose bet on Reds games and other baseball games
in 1985, 1986 and 1987.
   Peters has told federal authorities who also are investigating
Rose that he accepted perhaps more than $1 million in bets on behalf
of the manager for two years.
   Nadel held the letter up in court Sunday as he announced his
decision.
   ``It therefore appears to this court at this point that the
commissioner of baseball has prejudged Peter Edward Rose,'' Nadel
said. ``We further find that the hearing set tomorrow in New York
before the commissioner of baseball would be futile and illusory and
the outcome a foregone conclusion.''
   Nadel ruled that baseball can't take any action against Rose for
the 14 days the temporary restraining order is in effect. He also
ruled that Rose can't be fired during that time.
   The judge set arguments for a preliminary injunction for July 6.
If granted, an injunction could indefinitely block the commissioner
from deciding Rose's fate while the court takes over the case.
   Rose has sought just that _ getting a judge in his hometown
rather than Giamatti to determine the charges.
   Nadel's ruling didn't touch on the question of whether Rose bet
on baseball. Rose has denied doing so, but Dowd testified before
Nadel last week that the manager admitted he had bet on other
professional sports.
   The Reds' manager was in his office behind a closed door while
the decision was broadcast on television. Although he had little to
say afterward, several fans displayed banners of celebration at
Riverfront Stadium and Reds reliever Rob Dibble expressed full
support.
   ``Bart Giamatti knows nothing about baseball,'' Dibble said.
``That's what happens when you give somebody power like that to use
against Pete Rose.''
</TEXT>
