<HEAD>Secchia Visited By Italy's Ambassador To United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's ambassador to the United
States says Peter Secchia, newly confirmed U.S. ambassador to Italy,
will make a fine diplomat, despite his reputation for making crude
remarks.
   ``I don't think he needs any lessons,'' said Rinaldo Petrignani,
who spent last weekend visiting Secchia at the family's Lake
Michigan cottage in Ferrysburg.
   Secchia, whose nomination was confirmed by the U.S. Senate last
week following a monthlong delay, has been dubbed the ``ambassador
of dirty words'' by the Italian media. Petrignani brushed aside such
attention.
   ``It is clear that the president of the United States, by
choosing Mr. Secchia, chose a person he thought would be just right
as ambassador,'' Petrignani said. ``We are looking forward to having
Secchia in Rome.''
   Secchia, who will be sworn in Wednesday and fly to Rome on
Thursday, said he and Petrignani discussed the political and
economic climate in Italy and what Secchia should expect in his new
job.
   Secchia, a Grand Rapids businessman, is the grandson of Italian
immigrants.
