<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-26 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Secretary of State Says Syria Must `Back Off'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria must withdraw its troops from
Lebanon, Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger said Monday.
   ``The Syrians have to back off,'' Eagleburger said on
Christian-owned Voice of Lebanon radio.
   ``All of the outside parties ought to back off and let the
Lebanese make their own judgment about where their future lies.
There is too much foreign involvement on all sides,'' he said in an
interview recorded in Washington.
   His call for a Syrian withdrawal indicated an apparent U.S.
policy shift, but the State Department said it was not so.
   Eagleburger's comments appeared to reverse his March 16 statement
that Syrian troops restrain warring parties in Lebanon and that
their withdrawal would worsen the situation. He was speaking before
the Senate Foreign Affairs Committee, eight days into the current
round of fighting.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
Monday: ``We have often called for the withdrawal of all foreign
forces in Lebanon.''
   ``The deputy secretary's remarks are entirely in keeping with
U.S. policy. We believe and have often said the Lebanese should be
free to pursue a political process free of threats and coercion,''
Boucher said.
   In Monday's broadcast, Eagleburger said Washington hopes
Lebanon's 14-year civil war can be resolved by an Arab League
committee comprising King Hassan II of Morocco, King Fahd of Saudi
Arabia and Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid. ``We're obviously
very hopeful that the Arab committee can, in fact, bring sense to
the situation, and can convince the Syrians to withdraw plus all
those other foreign parties that have gotten themselves involved in
the tragedy of Lebanon,'' Eagleburger said.
   An Arab League summit gave the special committee six months to
find a settlement in Lebanon.
   The three Arab leaders are to meet Tuesday in the Algerian town
of Oran.
   Their mission was decided by a summit of the 22-member
organization after Syria refused some members' calls for it to
withdraw from Lebanon, where it is the chief power broker. Lebanese
Christians backed by Iraq, Damascus' main Arab foe, charge Syrian
troops have violated a 1976 league peacekeeping mandate by siding
with Moslem militiamen in recent fighting.
   A month after the summit, the committee still has not been able
to enforce a cease-fire between Gen. Michel Aoun's mostly Christian
army of 20,000 and 40,000 Syrian troops in Lebanon.
   The Syrians on Monday fired sporadic salvos of 130mm mortar
shells to maintain their blockade of Christian ports north of Beirut
and prevent Iraqi supplies reaching Aoun.
   Christian gunners retaliated with a barrage of 155mm howitzer
shells on the seaside boulevard of Moslem west Beirut, where several
Syrian batteries are deployed.
   No casualities were reported.
   By police count, 373 people have been killed and 1,460 wounded in
the 14 weeks of bloodshed.
   Also Monday, police said a bomb exploded at a school in the
Syrian-policed mountaintop town of Dhour Shweir, injuring the
principal, a teacher and seven children.
   Eagleburger's statement was broadcast a day after Secretary of
State James A. Baker III sent identical letters to Aoun and rival
Moslem leader Salim Hoss urging them to show restraint to avert
further bloodshed.
   The prestigious An-Nahar newspaper quoted unidentified political
and official sources as saying Syria is bent on overthrowing Aoun by
military, economic or political means.
   But the independent daily said the military option is out because
Syria has been notified that ``it was impermissible to invade
(Christian) east Beirut.'' It did not say who gave the order.
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' to free Lebanon of
Syrian domination.
</TEXT>
