<DOCNO> AP890626-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OilSpill-Bush     06-26 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Bush,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fitzwater Says Latest Spills Show Pervasiveness of Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's spokesman accused the oil
industry Monday of moving too slowly on oil-spill cleanup technology
and said three weekend spills highlight ``the pervasiveness of the
problem.''
   But presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said that Bush
would not take any direct steps to respond to the weekend spills in
Rhode Island, Delaware and Texas.
   ``The White House does not intend to assume an operational role
in oil spills,'' he said. ``We think the Coast Guard is fully able
and adequate to carry out these responsiblities.''
   Fitzwater also ruled out a moratorium on new oil drilling and
exploration.
   ``We have to go ahead with exploration and development of natural
resources. We have to have petroleum products for meeting our energy
needs,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said a ``commanding aspect'' of the latest spills was
to show `the pervasiveness of the problem.'' He said they
underscored the need for legislation to better define tanker owners'
liabilities.
   He cited legislation proposed by the administration on May 11 to
give tanker owners ``first level of responsibility'' for paying
cleanup costs.
   Under the administration bill, tanker owners would be
automatically liable for damages from $5 million to $78 million,
depending on the extent of the spill and the size of the ship.
   A federal fund would be set up to pay cleanup costs over the $78
million ceiling, to be financed by a fee of 1.3 cents on every
barrel of domestic as well as imported oil.
   Fitzwater said that the Coast Guard last year received reports of
7,500 oil spills, 200 of which required a federal takeover of
cleanup operations.
   ``We feel the industry could do more ... both individual
companies and the industry as a whole, particularly in the area of
research into better techniques for dealing with oil spills,''
Fitzwater said.
   ``Presumably we have had a lot of experience with oil spills. We
know that they are going to occur. We have in place systems to deal
with them. But we also know, from recent experience, that there are
problems that have to be corrected,'' he added.
   He said the ``most obvious'' shortcoming is the industry's
research and development into better ways to disperse oil spills.
   ``We also find that research has not produced dispersants the way
it should. That work is going forward. The sense of urgency I
believe is there in the Congress (and) in the administration. So
there's no need to delay development of energy resources, but there
is a need to move quickly and effectively on better techniques in
dealing with oil spills.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     06-26 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Romania,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Romania Pulling Down Fence With Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania is pulling down a wire fence it
recently built on its border with Hungary, MTI state news agency
reported.
   There was no word from Romania on the fence, which was criticized
by the Soviet Union at a human rights conference last week in Paris.
   The barrier was erected along a 188-mile section of the Oroshaza
district in southeastern Hungary apparently to stop Romanians from
crossing into Hungary illegally.
   ``The `wire curtain' and the concrete pillars were almost
completely removed from Saturday to Monday,'' MTI said Monday.
   Hungarian Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, on a visit to Austria,
said Monday, ``I haven't heard it yet, but the news delights me.''
   Horn called for Romania to re-establish an autonomous region to
safeguard ethnic and cultural rights of the 1.7 million-member
Hungarian minority.
   ``The situation is gradually deteriorating, it is disastrous,''
he said at a lecture on Hungarian foreign policy. ``But we haven't
given up hope for changes.''
   MTI said the dismantling of the fence was announced by Col. Janos
Pal, commander of Hungarian frontier guards in Oroshaza.
   During the first five months of this year, 3,231 Romanians
crossed illegally into Hungary, Hungarian officials said.
   About 30,000 Romanians, most ethnic Hungarians, have fled to
Hungary in recent years seeking refuge from chronic hardships and
discrimination under President Nicolae Ceausescu.
   In a June 20 dispatch, MTI denied a Western report that Romania
was building a wall along the border, but said a wire fence 6{ feet
to 8\ feet high was being erected and has been completed along 90
percent of the border.
   A subsequent MTI report said Romanian authorities had piled sand
on roads leading to the border, apparently to block traffic, and
border guards had noticed a kind of steel ``car trap.''
   MTI said Romania started building the fence 1{ years ago, but the
pace of construction was speeded up in March.
   Romania came under bitter attack for flouting human rights of
dissidents and ethnic minorities, including Hungarian Magyars,
during the month-long Paris meeting.
   Even the Soviet Union criticized its ally.
   ``The Helsinki Final Act makes no mention of a barbed wall,''
said chief Soviet delegate Yuri Kashlev. ``If we were the Romanians,
we wouldn't have done it.''
   Relations between Hungary and Romania have deteriorated. As
communist officials in Budapest prepare to embrace mutliparty
democracy and free elections next year, Ceausescu's hard-line
government plans to raze thousands of villages, including hundreds
of ethnic Hungarian communities, to force assimilation.
   Recently, Romania has protested alleged anti-Romanian statements
made during the June 16 public funeral of Imre Nagy, the executed
leader of the 1956 uprising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
