<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RhodeIsland-OilSpill     06-26 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rhode Island-Oil Spill,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mopping Up Continues As Officials Eye Aftermath</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spills Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental experts said Monday most of
the estimated 420,000 gallons of oil spilled into the ocean no
longer threatened the shore, and federal officials began a criminal
investigation.
   Only a few small patches of oil could be seen in Rhode Island
Sound and along the state's shoreline, state and federal officials
said.
   ``The worst is over,'' said Debbie Payton, an oceanographer with
the Natonal Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration. ``There's
not going to be any more shoreline impacts like there were at the
beginning. I'm confident of that.''
   She estimated no more than 5 percent of the highly toxic oil
spilled from the tanker World Prodigy remained floating on the
water. The tanker, loaded with nearly 8 million gallons, went
aground Friday on Brenton Reef at the mouth of Narragansett Bay. The
Coast Guard estimated 420,000 gallons spilled.
   There had been some reports of lobsters killed and several small
birds found dead, but officials said those did not appear to be
widespread.
   ``My feeling is that people in Rhode Island, scientists included,
are being maybe a bit upbeat,'' warned William Sargent, director of
the coastlines project at the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute in
Massachusetts.
   Agents from the FBI and three other state and federal agencies
met with Justice Department attorneys to begin their investigation
into the accident, said U.S. Attorney Lincoln Almond.
   ``The problem that we have is that some of the information the
Coast Guard has has been immunized and cannot be used by us,''
Almond said.
   The Coast Guard has been gathering material for a joint
investigation with the National Transportation Safety Board that
will open Tuesday in Providence, said Capt. Eric Williams of the
Coast Guard's marine safety office.
   Because some of that information must be provided by law to the
Coast Guard, it cannot be used in a criminal investigation, Almond
said. Among the statements in question was an admission by the
ship's Greek master that he mistakenly brought the 533-foot vessel
into the harbor without a pilot.
   Criminal charges could be filed for negligent operation of a
vessel or under the Clean Water or Refuse acts, Almond said. Each is
a misdemeanor with a maximum jail term of one year, but the Clean
Act violation could mean a fine of double the damages against the
ship's owner, Bollard Shipping of Athens, Greece, Almond said.
   State beaches from Jamestown almost to Connecticut remained
closed as a precaution, although eastern beaches were open. A
statewide shellfishing ban remained in effect.
   Conditions were ``much, much better than yesterday,'' said
Stephen G. Morin, state director of groundwater and wetlands, after
he and other officials flew over the area.
   ``I haven't seen it anywhere on the beaches we've flown today,''
he said.
   There was some problem with boaters, who ignored requests to stay
out of the area, dragging oil along in their wake, he said.
   Crews used booms and pads that can absorb up to 50 times their
weight in oil to soak up the remaining contamination, said Michael
Annarummo, deputy director of the state Department of Environmental
Management.
   He said officials had not decided how to dispose of the pads,
which must be handled as hazardous waste.
   Coast Guard Capt. Eric Williams said 72,500 barrels of oil were
left on the ship by mid-morning, of the 195,000 barrels it had been
carrying. He estimated the removal would take a day or two more and
said the ship would not be moved until it was empty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
