<FIRST>r a AM-Scotus-Juvenile-Thumbnails     06-26 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Juvenile-Thumbnails,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missouri, Kentucky Cases Focus of Supreme Court Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Scotus-Juvenile Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are thumbnail sketches of the two cases in which the Supreme
Court ruled Monday that states may impose the death penalty on
murderers who killed when they were 16 or 17.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Missouri: Heath Wilkins</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Heath Wilkins was 16 when he stabbed to death a convenience-store
clerk as she pleaded for her life. His attorneys described a
childhood of abuse, drugs and liquor. His first burglary was at age
7, and at 10 he bought rat poison, tried it on a dog, then put it
into Tylenol capsules for his mother and her boyfriend. She secretly
emptied the capsules, then made Wilkins swallow them.
   In July 1985, Wilkins plotted the robbery of Linda's Liquors and
Deli in Avondale. He told a girlfriend, another friend and Pat
``Bo'' Stevens about the plan; he and Stevens robbed the store while
the others waited nearby. Stevens grabbed Nancy Allen, 26, and
Wilkins stabbed her in the back and chest. As she pleaded for mercy,
he stabbed her in the throat. The robbery netted $450, cigarettes,
rolling papers, cheap wine and peppermint schnapps.
   Stevens pleaded guilty to second-degree murder and was sentenced
to life in prison. The two other accomplices were convicted of
conspiracy to commit first-degree murder; one got probation and the
other was sentenced to 15 years.
   A state judge is to rule July 26 on Wilkins' request for a new
trial based on the argument he was not mentally competent at the
time of the crime.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Kentucky: Kevin Stanford</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Stanford plunged into crime at age 9. He was a drug addict
at 12, and was arrested for robbery, burglary, assault, attempted
rape and other crimes by 17. That's when he raped, robbed and
murdered a gas station attendant.
   Stanford came from Louisville's low-income West End, his
surroundings modest but hardly desperate. He apparently never knew
his father; his mother, a hospital therapist, worked long hours.
Until he was 6, he lived mostly with his near-invalid grandmother.
He quit school after ninth grade.
   On Jan. 7, 1981, Baerbel Poore, 20, was alone at a Cheker Oil
station next to Stanford's apartment, working nights to support an
infant daughter. Stanford and two other teens decided to rob the
station.
   Stanford and David Buchanan, 18, sexually abused and terrorized
Poore in the bathroom while 15-year-old Troy Johnson waited out in a
car. Stanford then forced Poore into her car and drove with her to a
woods, followed by the other two. Stanford gave her a last
cigarette, then shot her twice in the head. The take was 300 cartons
of cigarettes, $143.07, two gallons of gas and a gas can.
   Johnson's case remained in juvenile court and he testified
against Stanford and Buchanan, who were tried together in August
1982. Buchanan did not face the death penalty because he wasn't the
triggerman; he was sentenced to life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
