<FIRST>r w AM-Bolivia-Article     06-26 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia-Article,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Embassy Official Writes of Bolivians as ``Trolls''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The just-departed spokesman at the American
Embassy in Bolivia called Bolivians ``trolls ... short and dark and
strange'' in a fictional story, prompting a State Department review
of the piece Monday.
   Mark Jacobs, author of ``Stone Cowboy on the High Plains,''
published the story in the June editions of the The Atlantic
Monthly. The magazine described him as the information officer and
spokesman at the embassy in La Paz, Bolivia.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher was asked about the
story after the Council on Hemispheric Affairs, a liberal think tank
that studies Latin American issues, drew attention to it in a
statement.
   Boucher said he was unaware of the article, but added: ``I can
assure you we'll go out and buy a copy of the Atlantic this
afternoon.''
   The hero of Jacobs' fictional story, Roger, is a character who
has spent time in a Bolivian jail and is eager to leave the country.
   Jacobs writes: ``(All Bolivians were trolls, Roger had decided a
long time ago. They were short and dark and strange, not like
people, really, but humanlike to a certain extent.)''
   At another point, Jacobs writes that only llamas, alpacas and
trolls could survive in the high altitudes of Bolivia. ``Real people
needed air with something in it their lungs could chew on,'' he
wrote.
   Later, he wrote: ``Something in the way the trolls said that word
was offensive, as if they were the human ones and Americans were
some low breed of dog.''
   Jacobs could not be reached for comment. Bruce Wharton, the press
attache in La Paz, said Jacobs left La Paz last Thursday on home
leave in Florida with relatives. Jacobs has been assigned to
Honduras, where he will assume his post at the embassy in August.
   Wharton said he knew that Jacobs enjoyed his tour in Bolivia and
had no intention of making disparaging remarks about the people. He
did not know whether Jacobs had submitted the story for any
pre-publication review by State Department officials.
   Larry Birns, head of the council, called the written
characterization of the Bolivians ``outrageous.'' He said Jacobs
should be recalled and reassigned to a country outside the
hemisphere for his ``racist and derogatory'' short story.
   Emily Eakin, assistant to the fiction editor at the Atlantic,
said the magazine had received at least two letters to the editor
criticizing the story for ``racial stereotypes.'' But others had
praised the piece, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
