<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Brezhnev     06-26 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brezhnev,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Calls for Brezhnev Medal to be Withdrawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legislator Monday suggested withdrawing the
nation's highest military order from Leonid Brezhnev, the former
Soviet leader awarded the honor for his service in World War II,
Tass reported.
   Supreme Soviet deputy Albert Likhachev said many people see the
decoration as one of Brezhnev's undeserved rewards. Tass, however,
said the legislature was not empowered to revoke the award.
   Brezhnev rose to major general serving as a political officer in
the war and got the jewel-encrusted Order of Victory in 1978, 33
years after the war ended. He died in 1982.
   Stripping him of the honor would further discredit the man now
widely condemned for plunging the economy into crisis and stagnating
the rest of Soviet society. His name has been stripped off cities
and ships, and his relatives have lost some of the benefits given
family members of a Soviet leader.
   In recent years, Brezhnev has been satirized for all the medals
he received, many of which he awarded himself.
   Likhachev spoke when the Supreme Soviet, the nation's first
full-time lawmaking body, convened Monday to confirm Cabinet members
and organize writing bills and ratifying treaties, Tass said.
   These are new powers for the Supreme Soviet, a division of the
larger Congress of People's Deputies that began work May 25.
   In closed hearings, legislative committees rejected at least four
of more than 60 nominees for ministerial and other senior posts. The
fight now moves to the full 542-member body.
   Several deputies have objected to the large number of military
and defense industry representatives on a committee to oversee
defense and the dreaded KGB secret police. But they were told Monday
the experts deliberately were assigned to committees in their area
of professional expertise, Tass said.
   The government daily newspaper Izvestia reported the committee's
hearings will be held behind closed doors, despite calls for more
openness in those areas.
   The chamber approved the composition of its committees after
changes, Tass said without elaborating.
</TEXT>
