<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpillGlance     06-26 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill Glance,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Spills At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spills Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are facts and figures on the status of three
major oil spills.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>RHODE ISLAND:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The estimated 420,000 gallons of oil spilled from a tanker off
Newport on Friday had largely dispersed or evaporated by Monday
morning, officials said. The Greek tanker World Prodigy struck a
reef Friday at mouth of Narragansett Bay. The spill was initially
estimated at up to 1.6 million gallons. The light oil had spread
over an area of almost 30 square miles by late Sunday. An
undetermined number of oil-covered small lobsters and several birds
were found dead.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DELAWARE:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil spilled Saturday when the Uruguayan tanker Presidente Rivera
ran aground in the Delaware River near Claymont, Del., was so heavy
it congealed into large globs in the cool water. An estimated
800,000 gallons of industrial heating oil was unaccounted for,
including an undetermined amount that became mixed with water and
remained in the vessel. Some oil fouled shores on both Delaware and
New Jersey sides of the river, plus some shores upstream in
Pennsylvania, but mostly the globs were too large to wash ashore.
Tanker was refloated Sunday and taken to a refinery dock to be
unloaded.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TEXAS:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A tug-driven barge ruptured when it collided Friday with a cargo
ship in the Houston Ship Channel near La Porte, Texas. Channel
connects Galveston Bay and Houston. Spill of heavy crude oil
estimated at 250,000 gallons. Most of the oil that washed ashore
affected industrial property. Wind and waves concentrated most of
the oil in a small channel and a third or more of the 6,000 barrels
that leaked from the barge had been recovered by Monday.
</TEXT>
