<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LatePayment     06-26 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Late Payment,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Pays $1.6 Million Extra After Insurer Sends Check Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxpayers in this Detroit suburb will
pay an extra $1.6 million because the town's insurance company was
four days late mailing a check to survivors of a man killed in a
1982 police shooting.
   Circuit Judge Thomas Foley doubled the $1.6 million award to the
estate of Benjamin Davis, 36, for the shooting, which led to the
1985 manslaughter conviction of Officer Michael Killian.
   Police in nearby Southgate began chasing Davis after they saw him
apparently commit a traffic violation. Killian joined the chase as
it went through Lincoln Park, and shot Davis to death near Davis'
home in Detroit.
   Lincoln Park, a town of 45,000, and California-based Mission
National Insurance Co. agreed to a $1.6 million settlement in the
shooting.
   The insurer paid $500,000 on time in 1986 but was four days late
with the remaining $1.1 million, City Attorney Edward Zelenak said.
The company is now bankrupt.
   Mayor Robert Heyer said he had no explanation for the late
payment.
   ``I would have been willing to get on a plane and go get the
check if someone would have asked me to,'' said Heyer, who was
police chief at the time of the shooting. ``We thought everything
was taken care of.''
   After the state Supreme Court refused to hear an appeal of
Foley's decision, Foley made the award final May 19. To pay the
award, taxpayers are being assessed about $50 each this year and
about $30 each next year.
   City officials would like to get the extra $1.6 million from the
insurers, but since the company is bankrupt they don't have high
hopes.
   ``The bottom line is, a deal is a deal,'' the mayor said. ``I
think the average citizen will realize this is one of the costs we
have to pay to provide law enforcement.''
</TEXT>
