<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NavyDeath     06-26 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Death,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says No Evidence Of Wrongdoing in 2nd Death At Navy School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressman who spurred an
investigation into the death of a recruit last year at a Navy
training school said Monday there's no sign that a second death
there stemmed from similar problems.
   After an extensive briefing by the chief of Navy training, Rep.
Toby Roth, R-Wis., said he saw no evidence of failed safety
procedures, instructor abuse or a lack of emergency services in the
death Friday at the Naval Training Center in Pensacola, Fla.
   A naval aviation officer candidate, Michael Fedie, 22, of
Altoona, died Friday in shallow water after a training exercise. A
preliminary autopsy showed abnormal brain swelling, and further
tests were under way.
   In March 1988, Airman Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton died during a
different type of exercise.
   ``It is really eerie that this should happen to another young
sailor from Wisconsin at the very same training facility,'' said
Roth.
   Roth had ordered a congressional investigation into the death of
Mirecki, a constituent, after the young man's family raised
questions about the Navy's explanation for the death.
   In the Mirecki case, the General Accounting Office, Congress'
investigative arm, found failures in safety procedures, abuse of
trainees by instructors and a lack of emergency services.
   The probe led to reforms at the school and disciplinary action
against a number of instructors and school administrators.
   A pathologist concluded that Mirecki had an abnormal fear of
being pulled under water and died of heart failure and drowning when
he was forced under water during training.
   Though Fedie is not from Roth's district, Roth has looked into
his death also. He said he had an extensive discussion Monday with
Adm. John Disher, who is chief of Navy training worldwide.
   ``It's clear as a bell the Navy is handling this (death) in an
entirely different way,'' Roth said in an interview in Washington.
   He said Disher ``appears to be on top of the situation, whereas
last year we had a lot of stonewalling.''
   Roth said Fedie was wearing a uniform and normal gear when he
jumped from the 12-foot tower at the training pool for an
abandon-ship exercise. Fedie's father has described him as an
excellent swimmer.
   After Fedie collapsed in shallow water as he was leaving the
pool, safety officers pulled him immediately from the water and
began first aid. An ambulance arrived within four minutes, Roth
said, and a doctor arrived shortly thereafter in a backup ambulance.
   A preliminary autopsy Saturday indicated Fedie died from acute
cerebral edema caused by an abnormal accumulation of fluid, said Kay
Esty, a spokeswoman for the Naval Education and Training Command.
   The Navy has temporarily suspended the abandon-ship exercise
Fedie had just completed when he collapsed and died, Roth said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
