<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Dermota     06-26 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Dermota,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Tenor Is Dead At 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anton Dermota, a celebrated tenor who sang
the operas of Mozart and other composers on the world's best stages,
has died of heart failure, the Vienna State Opera reported. He was
79.
   Dermota, who died Thursday, was born in the Yugoslav republic of
Slovenia and moved to Vienna as a young man. He lived there until
his death.
   Dermota sang in some of the Vienna State Opera's most noted
productions.
   He sang Jacquino in the 1945 premiere of Beethoven's opera
``Fidelio'' while the opera house was still in ruins after heavy
Allied bombing in the last days of World War II.
   Dermota sang the title role in the same opera when the Vienna
State Opera was reopened in November 1955, just six months after
Austria gained postwar independence.
   In a register of names kept at the opera that spans the 1945-80
period, Dermota is mentioned as having sung 50 different opera roles
in works by Verdi, Mozart, Wagner, Richard Strauss and Gottfried von
Einem.
   Dermota's prominence in Vienna and at the Salzburg Festival made
him a much sought-after guest performer on operatic stages around
the world.
</TEXT>
