<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hurt     06-26 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurt,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurt Ordered Employee to Shred Records and Had House Checked for
Bugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Hurt ordered his housekeeper to shred
financial records when the actor learned his former lover was suing
him, the ex-employee testified Monday.
   Former housekeeper Dianna Schiebel's testimony came on the fifth
day of a trial to determine whether Hurt, 39, had a common-law
marriage with Sandra Jennings, the 32-year-old mother of Hurt's son.
   Schiebel said Hurt told her in May 1988, ``Sandy is suing me for
divorce. We have to be very careful from now on in everything we say
and do because Sandy will be looking for information that could hurt
me.''
   ``He told me I had to take the financial records and quietly
destroy them,'' Schiebel said.
   Hurt, sitting at the defense table, lowered his head and ran his
fingers through his thinning blond hair. Jennings sat with her back
turned toward Hurt and stared at Schiebel.
   Jennings' lawyer, A. Richard Golub, asked whether the documents
had been destroyed. Schiebel that they had been shredded.
   ``Did Mr. Hurt own a shredder?''
   ``Yes,'' Schiebel answered just as Frances Jacobs, one of Hurt's
attorneys, objected. The objection was sustained.
   Schiebel said Hurt also worried about electronic eavesdropping.
``He started looking for a company to sweep the house for bugs,''
she said. ``He felt the house was bugged.''
   Jennings, a former dancer with the New York City Ballet, is suing
Hurt for divorce, claiming they have a common-law marriage.
   Jennings wants up to half of everything he's earned for the past
6{ years. Golub says Hurt, who starred in ``Kiss of the Spider
Woman,'' ``Gorky Park,'' ``Body Heat,'' and ``Accidental Tourist,''
is worth about $10 million.
   Jennings bases her common-law marriage claim on four weeks she
spent with Hurt in Beaufort, S.C., where he was filming ``The Big
Chill.'' She says the marriage began Dec. 9, 1982, when the actor
learned he was divorced from actress Mary Beth Hurt. He and Jennings
left the state Jan. 10, 1983.
   South Carolina permits common-law marriages. New York, where the
two lived together nearly all of the time they were together, does
not.
   Schiebel said she met Hurt in May 1987, when he hired her
housekeeping business, Kitchen Witch. She said he often called
Jennings and their son, Alexander Devon Hurt, now 6, ``my family.''
   Earlier Monday, attorney Scott Graber testified that Hurt and
Jennings came to his Beaufort office around Dec. 27, 1982, and
signed a document he considered a premarital agreement.
   Graber said the couple also signed an acknowledgement of
paternity, which he witnessed. He said he did not charge them a fee.
   Hurt has testified he did not recall ever signing a premarital
agreement with Jennings.
   Judge Jacqueline Silberman, who is hearing the non-jury case, has
said she will concern herself mainly with what happened in South
Carolina.
</TEXT>
