<FIRST>r a AM-People-Newman     06-26 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Newman,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects Newman's Bid to Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court on Monday rejected
actor Paul Newman's bid to appeal a judge's refusal to dismiss a
lawsuit brought by a man claiming he was promised a percentage of
the actor's food company.
   The lawsuit, filed by Westport delicatessen owner Julius Gold,
resulted in an 18-day trial that ended in mistrial after it was
determined that the jury received information not introduced as
evidence.
   The judge then refused Newman's request to dismiss the lawsuit.
Newman went to the Appellate Court, which ruled Newman could not
appeal because there had been no jury verdict.
   The actor's lawyers then went to the Supreme Court, which Monday
affirmed the Appellate Court ruling.
   The action could set the stage for a second trial, although
lawyers in the case could not be reached immediately by telephone
for comment.
   Gold claims he was promised an 8 percent share of Newman's Own.
Newman, who donates all proceeds from the company to charity, denies
making such a promise.
   The company distributes salad dressing, spaghetti sauce, lemonade
and popcorn.
</TEXT>
