<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Sisulu     06-26 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Sisulu,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Activist Seeks More Sanctions Against South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albertina Sisulu, the South African
anti-apartheid activist invited to visit by President Bush, said
Monday she favors additional international sanctions against her
country's white government.
   Mrs. Sisulu said she views the invitation by Bush as a
breakthrough that might portend a more active U.S. role in bringing
about negotiations between South Africa's black majority and its
government. He invited her last month after meeting with three other
anti-apartheid leaders visiting the United States.
   Mrs. Sisulu, 71, whose family has come to symbolize the fight
against racial segregation in South Africa, meets with Bush and
State Department officials later this week. This is the first time
she has been allowed to leave South Africa.
   Because she was invited by Bush, Mrs. Sisulu told reporters, she
did not encounter difficulties getting a passport. But the document
only allows her to travel to the United States and is only valid for
31 days, she added.
   Mrs. Sisulu, a nurse, is one of three joint presidents of the
United Democratic Front, treasurer of the Women's League of the
outlawed African National Congress and a founder of the Federation
of South African Women. Her husband, Walter Sisulu, has been serving
a life sentence since 1964 for being one of the founders of the ANC,
along with its jailed leader, Nelson Mandela.
   Two of Mrs. Sisulu's five children have fled into exile to avoid
imprisonment, and she served various jail terms and has been under
house arrest and other government restrictions for 18 years.
   Mrs. Sisulu declined to say what she would tell Bush, but said
that ``we would like the outside world to help us with comprehensive
and mandatory sanctions'' in order to pressure the government.
   President Reagan imposed limited economic sanctions against South
Africa in 1986 after his veto was overriden by Congress. Efforts by
liberal Democrats in Congress to broaden the sanctions have so far
failed.
   Bush, while reluctant to support additional sanctions, has
endorsed a more active U.S. role in bringing about negotiations to
end the apartheid system of segregation and grant political rights
to blacks.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is scheduled to meet next
month in Washington with F.W. de Klerk, who is expected to assume
his country's presidency later this year and will be the first South
African government leader on an official visit here in 30 years.
   Mrs. Sisulu said that despite his promise to enact political
reform and end the domination of 28 million blacks by 5 million
whites, ``we see no change with de Klerk.'' His predecessor,
President P.W. Botha, made similar promises and failed to fulfill
them, she added.
   De Klerk should legalize the ANC and return its leaders from
exile so he can negotiate with them, she said.
   Mrs. Sisulu praised former U.S. Ambassador Edward Perkins, the
first American black to hold that job, saying he had helped obtain
the release of South African children from jail. ``We are sorry to
lose him,'' she said. Perkins returned here recently to head the
Foreign Service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1711EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina     06-26 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Menem's Conservative Proposals Spark Dissent in Peronist Ranks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Carlos Menem, who
has translated the radical slogans of his Peronist campaign into
conservative proposals in the face of economic chaos, said Monday he
would fight for his program.
   He appealed to the Peronist Party for support, but said, ``I am
ready for an internal battle'' if necessary.
   ``My political life has not been a bed of roses,'' Menem, who is
to take office July 8, said in an interview with Radio Mitre. ``I've
had to take roads full of rubble and thorns, but when there is
firmness, capacity and a bit of audacity, things turn out well.''
   The 58-year-old provincial governor was elected May 14 with the
support of organized labor and the working poor. The Peronists and
their allies also won control of the legislature.
   Argentines expected a government that would spur employment,
continue the government's role in the economy and improve public
services without raising their cost.
   As a candidate, Menem promised huge pay increases and ``work,
work and more work.'' He criticized increases in utility rates,
hinted at suspending payments on the $60 billion foreign debt and
opposed efforts to sell inefficient state-owned companies to private
investors.
   As president-elect, he included three conservative non-Peronists
in his eight-member Cabinet and picked an economic team that
proposes large increases in utility rates, partial sale of the state
telephone and oil companies and a new currency.
   An austerity program being devised to combat triple-digit
inflation, recession and a chronic budget deficit will be
``extremely hard,'' he said last weekend.
   Menem was asked on Friday how Argentines could afford higher
gasoline prices.
   ``Normally, workers don't have their own cars,'' he replied.
``Those who have cars and can't afford gas will have to put them
away and buy a bicycle. ... In China and other parts of the world,
they ride bikes. It's good for your health.''
   Argentines were jolted by the statement. They consider car
ownership an achievable goal, if no longer a right, along with home
ownership and annual vacations.
   The Peronist Party and its backbone, the 4 million-member General
Labor Confederation, have accepted Menem's decisions so far, but
some party and union leaders are upset.
   Saul Ubaldini, the labor coalition's secretary-general, organized
13 general strikes against President Raul Alfonsin. Ubaldini
rejected Menem's offer of foreign diplomatic post, which was seen as
an attempt to get the labor leader out of the way.
   Menem made the offer public and further undercut Ubaldini by
rejecting his demand that Argentina halt payments on the foreign
debt.
   Other clashes are possible on the minimum wage, maintenance of
collective bargaining agreements and the right to strike.
   Jorge Triaca, Menem's designated labor minister, recently asked
Ubaldini for a pledge not to call a general strike for two years.
Ubaldini refused.
   When Alfonsin's government agreed last week to raise the monthly
minimum wage by 130 percent to 20,000 australs (about $44), Menem's
transition team expressed concern about where the money would come
from.
   Alfonsin's six-year term ends Dec. 10 under the constitution, but
he said two weeks ago he would step down early because he could not
stabilize the economy.
   Inflation was 78.5 percent in May and is almost certain to be
higher for June. Monthly interest rates surpassed 200 percent last
week.
   Construction in Buenos Aires has virtually halted. Auto,
electronics and other assembly lines have partially shut down.
Hospitals and pharmacies are short on medical supplies and La
Serenisima, one of the largest dairies, has filed for bankruptcy.
   No payments have been made on the foreign debt since last year,
and Argentina is about $4 billion in arrears. The Central Bank has
only about $140 million in foreign reserves, Menem said, and new
loans from abroad are unlikely.
   The budget deficit and unemployment are growing. Real wages have
shrunk by at least 30 percent so far this year.
   Menem describes the Argentina he will inherit as ``poisoned,
calamitous and chaotic,'' and says he has fashioned a government of
national unity to improve it.
   ``Those who criticized me most severely in the past now
understand that they were wrong,'' he said Monday.
   ``I hope my supporters who are now raising their voices finally
understand that Menem is not working'' just for the 6 million who
voted for him, ``but has to govern the 30 million'' citizens of
Argentina, he declared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
