<DOCNO> AP890626-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Drugs     06-26 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Drugs,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Tribunal Meets For Second Day In Drug Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, CUBA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decorated general charged with betraying
the ideals of the Cuban revolution by trafficking in cocaine, ivory
and diamonds appeared for a second day Monday before a military
honor tribunal.
   The court of 47 top-ranking officers was expected to conclude
Monday with a recommendation for a court-martial, Foreign Ministry
officials said on condition of anonymity.
   They said the court-martial of Division Gen. Arnalfo Ochoa might
begin as soon as Tuesday.
   The official Cuban news agency, Prensa Latina, said Ochoa
admitted he was guilty of the charges Sunday during the tribunal's
first session. In a statement, Ochoa said he ``accepted
responsibility'' for his actions, the agency said.
   Defense Minister Gen. Raul Castro, brother of President Fidel
Castro, told the tribunal Sunday that Ochoa's punishment should
``set an example.''
   Some Foreign Ministry officials interpreted this to mean Ochoa
might face a firing squad. But others speculated Ochoa might be
spared because of his decorated combat service, his long friendship
with Gen. Castro and his rank, one of the highest in the
Revolutionary Armed Forces.
   Ochoa is accused of being the ringleader of military and Interior
Ministry officials who collaborated with the Medellin cartel, the
world's largest cocaine-smuggling operation, based in Colombia. He
is also accused of smuggling ivory and diamonds.
   Gen. Castro accused Ochoa of trying to build his own power base,
a clique beholdened by lavish gifts. His comments were interpreted
to mean that Ochoa may have become a threat to the established order
run by the Castro brothers since the Marxist revolution in 1959.
   Gen. Castro said that after Ochoa returned from Angola last year,
he began spreading lavish gifts around ``in a delirous exercise of
self-complacency.''
   He said Ochoa was trying to create ``an image and ties of
personal gratitude with an absolute lack of principle and ethics.''
   The government has mounted an intensive public relations campaign
against Ochoa, describing his alleged corruption in extraordinary
detail in Granma, the official newspaper of the Cuban Communist
Party.
   Granma published the entire text of Gen. Castro's remarks to the
tribunal on its front page on Monday.
   Havana residents have mobbed news vendors since the scandal broke
on Thursday, buying up every available copy of Granma minutes after
it hits the streets.
   In a break from its usual reticence to report on internal
affairs, Prensa Latina has distributed extensive reports on the drug
scandal.
   Cuban televison showed film from the closed tribunal on Sunday
night, and government radio has run scores of interviews with
soldiers and officers who professed outrage at Ochoa for betraying
the high moral stands of the revolution and the armed forces.
   Ochoa was decorated for his service as a field commander in
Angola in 1987 and 1988 and is one of only five officers ever
awarded the Hero of the Republic of Cuba.
   Gen. Castro on Sunday told the tribunal that Ochoa's actions were
``a stab in the back to the fatherland.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
