<DOCNO> AP890626-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WorldBank-China     06-26 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Bank-China,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank to Consult China on Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank said Monday it is deferring
consideration of $780 million in loans to China which have been
stalled since troops cleared demonstrators for democracy from
Tiananmen Square in Beijing.
   The timing of future decisions will be reviewed in consultation
with Chinese authorities, the bank said.
   On June 8, four days after the Army attacked the square, Bank
President Barber Conable, an American, withheld the first of the
loans from consideration by the bank's Board of Executive Directors.
   The $780 million represents the sum of several loans since then
that were to have been considered by the directors this month.
   The directors represent the 151 countries that own the bank, the
major source of aid money to Third World countries. The 22 directors
include one Chinese and one American.
   Bank officials explained that Conable's action was intended to
leave time to determine whether disturbances would prevent carrying
out the terms of existing loans to China.
   The bank is supposed to take only economic considerations into
account in making its loans, and it is continuing to disburse funds
for loans to China that have already been approved.
   One June 20 President Bush said he would ask the bank to postpone
new loans.
   The bank had been scheduled to lend a total of $2 billion to $2.5
billion to China in the year that ends on Friday. The $780 million
was part of that total.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
