<FIRST>u w AM-Spills-CoastGuard     06-26 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spills-Coast Guard,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Facing Four Major Spills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The same pumps used to evacuate oil from the
Exxon Valdez in Alaska were clearing out the World Prodigy off Rhode
Island Monday as the Coast Guard found itself dealing with four
major oil spills.
   Officials said a response system that is under review as a result
of the March 24 Alaskan spill appears to be working well in handling
smaller oil spills in Rhode Island, Delaware and Texas.
   No equipment or personnel had to be moved from Alaska for the
latest spills, said David Pascoe, chief of the Coast Guard's
environmental response branch. Exxon is paying thousands of workers
to clean up oil in the 10-million-gallon Alaskan spill.
   In each of the latest spills, local Coast Guard officials were
overseeing the cleanup, said Pascoe.
   But a strike force used in Alaska and based in Alabama was at
work with its pumping equipment in Rhode Island's Narragansett Bay
where the World Prodigy ran aground Friday and spilled 420,000
gallons of processed heating oil, Pascoe said. The high-velocity
pumps purged the Exxon Valdez of its remaining 40 million gallons of
oil a few days after it ran aground in Prince William Sound.
   The World Prodigy retained about 6 million gallons, which was
being pumped into barges.
   Delaware National Guardsmen and private contractor employees were
scooping up blobs of oil from an estimated 800,000-gallon spill from
a Uraguayan tanker Saturday in the Delaware River. But Coast Guard
officials said shoreline damage downriver in Delaware, Pennsylvania
nd New Jersey was almost nonexistent because the oil was thick and
was not washing up on the shore.
   In Texas, the Coast Guard was investigating a collision Friday
between the tanker Rachel-B and a barge owned by Coastal Towing Co.
of Houston. Most of the area affected by that spill was industrial.
   Pascoe said it was too early for the Alaskan spill to have much
impact on the way the Coast Guard or other agencies respond to
spills. But he noted that Congress is considering several measures
to deal with spills in the wake of the Alaskan disaster, and the oil
industry last week announced its own plans for a coordinated
response.
   Coast Guard units throughout the country also are conducting a
six-month review of their contingency plans for oil spills. The
review is to be completed in the fall.
   Pascoe said the fact the reviews are under way may have
heightened the response of officials to the latest spills, but he
said there have been no policy or operational changes since the
Alaskan spill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
