<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-DeathReax     06-26 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Death Reax,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foes Call Death Penalty Ruling `Tragic'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents called Monday's Supreme Court
decisions upholding the death penalty for retarded killers and some
teen-age murderers appalling and tragic, but law enforcement
officials hailed the rulings as a victory in the fight against
violent crime.
   ``It is quite appalling that the Supreme Court would read the
Constitution ... as not banning the execution of children,'' said
Henry Schwarzschild of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``To let society hang children is medieval and barbaric.''
   However, Kentucky Attorney General Fred Cowan said he found the
decisions on juvenile killers gratifying.
   ``In an era of growing concern over the increase and seriousness
of violent crime, the court's decision ... reaffirms that state
legislators, the juvenile justice system and local juries _ not the
federal courts _ can and should decide upon the proper age to impose
the death penalty,'' Cowan said.
   ``Clearly, some 16- and 17-year-olds in our society are fully
mature and capable of plotting and carrying out the most heinous of
crimes,'' he said. ``The court has obviously responded to society's
demand to hold youths who are mature enough to commit horrible
crimes responsible for their actions.''
   The court said the Constitution's ban on ``cruel and unusual
punishment'' does not prohibit the death penalty for murderers as
young as 16, or for retarded adults with the reasoning capacity of
young children.
   The court upheld the death sentences of a Kentucky murderer who
was 17 when he killed and a Missouri killer who was 16, as well as a
Texas killer who has the mental capacity of a 7-year-old.
   ``It now falls to state legislatures to assure that no individual
with this disability is ever put to death in this country,'' said
James Ellis, president of the American Association on Mental
Retardation. ``The execution of any such person would represent a
tragic injustice.''
   Schwarzschild said ``the execution of people who are not fully
responsible for their acts is an atrocity.''
   American Bar Association President Robert Raven said his
organization was gravely concerned about the court's decision on
juvenile killers.
   ``To give up, with ultimate finality, upon a person even before
they emerge from childhood ... is squarely in opposition to the
fundamental premises of an enlightened juvenile justice system,''
Raven said.
   But Missouri Attorney General William Webster, whose office
successfully argued in favor of letting states impose the death
penalty on murderers who committed their crimes while 16 or 17, took
issue with such concerns.
   ``I think that's hogwash,'' Webster said. ``There's a lot of
people that say it's going to open the door. That's ludicrous.''
</TEXT>
