<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Ex-Dems     06-26 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Ex-Dems,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Ex-Democrats ``the Switch Is On'' to the Republican Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told five dozen ex-Democrats at
a party Monday for new Republican officials that ``the switch is
on'' to the GOP while the Democratic Party is moving ``to the left
and out of the mainstream.''
   The officials got handshakes from Bush, duly recorded by a White
House photographer, as part of a celebration that Lee Atwater, the
GOP chairman, called his ``proudest single moment'' in office.
   Bush looked at the state legislators, aldermen, judges, sheriffs
and other officeholders who had crossed political lines and
pronounced himself well pleased.
   ``The switch is on to the party in sync with the American
principles,'' said Bush. ``The switch is on to the Republican
Party.''
   On this sweltering afternoon, Bush was having none of the
bipartisanship, the ``extended hand,'' that he so often stresses in
dealings with the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   It was back to the hard-hitting, anti-liberalism he successfully
hammered Democratic presidential nominee Michael S. Dukakis with in
last year's campaign.
   ``People say the Republican Party is on the move. ... That's
true. We're moving in the right direction. But the Democratic Party
is on the move, too, to the left and out of the mainstream,'' Bush
said.
   He quoted ``the greatest former Democrat of them all,'' Ronald
Reagan, who has said that ``I didn't leave the Democratic Party. The
Democratic Party left me.''
   Rep. Bill Grant of Florida, the congressman who announced his
switch to the GOP at the White House in February, told the others:
``You didn't come here because it was an easy road. I know you went
through period of great self-doubt, ambivalence even before you
changed your party registration.''
   ``You're tough,'' he said. ``You're being accused of being a
traitor, turncoat, accused of betraying the voters by leaving the
Democratic Party,'' he added.
   Atwater said that ``this is a great day for our party. We've had
118 elected officials and party officials switch from the Democratic
Party to our party since my chairmanship began,'' while ``I know of
no single example of a Republican Party official or elected official
who has switched the other way.''
   All but a handful of the switchers were from the South, and most
made their move this spring.
   Charles Evers, outgoing longtime mayor of Fayette, Miss., and
brother of civil rights martyr Medgar Evers, said he switched
because ``I don't like to be with losers. The Democratic Party is a
loser'' and it ``took us for granted.''
</TEXT>
