<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     06-26 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savimbi Says Cease-Fire Holding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMBA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITA rebel leader Jonas Savimbi appeared
before thousands of cheering supporters Monday and said the
cease-fire is holding in the civil war and that more peace talks are
planned this week.
   Savimbi said at his bush headquarters in southeastern Angola that
he believes a national unity government can be established by the
end of the year, although he set no firm date.
   ``I am confident the negotiations will bear fruit,'' he said of
talks planned this week in Kinshasa, Zaire, between the
Western-backed UNITA guerrilla movement and the Marxist government
of Angola.
   ``The Angolan people want peace ... and the UNITA delegation is
prepared to be flexible,'' he said.
   Savimbi denied reports that he consented to go into foreign
exile. He said he will remain in his homeland as leader of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, known by its
Portuguese acronym, UNITA.
   ``A person goes into exile after he's been defeated,'' he said.
``I plan to stay right here.''
    Thousands of rebel soldiers and civilian supporters sang, danced
and waved red-and-green paper replicas of the guerrilla flag at a
parade to celebrate the cease-fire, declared Thursday at a 20-nation
African summit in Gbadolite, Zaire.
   ``The spirit of the cease-fire can be considered as holding,''
Savimbi said. He said isolated skirmishes could break out due to the
difficulty of contacting all combatants, but he said he thinks the
truce will last.
   The summit was the first meeting between Savimbi and President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos since the battle for power broke out in 1975
shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal.
   The guerrilla movement controls areas in southeastern Angola
occupied by up to 3 million of the country's 9 million people.
   Savimbi and dos Santos sealed the accord with a handshake and
agreed to more talks.
   Since the handshake, Angola radio has referred to Savimbi as
``UNITA president,'' rather than its previous description of him as
a ``traitor'' and ``bandit leader.''
   Savimbi, meanwhile, said the rebel radio now refers to dos Santos
as ``president'' rather than ``caudillo,'' the Portuguese word for
``tyrant'' or ``dictator.''
   Savimbi praised dos Santos for his ``bravery'' in agreeing to the
talks with UNITA. ``I want President dos Santos to succeed,''
Savimbi said. ``I know he needs time.''
   Savimbi said he expected talks between the two sides in Zaire and
possibly another African summit to review the process in August or
September.
   The Angolan government said during the weekend that the
cease-fire was holding.
   UNITA's chief of intelligence, Gen. Wambu Chindondo, said the
rebels declared a halt to offensives in February and that the
guerrilla movement had no difficulty abiding by the cease-fire. He
said the combined Angolan-Cuban forces appeared to be preparing for
attacks but there were no major battles in recent weeks.
   The Angolan civil war has claimed tens of thousands of lives, and
involved several foreign governments including the United States,
the Soviet Union, South Africa and Cuba.
   In a dispatch from Luanda, the Portuguese news agency Lusa quoted
unidentified diplomatic and military sources as saying the United
States pressured Savimbi to attend the Gbadolite summit and accept
the Angolan peace plan.
   According to Lusa, the sources said Savimbi at first refused
because of ``internal discord'' within UNITA. Zaire President Mobutu
Sese Seko was ``obliged to contact Washington and Pretoria, in order
to ensure the success of the summit.''
   The cease-fire follows U.S.-brokered regional peace accords
Angola signed in New York in December with Cuba and South Africa.
   Under the accords, South Africa agreed to allow Angola's southern
neighbor, Namibia, independence under a U.N. plan and halt aid to
Savimbi's guerrillas. In exchange, Cuba agreed to a phased
withdrawal of its estimated 50,000 troops backing dos Santos'
government. UNITA was not party to the agreement.
</TEXT>
