<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     06-26 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Member of New Collective Leadership Pledges `Unambiguous Reform'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, HUNGARY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rezsoe Nyers said Monday he and the
other three members of the Communist Party's new collective
leadership will work together for ``unambiguous reform.''
   Nyers, the new party chairman, said the four leaders chosen over
the weekend have equal responsibility, but in matters of party
policy he is ``first among equals.''
   Creation of the four-man presidium by the Central Committee
appears to strengthen the reform wing and limit the power of Karoly
Grosz, the party general secretary, who also is a member.
   Grosz, who replaced longtime party chief Janos Kadar 13 months
ago, has resisted numerous demands from reformers that he resign.
   Also on the new leadership team are Imre Pozsgay, the party's
leading reformer, and reform-minded Premier Miklos Nemeth.
   Nyers, Pozsgay and Nemeth insisted at a news conference Monday
that each of the four had equal power.
   ``It is not a mathematical formula of three plus one,'' Nyers
said in a clear reference to the reformers and Grosz. ``It is not a
question of where we've been, but where we are going. The party
wishes to become a more unambiguous reform party.''
   He said the party had chosen to dissociate itself from
``extremes.''
   Pozsgay said: ``A real compromise was achieved. The important
matter is the unity of views, and not the differences.''
   He said peaceful transition to ``democratic socialism'' and a
multiparty system should not lead to a ``power vacuum.''
   ``A country should not run loose,'' Pozsgay declared. ``It is
important to govern.''
   Prominent members have expressed concern that a split might cause
the party to disintegrate. Pozsgay has said repeatedly that none of
the political groups springing up in Hungary is ready to assume
power.
   Nemeth said, ``It would be wrong to define unity by the former
criteria,'' under which the leadership presented a unifed platform.
``Everyone is a boss in some way'' in the new presidium, he said.
   As Nyers explained it, Grosz would be responsible for the entire
party apparatus and Nyers, the chairman, would handle the party's
domestic and foreign relations.
   Pozsgay has been proposed as the party candidate for president of
Hungary when the post is created. The new presidency would have far
greater powers than the current ceremonial office.
   In the new leadership ``everyone supports reform,'' Grosz told
the news conference, with debate centering on the type of reform and
the pace at which it should occur.
</TEXT>
