<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov     06-26 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Urges Cut in Soviet Army To Promote Disarmament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIK A. WOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident Andrei D. Sakharov said
Monday that trimming the Soviet military and halving enlisted men's
service time would have ``a colossal effect for world disarmament.''
   Sakharov said the number of Soviet army officers should be
reduced at a slower rate ``with the view of setting up an
all-professional army.''
   He told reporters at the Nobel Institute that arms reduction
should be Moscow's major foreign policy priority.
   The institute is home of the committee that awarded him the 1975
Nobel Peace Prize. Sakharov, 68, arrived from London on Sunday for
his first visit here since winning the prize for his human rights
activities.
   Sakharov said the Soviets were being ``pragmatic'' in their
guarded response to the Beijing government's crushing of the Chinese
democracy movement and the death sentences for Chinese students.
   He pulled a paper from his pocket that he said was a telegram he
sent to world leaders. It said, ``Now is not the time for cautious,
pragmatic reactions.''
   Sakharov said that despite the Kremlin's removal of its last
troops in Afghanistan in February, ``the Soviet Union still has
considerable influence in Afghanistan and ought to reduce it.''
   He spent eight years in internal exile in Gorky for attacking the
mass Soviet military intervention in Afghanistan in late 1979.
   Sakharov, a renowed physicist who helped develop Soviet nuclear
capability, said he favors continued use of nuclear energy, but
recommended that power plants be built underground.
   Sakharov and his wife, Yelena Bonner, were invited by the
Oslo-based Norwegian Research Council for Science and the
Humanities; the Nobel Committee and Michelsen Institute for Science
and Intellectual Freedom in Bergen.
   Soviet authorities would not let him come to Oslo to accept the
1975 Nobel prize and Ms. Bonner received it on his behalf.
   ``She came home full of warm feelings for Norway. Now I'm
extremely happy to be in this house which has so often been in my
thoughts,'' Sahkarov said.
   He is to meet Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland and Foreign
Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg. He also will address scientists,
visit research institutes and attend a human rights seminar.
   The Sakharovs earlier visited the Netherlands and Britain and
will proceed to Switzerland from Norway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
