<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   06-26 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0661,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Says Deportations Can Help Put Down Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD first reference to Meridor.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The justice minister Monday said Israel should
deport more Palestinians to help crush the revolt in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Dan Meridor's suggestion is among tougher measures to handle the
18-month uprising proposed by Israeli officials and criticized by
the United States and human rights organizations.
   ``I think deportation is serious but must be used, I would say
perhaps even more that what has been done until now,'' Meridor told
army radio.
   ``I think it's an effective punishment when we have appropriate
evidence,'' he said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin has recommended speeding up
deportation procedures as well as demolishing more homes of
Palestinians suspected of anti-Israeli activities and lengthening
the term security suspects can be detained without trial from six
months to one year.
   Washington and human rights organizations say all three methods
ignore international conventions on the treatment of people in
occupied lands and violate due process of law because suspects have
no chance to go to court.
   The justice and defense ministries Sunday set up a joint
committee to devise tougher measures to put down the uprising.
   Meridor told the radio about 50 Palestinians have been deported
since the start of the uprising and nearly 300 houses have been
demolished or sealed.
   Also Monday, the body of a woman suspected of cooperating with
Israeli authorities was found in the West Bank city of Nablus, Arab
reports said. She had been beaten to death, they said.
   Palestinians said Sabah Khadi Kanaan, 30, had been accused of
collaborating with Israel's secret police, but an army spokesman
said police believe the killing was criminal.
   Ms. Kanaan was the 68th suspected collaborator killed by
Palestinians since the uprising began in December 1987. The unrest
has killed 536 Palestinians and 23 Israelis.
   A suspected collaborator killed Sunday initially was identified
by Arab reporters as Nidal Salhab, 21, but police Monday said
Salhab's father reported his son was alive. The victim's head had
been crushed, and police said they still are trying to determine his
identity.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, said Israel must present
a united front on its peace plan.
   ``Though it may be difficult and painful, Israel must declare and
demonstrate to one and all, friendly and unfriendly, that she is not
divided and that her mission of peace is sincere and real,'' Inouye
said, speaking at a Hebrew University graduation ceremony.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has proposed holding elections in
the occupied lands to select Palestinian representatives to open
negotiations on an interim peace agreement with Israel.
   Hard-liners in his right-wing Likud bloc oppose the plan, saying
it could lead to formation of a Palestinian state.
   Inouye also said the United States should stand behind Israel.
   ``This is a time of testing for America and Israel, testing
whether we are prepared to take this important step in the pathways
of peace, and we must not fail,'' Inouye said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
