<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Poland     06-26 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Poland,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Recess; Government Refuses Comment on Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recess was reported Monday in talks
with Poland aimed at ending mistrust rooted in the German invasion
that began World War II, but the government would not say whether
progress had been made.
   Negotiations began six months ago on an exchange of West German
economic aid to communist Poland Polish recognition of its German
minority. Agreement would play a symbolic role in easing relations.
   A West German government spokesman, who demanded anonymity,
confirmed the latest round had ended, but said ``we cannot release
details at this time.'' He refused to say whether agreement was near
on a visit to Warsaw this year by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   West German officials had hoped the latest talks would open the
way for a visit and presage reconciliation between the two countries.
   Negotiations ``are to be taken up again soon'' but he did not
know whether a date had been set, the spokesman said.
   Horst Teltschik, one of Kohl's main advisers, met in Bonn for
most of the day with Ernest Kucza, head of the foreign affairs
department of the Polish Communist Party Central Committee.
   Suedwestfunk radio said ``the talks were broken off'' and ``no
new date has yet been set'' for resumption.
   Lack of progress in relations with Poland has been a foreign
policy disappointment for Kohl, who has built on West Germany's
earlier agreements with other Soviet bloc countries.
   West Germany seeks recognition of language rights for Poland's
German minority and other improvements in conditions for the ethnic
Germans. Poland wants help for its crippled economy.
   Polish officials said before the Monday meeting they had agreed
to Bonn's conditions, but that disagreement remained on economic
aid. The West Germans said the amount of new credit to be given
Poland was the only point unresolved.
</TEXT>
