<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Bulgaria     06-26 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Bulgaria,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Criticizes Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The forced exodus of Turks from Bulgaria
demonstrates a systematic denial of basic human rights by the
Bulgarian government, the White House said Monday.
   ``We deplore Bulgaria's blatant violations of the human rights of
its citizens,'' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in a
statement.
   Fitzwater said about 60,000 Turks had ``either fled or been
forcibly expelled'' and had migrated to Turkey in the last month,
``many with nothing more than the clothes on their backs.''
   The United States has urged Bulgaria ``to cease these violations
and to allow for the orderly emigration of those ethnic Turks who
desire to leave,'' Fitzwater's statement said.
   Restraints on Bulgarians of Turkish descent, including forbidding
the use of the Turkish language, sparked riots throughout the
country last month in which 30 people were reported killed. The
Bulgarian government began deporting ethnic Turks on May 26.
   There are an estimated 1 million Bulgarians of Turkish descent.
They are Moslems, while the majority of Bulgarians are Christian.
</TEXT>
