<DOCNO> AP890626-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-26 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms From Rockies To East Coast, Tropical Storm In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Allison rolled ashore Monday in Texas with high
wind, torrential rain and high tides as thunderstorms packing
damaging winds and tornadoes formed from Colorado to the East Coast.
   Allison's main threat was expected to be heavy rain, with up to
10 to 15 inches of rainfall considered possible in eastern Texas and
southwestern Louisiana before late Tuesday afternoon.
   In just 20 minutes, 1.10 inches of rain fell on northern Bossier
City, La., and in 6 hours 1.89 inches of rain fell at Galveston,
Texas, with 1.21 inches at Houston.
   A tornado touched down in Galveston, but no injuries or damage
were reported.
   In the Houston area, Allison flooded streets and cut off power to
30,000 Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co. customers. Tides 5 feet above
mean sea level closed the Houston Ship Channel from Galveston Bay to
Houston. Several schools, including the University of Houston at
Clear Lake, canceled Monday night classes.
   Much of the nation east of the Rockies was under a hot, humid,
unstable air mass, just the right ingredients for thunderstorms. By
early afternoon thunderstorms popped up over many locations from
Colorado to the East Coast.
   A line of strong thunderstorms reached from eastern Wisconsin to
northwestern Illinois and northeastern Missouri.
   In Wisconsin, scores of confirmed and unconfirmed tornado
touchdowns were reported in the south-central section of the state.
   Sheriff's offices reported damage to homes and many trees in
Richland and Sauk counties, including a mobile home destroyed south
of Richland Center, and damage to numerous barns, small buildings,
trees and power lines.
   A school addition under construction at Baraboo was toppled by
high wind, injuring a worker, officials said.
   Severe thunderstorms produced heavy damage at Avoca, about 40
miles west of Madison, and winds gusted to 60 mph just west of
Monroe.
   Thunderstorm winds downed trees and power lines in Eagle, and
1{-inch diameter hail was reported in northwestern Milwaukee County.
   Numerous thunderstorms developed rapidly across parts of
southeastern Kansas, most of the mid- and lower Mississippi Valley,
southern Florida, and New York state. A tornado touchdown was
reported near North Miami Beach, Fla.
   Severe thunderstorms also formed over parts of eastern Colorado.
Hail an inch in diameter fell in Waterton, and 1- to 2-inch hail
pelted other parts of central Jefferson County.
   Montana continued its run of cool weather with a record low for
the date of 41 degrees at Glasgow.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Bellingham, Wash., to 102 at Phoenix and Gila Bend, Ariz.
Monday's low for the Lower 48 states was 27 at Leadville, Colo.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from southeast Missouri to eastern Wisconsin, the central and
eastern Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and the central and northern
Appalachians, as well as from the eastern halves of Oklahoma and
Texas to the lower Mississippi and Florida. Widely scattered showers
and thunderstorms were forecast from northern California to the
northern Rockies, and in the mountains of Colorado and northern New
Mexico.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted from the Pacific
Northwest to northwestern Montana, as well as northern Minnesota,
upper Michigan, and along the central and southern coasts of
California; between 100 and 110 degrees from the desert Southwest to
far southwestern Texas; and in the 80s and 90s in the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
