<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     06-26 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agrarian Reform Secretary Resigns Over Land Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's land reform secretary
has resigned, but President Corazon Aquino said Monday she would not
accept the resignation until scandals in his department are
investigated.
   Philip Juico said he submitted the resignation Saturday because
of allegations of criminal conspiracy in the purchase of an estate
in Camarines Sur province for distribution to peasants.
   The purchase was blocked in December when officials said the
government had agreed to pay $3 million for land worth only $142,000.
   Juico and 20 department officials went on leave last month after
newspapers disclosed the deal. At the time, Juico said he was taking
leave so an investigation Mrs. Aquino ordered would not be
influenced.
   After the Camarines Sur sale was disclosed, investigators said
that in at least two other cases, Juico's department agreed to pay
vastly inflated sums for land.
   The secretary has denied wrongdoing and said subordinates
deceived him. He He said Monday that his resignation was not an
admission of guilt.
   Mrs. Aquino told reporters she had received the resignation but
would wait for the investigating committee's recommendations ``and
then act accordingly.''
   J. Antonio Carpio, head of the National Bureau of Investigation,
said last week he had recommended criminal charges against 19
department officials. He refused to name them.
