<HEAD>Bush Praises Protugese President for NATO Stance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush praised Portugese President
Mario Soares Monday for a ``wonderful closeness'' with the United
States on issues before NATO.
   The two leaders met in the Oval Office for 35 minutes.
   During the session, Bush ``expressed his appreciation for
Portugal's positive contribution to the North Atlantic Alliance,''
said Marlin Fitzwater, Bush's press secretary.
   ``The two leaders discussed the European Community, China and
Central America. Southern Africa was also discussed, particularly
the Angola peace process,'' Fitzwater said.
   During a picture-taking session at the beginning of the meeting,
Bush told the Portugese leader: ``We sure appreciate the wonderful
closeness of Portugal and the United States on these NATO East-west
issues.''
   Soares told Bush, through a translator, that he also planned to
visit California and to meet with Portugese-American leaders in Los
Angeles, San Francisco and San Diego.
   ``There are about half a million people of Portugese descent in
California,'' Soares said.
   ``That's a lot,'' Bush said.
   ``They're quite prominent too,'' Soares added.
