<FIRST>u w AM-INS-Nelson     06-26 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS-Nelson,1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES throughout with more detail on reasons behind Nelson's
departure, SUBS 8th graf pvs: ``Leo said,'' with two grafs, now grafs 10-11,
with Leo CORRECTING pvs statement when Nelson informed, Wednesday sted
today;    ADDS two grafs with comment from Rep. Bruce Morrison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nelson Out as Immigration Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan C. Nelson, criticized earlier this year in
a Justice Department audit, was replaced Monday as head of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, the department said.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh announced in a brief statement
that he was appointing James L. Buck, deputy INS commissioner, as
acting head of the service to replace Nelson, who resigned.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel declined to say why
Nelson was being replaced before a permanent successor is found.
   But a Justice Department source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said officials were concerned about the overall
management at INS, which was criticized in the audit ordered earlier
this year by Thornburgh.
   Officials were particularly concerned about the agency's budget
because Nelson _ as a lame duck _ had no incentive to control
spending, the source said.
   Nelson, a holdover from the Reagan administration, has been
privately criticized by department officals, who have long signaled
that he would be replaced.
   His resignation has been pending since the start of the Bush
administration but was not accepted until this weekend, Runkel said.
   Gene McNary, the chief executive of St. Louis County, Mo., is
expected to be nominated by President Bush to fill the post.
   INS spokesman Greg Leo said senior officials of the agency were
not informed of Thornburgh's decision to replace Nelson with Buck
until 10:30 a.m. Monday, about the time the Justice Department
issued its public announcement.
   Leo said Nelson, who was in California, was first advised last
Wednesday that Bush would be accepting his resignation and was
formally informed of the action by telephone on Saturday.
   The audit said accounting, management and administration were in
disarray, citing a growing backlog of cases awaiting adjudication.
   It also noted that INS Western regional officials had chartered
jets to fly to conferences when commercial flights were available.
   More recently, Nelson raised the ire of Justice Department
officials by approving a trip to the National Sheriff's Association
convention in Honolulu of 19 officials of his agency.
   Nelson was forced to cancel the trips of all but three or four
after the department issued an order ``to curtail the number of
attendees traveling'' to conferences and meetings.
   This episode, the source said, raised concerns in the Justice
Department about Nelson's commitment to controlling spending.
   Nelson defended his agency against criticisms in the audit, which
he called ``grossly deficient.''
   The audit noted that the agency had spent $1,500 for an oil
portrait of Nelson. Justice Department officials were also privately
critical of a videotape tribute to Nelson that INS produced at
taxpayer expense.
   In his statement, Thornburgh noted that Nelson ``has led the
Immigration and Naturalization Service through difficult times.''
   During his tenure at INS, Nelson oversaw the amnesty program for
illegal aliens that was enacted by the 1986 Immigration Reform and
Control Act.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., who chairs the House immigration
subcomittee, said in a statement that he ``wished Commissioner
Nelson well'' but added that ``I have long felt that a change in
leadership was needed'' at INS.
   ``But more than new leadership, what is needed is a complete
reorganization of the structure if the functions now collected under
the INS are to be performed effectively.''
</TEXT>
