<FIRST>r i AM-Uruguay     06-26 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Cuts Expanded in Uruguay; General Strike Called</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL GIANELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state power company said Monday
that electricity shutdowns in this capital city of 1.2 million
people will be doubled to six hours a day. It put most of the blame
on drought.
   Uruguay's biggest labor coalition meanwhile announced it will
stage on Tuesday its eighth general strike against the government of
President Julio Sanguinetti to press demands for wage and pension
increases.
   Jose Serrato, president of the state Electric Power and
Transmission Co. said electricity in Montevideo and several other
cities will be cut from 5 p.m. to 11 p.m., adding, ``Since records
have been kept, there has not been so severe a shortage of rain.''
   Much of the electricity in this Oklahoma-sized, South American
nation of 3 million comes from hydropower. The lack of rain has
idled 13 of the 14 turbines of the Salto Grande complex on the
Uruguay River, a major power source.
   For weeks, Uruguay bought electricity from neighboring Argentina.
But this week Argentina, which has been having its own troubles, is
scheduled to resume power cuts itself.
   A bit more than 8{ inches of rain have fallen this year, Serrato
said, less than half the normal amount.
   Drinking water is being rationed in the small city of Melo.
Throughout Uruguay, grazing land has dried out and water is being
trucked in for livestock.
   The general strike was called by the National Central of Workers,
which is demanding a pay increase of about 30 percent starting July
1.
   The current minimum wage, set in February, is about $70 a month.
   The increase would apply to many of the approximately 260,000
state employees, who make up about one-quarter of the total work
force. Private sector companies raised wages by about 25 percent for
the March-June period.
   Inflation for 1989 is projected at 80 percent.
   Union leaders also want an increase in retirement pensions and
oppose proposals to sell state companies which might result in
layoffs or higher prices for services.
</TEXT>
