<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     06-26 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Unrest Breaks Out In Soviet Georgia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another outbreak of ethnic rioting, Georgians
and Azerbaijanis clashed in Soviet Georgia and five people were
wounded, a news editor in the southern republic said Monday.
   The riots took place Sunday night in Marneuli and Bolnisi, said
Zurab Lomidze, an editor of Gruzinform, the official Georgian news
agency. Lomidze said he had no details about the clashes or what
caused them and there were no reports about the rioting in the other
Soviet media.
   In April, 20 people were killed in the Georgian capital, Tbilisi,
when troops were called in to quell a pro-democracy demonstration.
   In other ethnic clashes, Tass reported one more person died
Sunday from injuries sustained in the Central Asian republic of
Kazakhstan, raising the death toll there to five. Tass said 22
people remain hospitalized.
   The June 17-20 riots were in the oil production center of Novy
Uzen between Kazakhs and settlers from the Caucasus Mountains
region. Native Kazakhs complain the settlers dominate oil industry
jobs and receive preferential treatment in housing and other
benefits.
   More than 3,500 people have fled Novy Uzen because of the unrest,
Tass reported. A curfew remained in effect and the city was calm,
the news agency said.
   In the last two months, ethnic protests were also reported in the
Central Asian republics of Tadzhikistan and Uzbekistan. In the worst
rioting, about 100 people died in the Fergana Valley region of
Uzbekistan earlier this month.
</TEXT>
