<FIRST>r i AM-PapuaNewGuinea     06-26 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Papua New Guinea,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Begin Operation To End Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIETA, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops launched an operation on
Monday to put down a 7-month-old secessionist uprising, burning
homes and seizing villagers, according to news reports.
   The revolt has closed an economically crucial mine of
Bougainville Copper Ltd. on northern Bougainville island. The
insurrectionists were reported overnight to have destroyed a power
plant at a farm owned by the company.
   Unrest shut down the mine May 15. Rebel landowners complain it
damages the environment and want $10 billion in compensation. The
pit had been contributing 20 percent of Papua New Guinea's total
revenue through royalties and taxes.
   Rebels spurned all attempts at conciliation, ambushing mine
workers and soldiers. Three soldiers were killed and about 20
security force members and many civilians were wounded.
   Under a state of emergency that went into effect Monday,
authorities were granted broad powers to search, seize and arrest,
and to evacuate people from emergency areas, Australian Associated
Press said.
   The agency quoted witnesses as reporting houses were set afire
and at least two dozen people were taken away by police on Monday,
with soldiers blocking the road to the mine and checking all
vehicles.
   It said many residents probably will be evacuated by force from
rebel-held areas to isolate secessionist leader Francis Ona, a
35-year-old surveyor, and his Bougainville Republican Army.
   Australia's largest mining company, CRA Ltd., jointly operates
the mine, which is about 300 miles northeast of the mainland.
   Security forces commander Col. Lima Dotaona asked Ona to
surrender. He expressed confidence on Sunday that his forces would
restore order, but said he expected a drawn-out operation.
   Prime Minister Rabbie Namaliu said Friday the government could
not let a ``criminal minority'' threaten national unity and economic
stability.
   Papua New Guinea, with 3.5 million people, became independent
from Australia in 1975. It lies in the tropics between Asia and
Australia.
</TEXT>
