<FIRST>r w AM-US-Australia-SouthAfrica     06-26 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Australia-South Africa,355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawke Says Time Running Out for South African Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With U.S.-Australia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's emerging new leaders must be
pressured to quickly end apartheid because ``the time is running
out'' for a ``congenial, bloodless'' resolution, Australian Prime
Minister Bob Hawke said Monday.
   ``It is the time now for pressure to bring them not to their
knees, but to the (negotiating) table ... '' Hawke said in answer to
questions at the National Press Club.
   Hawke said apartheid will be resolved one way or another and
``the time is running out where the conflict can be resolved in a
congenial, bloodless way.''
   ``I trust ... that what will be done by the rest of the world is
to keep up pressure, but to give the new leadership emerging in
South Africa the opportunity of responding, getting them to
understand that only by getting to the negotiating table in the near
future are we going to have the opportunity of a resolution of the
conflict in a bloodless way,'' he continued.
   Leaders of South Africa's black resistance movement, the African
National Congress, and the black frontline countries bordering South
Africa want a multiracial society in the country, Hawke said. They
recognize that country's future prosperity depends on keeping the
whites, white capital and expertise, he said.
   But those black leaders ``are running out of time with their
younger generations,'' who question such an attitude when it brings
no positive response, he added.
   Hawke described as ``silly'' the view of those who said that U.S.
economic sanctions voted by Congress over former President Ronald
Reagan's veto failed to have the desired effect. He noted that both
the South African finance minister and central bank governor
admitted the sanctions had the impact of forcing a lowering of
standards and expectations.
   F. W. de Klerk, the new leader of South Africa's governing
National Party, is expected to succeed President P. W. Botha later
this year and a de Klerk visit to Washington is under diplomatic
discussion, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen said last
week.
</TEXT>
