<FIRST>r i AM-US-Soviet-Nuclear 1stLd-Writethru a0711 06-26 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Begin New Talks on Monitoring Underground Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: LEADS throughout, CORRECTING Hiroshima blast kilotons, UPDATING
with White House statement. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators resumed talks Monday on
monitoring nuclear tests, and both sides predicted agreement soon.
   They are drafting new monitoring provisions for two superpower
treaties of the 1970s, still not ratified by the U.S. Senate,
limiting military and other nuclear explosions to 150 kilotons.
   One kiloton has the force of 1,000 tons of TNT. The bomb dropped
on Hiroshima, Japan, in 1945, originally reckoned at 20 kilotons,
had an explosive force of 12 or 13 kilotons.
   The goal is to get Senate ratification, which was withheld
because of concern that the limits could not be enforced.
   Talks resumed after a six-month recess caused, in part, by the
Bush administration review of arms control and security policy.
   Monday's meeting was held at the U.S. Mission in Geneva, between
delegation chiefs C. Paul Robinson of the United States and Igor
Palenykh of the Soviet Union.
   Robinson has said the purpose of the new negotiations, expected
to last five to six weeks, is to produce complete agreements.
Palenykh said there is ``a good basis for reaching practical results
within a short time.''
   They said a verification plan for the 1976 Peaceful Nuclear
Explosions Treaty is virtually complete but some work remains on how
to prevent cheating on the 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty.
   Both sides are to be allowed various methods of measuring the
power of explosions, including on-site checks at each other's
testing grounds.
   Future negotiations are intended to produce more agreements to
limit nuclear tests and ultimately prohibit the.
   The Soviet Union has urged Washington to join in a test ban, but
the United States says tests will be necessary as long as its
military strategy includes reliance on nuclear weapons.
   Talks on nuclear testing are separate from U.S.-Soviet
negotiations on reducing long-range nuclear arsenals, which resumed
in Geneva last week.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said in Washington
that a realistic verification plan is crucial to success of the new
talks on monitoring tests.
   ``The U.S. approach to these negotiations complements our efforts
to reach agreements that will strengthen our security and enhance
stability,'' Fitzwater said in a statement. ``A priority for these
step-by-step talks is to complete protocols to provide for effective
verification'' of the two treaties.
   He said the Senate ratified neither treaty because ``they were
not ratifiable in their original form.''
   ``Our approach to these negotiations is based on a realistic
approach to our security,'' Fitzwater said. ``As long as we must
rely on nuclear weapons, we must continue to test to ensure their
safety, security, reliability, effectiveness and survivability.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OhioMine     06-26 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ohio Mine,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Report: Federal Mining Agency Violated Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency violated its own policy when
it cleared the way for an Ohio coal company to strip mine coal in
the Wayne National Forest, congressional investigators have
concluded.
   ``It is improper for the Office of Surface Mining to have based
this decision on considerations other than its stated policy,'' said
a report by the House Interior Committee's mining subcommittee
delivered to the Interior Department, parent of the Office of
Surface Mining, on Friday and made available on Monday.
   Agency records showed the decision to let Belville Coal Co. of
Ironton, Ohio to mine was based on flimsy reasoning, a skimpy review
and no independent documentation, according to the report.
   Carl Close, the director of the Pittsburgh office of the Office
of Surface Mining, has said he consulted a staff attorney and
believed he was on firm legal ground when he made the now-contested
decision.
   Close in December reversed a 1986 decision and determined that
the company had a valid existing right to mine in the 190,000-acre
forest on the Ohio River _ in other words, mineral rights that
pre-dated creation of the forest that the federal government was
bound to recognize.
   ``It is inappropriate for a decision of this magnitude, involving
approximately 5,440 acres of National Forest land, to have been
based on a dearth of written independent agency analysis and
supporting agency documentation,'' the report said.
   ``No record exists which suggests that the Office of Surface
Mining conducted a thorough analysis'' before ruling that the
company had a legal right to strip mine for coal, said the report.
   The company has submitted an application for state mining permits
covering 180 acres. Spokesman Todd Ambs said the Ohio Department of
Natural Resources ``will probably act on it sometime before the end
of the summer.''
   Interior Department spokesman John Wright said Monday a deputy
assistant secretary was reviewing the Wayne Forest determination
``to see what prompted the decision, how it was based,'' and he
could not comment on the report.
   The congressional probe was conducted at the request of Rep. Nick
Rahall, D-W.Va., chairman of the subcommittee. He has asked Interior
Secretary Manual Lujan to freeze activity on all pending coal rights
claims until there's a federal standard in place.
   Wright said a reply probably would be ready next week.
   The Forest Service, part of the Agriculture Department, and the
congressional investigators contend the Office of Surface Mining
should have followed state standards since there's no federal
standard governing companies that buy previous owners' mineral
rights and apply to mine on land like national forests.
   An unsigned, undated Office of Surface Mining memorandum provided
to the investigators said turning down the coal company was
``probably the most defensible position legally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Eastern-Pilots     06-26 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pilots,2nd Ld-Writethru,a0720,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern, Pilots Meet With Court Examiner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 3 pvs: ``A pilot's,'' with one graf to give union
spokesman's account of Monday's talks; 4th graf edited for transition;
SUBS graf 11 pvs: ``Dan Ashby,'' to delet now-redundant first name of spokesmanconform
reference to spokesman, making graf bgn: ``Ashby said,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its pilots' union met
under court order Monday, negotiating for the first time since
Eastern sought permission last week to cancel the pilots' contract
and impose wage and other concessions.
   Representatives of Eastern and the Air Line Pilots Association
met with David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed examiner overseeing
the airline on behalf of the bankruptcy court.
   A pilots' union spokesman said ``nothing fruitful'' came from the
talks, which were ordered by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R.
Lifland. ``It was essentially feeling-out process, a discussion of
basic issues,'' said the spokesman, Dan Asbhy. Another session was
scheduled for Tuesday.
   In a related matter, a House subcommittee plans this week to
examine the impact of the nearly 4-month-old strike, and a Senate
panel has asked the General Accounting Office to assess the impact
Eastern's proposed reorganization would have on the airline industry.
   A group of six senators also is asking Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner to, at least temporarily, block Eastern from selling
more assets, a major part of the airline's reorganization plan.
   A consultant to the pilots' union said over the weekend that
Shapiro would oppose Eastern's bid to terminate the contract.
Shapiro did not return calls seeking comment Monday and Eastern said
it wasn't aware of Shapiro's position.
   Most of Eastern's pilots are, in effect, striking, although
technically they are honoring the pickets of the striking
machinists, as are Eastern's flight attendants.
   The meeting, at Shapiro's law office here, came five days after
Eastern requested about $50 million in wage and benefit concessions,
as well as changes in work policies that would allow Eastern to
increase pilots' hours.
   ``We've been trying to get the pilots to meet with us for some
time,'' said Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock. ``We at least see this
as having brought that about.''
   Ashlock declined to say whether Eastern had revised any of its
positions.
   Ashby said Eastern's statements that the pilots have refused to
meet were groundless and appeared to be part of an effort to
convince the bankruptcy court that the pilots were acting in bad
faith.
   The federal Railway Labor Act, which also covers airline
collective bargaining, requires both sides to continue negotiating
unless an impasse is declared and the talks referred to a federal
mediator.
   ``You'd never know it by what the company says but we've met with
them at every scheduled meeting,'' Ashby said.
   Eastern said it needed contract concessions from the pilots as
part of its plan to reorganize and emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protections as a smaller carrier.
   Lifland would have to approve the reorganization plan, which
includes major asset sales. The unions unsuccessfully have sought
the sale of Eastern.
   Lifland said three weeks ago that the court would no longer
consider the buyout offer of Chicago commodities trader Joseph
Ritchie, although he said Ritchie was free to pursue his offer with
Eastern.
   The airline has said it doesn't plan to sell, but the unions have
maintained that Ritchie's effort to buy Eastern continues.
   On Captol Hill, the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and
Transportation has requested the GAO investigation, saying in a
letter that its review ``should examine whether the proposed
business plan of Eastern has any realistic prospect of revitalizing
the carrier.''
   In a separate letter to Skinner, six senators called on the
transportation secretary to ``seek a delay in additional sales that
could further erode the competitive base in the airline industry.''
   The senators specifically cited Eastern's reported plans to sell
its South American routes.
   The senators who wrote to Skinner were Democrats Frank R.
Lautenberg of New Jersey, Wendell H. Ford of Kentucky, Bob Graham of
Florida, Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, John F. Kerry of
Massachusetts and Republican Alfonse M. D'Amato of New York.
</TEXT>
