<FIRST>r a AM-JuvenileDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0749 06-26 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Juvenile Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0749,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys for Death-Row Convicts Blast Supreme Court Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS overline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for death-row convicts blasted a Supreme Court ruling
Monday that allows the execution of murderers who committed their
crimes as young as 16, while prosecutors applauded the decision.
   ``In my opinion, it's utterly barbaric to execute any 16- or
17-year-old,'' said Sapulpa, Okla., attorney Bob Ravitz.
   His client, Sean Sellers, was convicted in 1986 of killing his
parents and a convenience store clerk in Oklahoma City at age 16.
Ravitz argued that his client was under Satan's influence.
   Asked about the decision, Oklahoma Assistant Attorney General Bob
Nance said, ``I think we're pleased from the attorney general on
down.''
   In 5-4 votes, the Supreme Court said the Constitution's ban on
cruel and unusual punishment does not prohibit execution of older
juveniles or adults with only the reasoning capacity of children.
   In a second instance, however, the court ruled that convicted
murderers have a right to demand that sentencing juries and judges
consider mental retardation as a possible mitigating factor.
   The juvenile killers ruling affects about 25 of the 2,200 death
row inmates across the nation.
   There are at least 11 states with one or more inmates under a
death penalty for crimes committed before they were 18, according to
state officials. Texas topped the list with nine inmates, followed
by Alabama and Georgia with four each.
   The Supreme Court apparently drew the line for capital punishment
at age 16 last year when they voted 5-3 to throw out the death
sentence of an Oklahoma murderer who committed the crime when 15.
   The ruling will probably not affect Paula Cooper because she was
15 when she stabbed a retired Gary, Ind., Bible teacher to death,
said her attorney William L. Touchette. Miss Cooper's case has drawn
international attention and a call for clemency from Pope John Paul
II.
   In West Palm Beach, Fla., lawyer James Eisenberg reacted with
sadness to the court's ruling.
   Eisenberg was the trial attorney for Cleo Lecroy, who was
convicted in Florida in the 1981 shooting deaths of a couple camping
in rural Palm Beach County. Lecroy was 17 at the time of the crime.
   ``Even countries such as Russia have recognized that killing
their children is not something that people ought to do, and I'm
sorry that in this country we don't feel the same way, don't have
the respect for our kids' lives,'' Eisenberg said.
   Carolyn Snurkowski, who is in charge of death appeals for Florida
Attorney General Bob Butterworth, said the ruling seemed ``to affirm
the system that we currently employ.''
   In its decision, the high court upheld the death sentence of
Missouri inmate Heath Wilkins, who was 16 when he stabbed a Kansas
City area liquor store clerk to death in 1985.
   Michele Coleman of the Missouri Coalition Against the Death
Penalty called the ruling ``devastating.''
   ``It just gives our state rein to execute children. I can just
hear prosecutors using (the Supreme Court's) ruling in their closing
arguments,'' Ms. Coleman said.
   Missouri Attorney General William Webster called such arguments
``hogwash.''
   ``There's a lot of people that say it's going to open the door.
That's ludicrous,'' said Webster.
   Webster said that before a juvenile can face the death penalty,
he or she has to be certified as an adult, go through a battery of
mental exams and have their age considered as a mitigating
circumstance by the judge.
   But Wilkins' court-appointed attorney, public defender Nancy
McKerrow, said courts decide whether to try a youngster as an adult
according to the seriousness of the crime, not the youngster's
mental nature.
   ``Where are the safeguards?'' McKerrow said. ``They make no
determination of a child's maturity. They're looking at the
seriousness of the crime. Then age becomes irrelevant. The fact that
(Wilkins) was 16 years old made no difference.''
</TEXT>
