<FIRST>r a AM-MayoralThreat     06-26 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayoral Threat,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Returns Home Despite Alleged Threat by City Airport Commissioner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr. and his family
returned home under increased police protection after fleeing their
house for 48 hours because of threats allegedly made by the city's
airport commissioner.
   The commissioner, Luther Boykins, faces two misdemeanor counts of
third-degree assault against Schoemehl.
   Boykins allegedly made the threats because of ordinances adopted
last week that sharply curtailed the duties of his ex-wife, city
License Collector Billie A. Boykins.
   The mayor kept up his schedule over the weekend despite the
problems, going to meetings, a high school reunion and a Jefferson
Day rally, aides said. The Schoemehl family returned home Sunday
night.
   ``He felt threatened,'' Deputy Police Chief Ray Lauer said. ``We
were concerned with the mayor's fears. I had no assurance from
(Luther) Boykins that this was over.''
   Schoemehl said police made the decision Friday to increase the
number of his bodyguards from one to four. He also decided to move
his family to a safe place, as he has done in the past during
protests and demonstrations in front of his house.
   Meanwhile, the transfer of most of Billie Boykins' duties to
other municipal agencies began.
   Luther Boykins, whom Schoemehl appointed airport commissioner,
coordinated the mayor's 1985 re-election campaign on the city's
predominantly black north side.
   Schoemehl said Luther Boykins' threat was expressed to aides
Peter Sortino and Nancy Rice ``in a very hostile, very vulgar, very
aggressive way'' after Schoemehl signed ordinances stripping Ms.
Boykins of most of her duties.
   The city aldermen drafted the ordinances on the basis of State
Auditor Margaret Kelly's report that Ms. Boykins had failed to
collect millions of dollars in revenues due the city.
   On Friday, the aldermen voted 16-13 to reduce Ms. Boykins' staff
from 54 employees to three.
   Supporters of Ms. Boykins, who is black, contended that the
ordinances were racially motivated.
   Luther Boykins, who was released from a police holdover cell
shortly before midnight on Friday, could not be reached for comment
on Monday. He said over the weekend he had ``no quarrel'' with
Schoemehl.
   Boykins has a July 6 court date scheduled to answer the
misdemeanor charges.
   Also Monday, the Missouri Court of Appeals refused to grant Ms.
Boykins an injunction that would bar the takeover of her office. Her
appeal followed a circuit judge's rejection of the same request.
   Ms. Boykins also faces a felony-drug charge in Bloomington, Ill.,
that stems from her arrest near there last fall.
</TEXT>
