<FIRST>u w AM-US-China 3rdLd-Writethru   06-26 1094</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0733,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Chinese Leaders Cannot Stop Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Minor editing in 2nd and 3rd grafs to reflect Baker delivered
remarks, INSERTS new 6th graf describing society, picks up 6th graf pvs,
``Meanwhile, Monday...'' INSERTS new 17th graf with Mitsuzuka comments,
picks up 18th graf pvs. ``Earlier Fitzwater was,'' INSERTS comments from
Australia's prime minister at 18th graf, bgng ``Baker leaves.'' ^By BARRY
SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, looking
beyond the current wave of arrests and executions, said Monday night
the leaders of China cannot block forever the country's ``rendezvous
with freedom.''
   Baker told 1000 guests at a black-tie dinner of the Asia Society
in New York, ``we will be there to help when the day follows the
night.''
   Baker's theme, in a 25-minute speech to the group, was that a
``new order'' of freedom is emerging in Asia and the Pacific. He
called repression in China and Burma ``rites of passage'' and spoke
philosophically of recent events in Beijing.
   ``We and some other nations have suspended business as usual,''
Baker said. ``But we and the rest of the world must not let our
revulsion at this repression blind us to pressure for reform.''
   He added: ``China has suffered a tragic setback, but the story is
not over.''
   The Asia Society is a private organization dedicated to improving
Americans' understanding of Asian affairs.
   Meanwhile Monday, Chinese authorities told 11 Americans not to
leave Kunming while charges of distributing religious tracts were
investigated. A U.S. official said ``we expect the matter to be
resolved soon.''
   The Americans went to China June 13 despite a warning by the
State Department after soldiers fired on students June 3-4 in
Beijing.
   The Americans being held were believed to be associated with an
evangelical Christian group, the Latter Rain Ministry of Litchfield,
Ill.
   The charges against them were not considered serious under
Chinese law. A U.S. diplomat was on his way from the American
consulate in Chengdu to investigate.
   In the past, Americans who distributed religious tracts have been
fined and asked to leave.
   According to Adam Shub, a State Department spokesman, the 11
Americans, who had planned to return home early next month, were
detained at the Yunnan University guest house and charged with
passing out religious material to the public. Their passports were
taken and they were forbidden to leave the city.
   Laura Templeton, secretary of Latter Rain Ministries Inc. in
Litchfield, said the group was ``99 percent sure'' the members were
in no serious trouble in Kunming.
   ``They weren't scheduled to leave for Hong Kong until next
Tuesday, and I am sure they will be leaving on schedule,'' she said.
   At the White House, President Bush said the United States
intended to ``continue trying to convince the Chinese leadership
that it is in their interest to keep reform moving forward,''
despite the recent bloodshed, said presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater said Bush made the observation during an Oval Office
meeting with Japan's new foreign minister, Hiroshi Mitsuzuka.
   ``The foreign minister said Japan was encouraged by the
president's experience in the region and hoped our two countries
would keep each other informed on our views,'' Fitzwater said in a
statement. Bush was head of the U.S. liaison office in China in
1974-75.
   Mitsuzuka, speaking before Baker at the society dinner, called
China's ``path toward isolation in the international community''
regrettable and appealed to China's new leaders to ``govern in a
spirit of reconcilation and restraint.''
   Earlier, Fitzwater was asked at a White House briefing if Bush
had sent any communication to the new Chinese Communist Party chief,
Jiang Zemin, who replaced the ousted Zhao Ziyang.
   ``I don't believe he has communicated with the new Communist
Party chief,'' Fitzwater said. ``I don't know whether he knows him
or not.''
   Australia' Prime Minister Bob Hawke insisted that he, Bush and
the leaders of Britain and France must walk ``a very difficult
dividing line'' in supporting continued economic reform in China
while denouncing the crackdown on political freedom.
   Hawke, who met with Bush at the presidential retreat in Camp
David, Md., told reporters at the National Press Club, ``We have to
express a position without equivocation of condemnation ... at the
same time make clear (we) want to do what can be done to assist the
processes of economic reform. The interst of the people of China,
and particularly those who are committed to political reform, would
be very adversely affected if by the action of the rest of the world
China was forced to turn completely in upon itself because the
process of economic reform would be diminished and subsequently the
opportunity to political reform.''
   Baker leaves July 3 on a trip to Asia. His speech Monday night
was his first summarizing Bush administration policy on the region.
   ``The post-war era is over,'' he said. ``In Asia, as in Europe, a
new order is taking shape.''
   Baker will stop in Tokyo to help plan multinational economic aid
for the Philippines. Then, in Brunei, he will attend the annual
meeting of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations. This is an
economic grouping of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore and Thailand.
   ``The purpose of my trip is to establish the framework for a new
Pacific partnership,'' he told the private group. ``To build that
new partnership we need continued American engagement in the
region's politics, commerce and security.''
   Above all, Baker stressed U.S. ties to Japan.
   He called for ``a more creative sharing of global
responsibilities,'' and praised the Japanese for shouldering more of
the cost of keeping U.S. troops in the country _ about 40 percent.
   And, Baker said, Japan soon will be the largest donor in the
world of overseas development assistance. Yet Mitsuzuka, stressed
the need for America ``to maintain a strong political, economic and
military presence and commitment to the region.''
   Turning to China, Baker concluded the country clearly had decided
to abandon its isolation from regional progress but the pace of
political change did not match the aspirations of the people.
   Defending U.S. policy against calls for sterner measures in
response to the violence, Baker said ``we have acted in a measured
way.''
   He said it would be a mistake to dismantle the relationship the
United States built up over two decades with the Communist
government in Beijing.
   However, Baker said, Americans and the U.S. government will stand
for democratic values. And, he said, ``China's rendezvous with
freedom, like its rendezvous with the advancing nations of the
Pacific. cannot be long delayed.''
</TEXT>
