<FIRST>r i AM-EEC-China     06-26 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-China,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Draft Statement Calls For Freeze On Loans To China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   EEC leaders are ready to recommend that the
World Bank and other financial institutions suspend loans to China
following the military crushing of pro-democracy protests there,
Spain's foreign minister said Monday.
   Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez said the recommendation was
included in a statement drafted by EEC foreign ministers. The summit
was expected to approve the statement Tuesday.
   Spain is current president of the 12-member European Economic
Community, which was meeting in the Spanish capital.
   Ordonez said besides suspending loans to China, the document
called for:
   _Suspension of military aid and arms sales to China.
   _A freeze on visits to China by high-level EEC officials.
   _No new development aid projects in China and a freeze on
existing projects.
   _Discussion of human rights abuses in China in the proper world
forums.
   _Authorization for independent observers to attend the trials of
purported agitators in China and to visit prisons where they are
being held.
   _Indefinite extension of visas held by Chinese students in EEC
countries.
   _Limiting cultural exchanges.
   In response to the Chinese army's clearing out protesters in
Tiananmen Square in central Beijing on June 3-4, President Bush
suspended military aid and contacts with China on June 6. He later
said Washington would withold its support of international loans to
Beijing and banned visits to China by senior administration
officials.
   Fernandez Ordonez said the ministers also drew up a declaration
on the Middle East, the first by European heads of government since
a statement issued in Venice in 1980.
   He said the declaration included a statement that the Palestine
Liberation Organization should take part in any Mideast peace
conference. It supported Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
proposal for elections in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, provided the vote is a step toward definitive solution of the
Israeli-Palestine conflict.
</TEXT>
