<HEAD>Retransmits a0764 to fix category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Houston Mayor Seeks Fifth Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Kathy Whitmire announced Monday she is
seeking a record-tying fifth consecutive term and will ask voters to
compare her with her main challenger, who held the job in the
mid-1970s.
   ``I am very proud to be your mayor today and when the voters go
to the poll this November, I'm going to ask them to compare the
records and elect the better mayor for Houston,'' she said to a loud
applause from about 350 supporters at a downtown hotel.
   Mrs. Whitmire said if elected she would make battling the drug
problem in Houston a top priority.
   ``The drug epidemic that has swept this nation is the most
serious threat that our city faces today,'' the mayor said.
   Fred Hofheinz, who won two-year terms in 1973 and 1975, announced
his candidacy in March. Mrs. Whitmire's entry brings the number of
candidates in the Nov. 7 non-partisan field to at least five. Also
running are Rosie Walker, publisher of Houston Downtown Magazine;
Shelby Oringderff, a retired Houston schoolteacher, and Hispanic
leader James Galvan.
   For Mrs. Whitmire, 42, the race marks the second time she will
face a former mayor. In 1985, she trounced Louie Welch, whose
mayoral longevity mark she is trying to match. Two years ago, she
won her fourth term against token opposition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
