<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede TOKYO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Official Says Train Blast in Shanghai Kills 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Chinese official reporting blast,
Chinese news agency saying it was dynamite. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion aboard a train in the suburbs of
Shanghai killed 20 people and seriously injured 11, an offical
reported Tuesday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency reported that an on-the-spot
investigation showed the explosion was caused by dynamite.
   The official of the Shanghai Foreign Affairs Office called it an
accident and said the blast happened at 11.13 p.m. Monday (10:13
a.m. EDT) in Songjiang county, 18{ miles southwest of the city.
   He said the No. 364 train was on its way to Shanghai from
Hangzhou, 112 miles to the southwest. It was scheduled to reach
Shanghai at 00:08 a.m. Tuesday.
   He said the blast occurred in the No. 7 seated compartment of the
train but could not give details.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported that
20 people died, 11 were badly hurt and an unknown number of
passengers were slightly injured.
   He was unable to give the capacity of the train or the
compartment.
   According to Japan's Kyodo News Service, the explosion occurred
in a toilet in the front of the compartment. The Japanese NHK
television station reported that the interior of the train was
severely damaged but not burned.
   Xinhua said the vice mayor of Shanghai, Ni Tianzeng, had arrived
at the scene to organize rescue work.
   Six people died in Shanghai when a train smashed through a
barricade set up by demonstators pressing for democratic reform this
month. Three youths who were accused of later setting fire to the
train were convicted and executed two weeks later.
   Last March, brake failure caused the collision of two trains in
Shanghai, killing 28 people. Among them were 27 members of a
Japanese high school tour group.
</TEXT>
