<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     06-26 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Army Patrol Kills 42 Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, PERU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army patrol battled leftist rebels at
their remote highland stronghold and killed 42 of them in some of
the worst fighting in the rebels' nine-year insurgency, a military
official said Monday.
   The military refused to provide information on army casualties.
   The troops and Shining Path rebels fought Sunday evening near the
village of Pampaccori, 40 miles northeast of Ayacucho, a military
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The military spokesman said troops also captured a large number
of weapons and ``subversive propaganda.''
   He said it was one of the biggest losses of life suffered by the
Shining Path in their nine-year-old fight against the government.
   The Ayacucho region, 235 miles southeast of Lima, is the
birthplace of the Shining Path insurgency and remains its stronghold.
   The guerrilla organization began its fight against the government
in May 1980 after 10 years of grass roots organizing among Indian
peasants in this impoverished region.
   Since then the violence has spread throughout the country, and
more than 15,000 people have died in clashes between troops and
guerrillas, as well as in rebel attacks.
   There has been a recent surge in rebel activity, and analysts say
the stepped-up attacks are intended to sabotage municipal elections
in November.
   In violence Monday, two policemen were killed and four were
missing after 50 Shining Path guerrillas Monday ambushed a truck
carrying six policemen in a mining province in the highlands, police
said.
   The guerrillas hurled sticks of dynamite and opened fire with
machine guns during the ambush, which occurred close to a
copper-mining complex near Huancayo, 140 miles east of Lima, police
said.
   Last week Shining Path rebels ambushed an army convoy in the
Amazon jungle near Aguaytia, 270 miles northeast of Lima, and 20
rebels and 15 soldiers were killed in the fighting.
</TEXT>
