<HEAD>For Release Saturday, July 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, July 8, the 189th day of 1989. There are 176
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, ``The Wall Street Journal'' was first
published.
   On this date:
   In 1663, King Charles II of England granted a charter to Rhode
Island.
   In 1776, a Colonel John Nixon gave the first public reading of
the Declaration of Independence to a crowd gathered at Independence
Square in Philadelphia.
   In 1891, future president Warren G. Harding married Florence K.
DeWolfe in Marion, Ohio.
   In 1896, William Jennings Bryan captivated the Democratic
national convention in Chicago with his ``cross of gold'' speech.
   In 1907, Florenz Ziegfeld staged his first ``Follies,'' on the
roof of the New York Theater.
   In 1919, President Woodrow Wilson received a tumultuous welcome
in New York City after his return from the Versailles Peace
Conference in France.
   In 1947, demolition work began in New York City to make way for
the new permanent headquarters of the United Nations.
   In 1950, Gen. Douglas MacArthur was named commander-in-chief of
United Nations forces in Korea.
   In 1959, Maj. Dale R. Buis of Imperial Beach, Calif., and Master
Sgt. Chester M. Ovnand of Copperas Cove, Texas, became the first
American soldiers to be killed during the Vietnam War.
   In 1975, President Gerald R. Ford announced he would seek the
Republican nomination for the presidency in 1976.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter continued his summit on
domestic issues at Camp David, Md., consulting with a procession of
state and national officials.
   Five years ago: John McEnroe defeated Jimmy Connors in straight
sets, 6-1, 6-1, 6-2 to become the first American man in 46 years to
capture back-to-back Wimbledon tennis titles.
   One year ago: Iran's parliamentary speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani,
said his nation would not seek revenge against the United States for
the shooting down of an Iranian jetliner over the Persian Gulf that
resulted in the deaths of all 290 people on board.
   Today's birthdays: Former Michigan Gov. George Romney is 82.
Critic Walter Kerr is 76. Singer Billy Eckstein is 75. ABC News
President Roone Arledge is 58. Singer Steve Lawrence is 54.
Ballerina Cynthia Gregory is 43. Actress Kim Darby is 41.
   Thought for today: ``Money often costs too much.'' _ Ralph Waldo
Emerson, American essayist and poet (1803-1882).
</TEXT>
