<FIRST>s i BC-APN--FrenchBicentennial-Quotes Adv09   06-26 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--French Bicentennial-Quotes, Adv 09,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--French Revolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Quotations inspired by the French Revolution:
   ``Man is born free, and everywhere he is in irons.'' _ Jean
Jacques Rousseau.
   ``History is little else than a picture of human crimes and
misfortunes.'' _Voltaire.
   ``I am the rage of the people.'' _ Jean Paul Marat, who also
urged the crowd to ``cut the thumbs off aristocrats who conspire
against you; split the tongues of the priests who have preached
servitude.''
   ``It would be unwise to appeal to the people, because virtue has
always been a minority on this Earth.'' _ Maximilien de
Robespierre's argument against putting the execution of Louis XVI to
a public vote.
   ``I cannot shed the blood of my people.'' _ Louis XVI's repeated
excuse for not using force against the crowd.
   ``Let them eat cake.'' _ Marie Antoinette's alleged reply when
told the country people had no bread. (The actual quote was ``Qu'ils
mangent de la brioche'' _ let them eat breakfast buns.)
   ``O, Liberty! How they have duped you.'' _ Madame Jeanne Roland's
last words, addressed to a plaster statue of liberty set up near the
guillotine.
   ``It is a far, far better thing that I do, than I have ever done;
it is a far, far better rest that I go to, than I have ever known.''
_ Sydney Carton, going nobly to the guillotine in the Charles
Dickens' novel ``A Tale of Two Cities.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
