<DOCNO> AP890626-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ReportFromAlaska-II Adv09-2Takes   06-26 0996</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Report From Alaska-II, Adv 09-2 Takes,1022</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 locator
map, 1 logo.    EDITOR'S NOTE _ No phones, no TV, no store, yet, remarkably,
a post office. But if it's gold you're after, and boom-town lore, Flat,
Alaska, is the place to go. One native son, at age 71, is still digging.
   ___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JULES LOH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLAT, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can count the year-round population of
this town on the fingers of one hand. They are Mark and Sherri
Kepler and their three children.
   In the summertime, the four months of thaw in interior Alaska,
the population swells to a grand total of maybe 30. These are gold
miners drawn back as irresistibly as the migrating swallows. They
come to work their old mining claims, to see anew the bedazzling
flashes of yellow among the gravel in their gold pans.
   The lure must be irresistible because even in summer Flat has
none of the amenities you might expect in any American village,
however small, with a certified U.S. post office. Not one store. Not
one cash register. Not one telephone.
   ``I am the federal presence here,'' says Mark Kepler. ``I am the
postmaster. Here is the post office.''
   He shows, proudly, a one-room building of about 10 feet by 15
feet that he explains was once a liquor store he restored according
to government specifications, complete with a Zip code and a flag.
   ``I fly the flag by the rules,'' he says. ``I raise it at dawn,
which here in Alaska happens in April, and I take it down at sunset,
in September.''
   Correction. Flat, Alaska, does have a store. It is padlocked, but
its goods are still on the shelves, unsold. The last sale was about
1942. One of the unsold items is a brand-new dog sled.
   It also has a bank, likewise padlocked. Inside is a roll-top
desk, its pigeonholes full, a green visor and sleeve garters in one
drawer, a locked vault with who knows what in it, and a set of brass
scales that weighed 1.7 million ounces of gold.
   Flat was one of this frontier state's boomingest gold boom towns,
now frozen in time but still breathing.
   Its gravel streets and byways are strewn with carcasses of cars
and trucks and mining debris dating from the 1930s. ``When those
people all left,'' says Kepler, ``I guess it was too much trouble to
take them out.''
   Kepler, a mechanic, drives a '38 pickup truck he made to run like
a jeweled watch from salvaged parts.
   It would indeed have been at least as much trouble to take all
that stuff out as it was to haul it in.
   Flat was named for nearby Flat Creek. It might as easily have
been named Otter for another nearby creek. (Or Poorman, for yet
another, although that would not, over all, have been accurate.) It
is out in the wilderness 275 miles northwest of Anchorage as the
crow flies.
   As the hungering miners found their way here when gold was
discovered by a prospector named John Beaton in 1908, the route was
much longer.
   It required riverboats up the Kuskokwim River, then up the
Iditarod River to a landing place, then eight miles overland to the
gold fields of Flat.
   A town of about 6,000 sprang up at the landing place, Iditarod,
and the gold rush became known as the Iditarod Stampede. Nothing
remains of Iditarod, only weathered skeletons of a few buildings.
One of them was Tootsie's, a house of ill fame.
   A bathtub from the collapsed rubble of Tootsie's now resides in
the home of Mark and Sherri Kepler at their home in Flat, which they
built and furnished themselves.
   ``Isn't it something, look at those clawed feet,'' says Mrs.
Kepler. ``If only it could talk.''
   John Miscovich remembers Tootsie's.
   In fact, Miscovich has a remarkable memory for every place and
every excitement in Flat since he was born here in 1918 in a cabin
on Otter Creek.
   He is the son of an ambitious immigrant who heard about the
Iditarod Stampede, got in on it, worked for wages, bought a claim
and sent for his wife in Yugoslavia. John is the result.
   He, at 71, and his wife, Mary, and any of their four grown
children who can make it, return to Flat every summer, with the
swallows, to take out of their now extensive land holdings whatever
gold a mom-and-pop operation, as he calls it, can yield.
   ``In the early days we took 6,000 ounces a year,'' he says. ``We
don't even try for that now, but it's still worthwhile.''
   You bet. Gold appears daily in his sluice, and two years ago he
unearthed a 28-ounce nugget. At the going price of gold, that alone
is worth about $8,000.
   ``Well,'' says Miscovich, ``because it's a nugget and not dust,
and it fits just right in the palm of your hand, it's probably worth
at auction 10 times the price of gold. Some Texan would pay that to
make it into a belt buckle.
   ``Oh, yes, we still have it,'' he says. ``You're never broke if
you have a little gold put aside.''
   But Miscovich didn't make it only on gold. Working for his father
as a boy he had to straddle, like a horse, a huge and heavy
cannon-like hose nozzle used to bust up gold-producing earth with a
high-pressure stream of water. It was hard work, and dangerous. He
figured there must be a better way. So he invented one, and patented
it.
   If you have seen a fireboat at work or a ladder truck with a
mounted nozzle you have seen Miscovich's invention, a water cannon
with even higher pressure but small and safe and easy to aim. ``I
designed it for miners,'' he says, ``but it was firefighters who
wanted it the most.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ReportFromAlaska-II Adv09-1stAdd   06-26 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Report From Alaska-II, Adv 09-1st Add,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>FLAT, Alaska: the most.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Miscovich left school in the 11th grade, never went to college.
Yet the knowledge of geology and mining he picked up on his own is
so recognized that he has served for years in the winter months as a
consultant to mining companies, inspecting potential digging sites
around the globe.
   He could have made a fine living at that alone. It isn't need or
greed, he says, that draws him and his wife here every summer from
their comfortable winter home in Orange, Calif.
   Their home here is typical of an Alaska mining camp. It is small,
tin-roofed, its plumbing uncertain, its dooryard cluttered with old
wagon wheels, moose antlers, remains of mining equipment.
   ``It doesn't have all the comforts,'' he says, ``but we actually
look forward to coming back every year.
   ``We like the isolation. We like getting out and working with our
hands. If the ballgame on TV, or the Sunday paper, or the movie
house aren't all that important to you you would understand.''
   The now-empty town also brings back vivid memories for Miscovich.
   He remembers the day Wiley Post crash-landed here in 1933. A
snapshot of Miscovich with the pioneer aviator hangs on his wall.
   He remembers catching fish as a boy, selling them to the miners
to relieve their diet of moose steaks, and of the excitement when a
bear would wander into town.
   He remembers the Fourth of July bashes at the recreation hall
that lasted three days. The hall remains, decorated with 48-star
flags and a fine upright piano. The piano needs tuning.
   And he remembers the great Black Bear gold robbery, Flat's only
recorded crime.
   ``It was set up by the mail carrier who delivered the gold by dog
sled, $120,000 worth, and by a prostitute known as Black Bear _ her
sister was called The Cub _ and by her procurer.
   ``They got caught, the gold was recovered, the mailman turned
state's evidence and went free. The other two were tried in
Fairbanks. The jury set them free, too ...
   ``Black Bear and the procurer later made a fortune in bootlegging
and went off to California to raise racehorses.''
   Miscovich saw the boom end and Flat's terminal illness set in.
Flat became inaccessible except by airplane, the old Iditarod road
rendered impassable by neglect. Small operators couldn't meet the
bottom line.
   For excitement in Flat today, the biggest attraction would be
Mark Kepler's workshop.
   It is truly a wondrous place. Machinery from another age still
functions _ lathe, drill press, saw, forge _ turned to life by a
single motor and a dozen flapping belts.
   ``This is where I spend most of my time,'' he says. ``It's my
playground.'' Anything busted, Kepler can fix.
   The very isolation of Flat, not to mention all that abandoned
machinery to play with, was what prompted the Keplers to buy one of
its forsaken houses seven years ago to use for summer outings.
   They lived in Aniak, a small village 75 miles southwest, the
closest place from here where people live. He worked there as a
commercial pilot and airplane mechanic. Kepler is 35. The two Kepler
boys are 12 and 9 and the girl is 2.
   ``When the postmaster job opened up three years ago we decided to
come out here and stay permanently. To us, this is paradise. I have
plenty to keep me busy.''
   What do you do in winter?
   ``Mostly cut wood.''
   Wood fuels the Kepler furnace and the kitchen stove. A diesel
generator provides electricity for the refrigerator, but kerosene
lamps serve for much of the lighting.
   Do the children like the life?
   ``They love it. The other day Sherri and I were discussing the
possibility of the post office closing down and us having to leave.
The boys said they would stay without us.''
   Mrs. Kepler teaches the children by correspondence, not unusual
in the Alaskan outback. She uses books and lesson plans provided by
the state. She talks to a correspondence teacher twice a week, by
radio. ``Both boys test well above their grade level,'' she says.
   Every three or four months Mark cranks up his airplane and the
Keplers go shopping in Anchorage. They have their supplies mailed
back, which gives Kepler a little business at the post office.
   His other postal business is mainly forwarding mail in winter to
the miners who keep Flat as their permanent mailing address. Unlike
Miscovich, who has a regular second home, most of the others go off
to various sunny places to spend their gold.
   The mail plane arrives three times a week, even if there's
nothing to deliver.
   Flat happens to be on the way between other more populated mail
drops and it isn't much trouble to make one more landing. Besides,
Alaskans have a tradition of seeing to one another out in the bush,
especially during the dark, harsh winter.
   ``Drop us a Christmas card,'' says Kepler. ``We're always glad to
hear from the outside.''
   Five people there. That's all. Their address is Flat, Alaska,
99584.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 9</NOTE>
