<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   06-26 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``True Believer'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95.
Rated R)
   
   ``True Believer'' is fun to watch. Unfortunately, it is not
believable.
   James Woods plays, with his trademark intensity, Eddie Dodd, a
pioneering civil rights lawyer who lost his 1960s spirit on the way
to the '80s. He finds himself defending mostly drug dealers, and
defending himself for doing so.
   Along comes a young lawyer, Roger (Robert Downey Jr.), who
worships Dodd's earlier work, and an 8-year-old murder case in which
the defendant might actually be innocent. Dodd is reluctant to take
the case, and Roger sneers, ``It was close, huh? We almost defended
someone who wasn't a drug dealer.''
   But Dodd plunges into the case, and he also finds he's fighting
public corruption and various urban evils.
   The problem with the movie, directed by Joseph Ruben, is that
instead of taking a close look at Dodd's disillusionment, or at the
relationship between Dodd and Roger, ``True Believer'' takes the
easy way out and goes for the thrills.
   For starters, the old murder is recreated, Dodd is beaten up by a
phony white supremacist, and there's a crazy and dangerous chase
through a plumbing supply factory. On the good side, the ending is
clever.
   Downey is fine, as is Yuji Okumoto playing the convict and
Margaret Colin as a private detective.
   _ By Mary MacVean, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Midnight Hour'' (Vidmark, VHS-Beta, $89.95)
   
   ``The Midnight Hour'' is a good little vampire, witches and
ghouls tale starring Shari Belafonte-Harper as a witch who brings
terror to a small town on Halloween.
   Although there are recognizable names in the movie, the acting
leaves much to be desired. Co-starring are: Levar Burton, Lee
Montgomery, Dick Van Patten, Kevin McCarthy, Jonelle Allen, Dedee
Pfeifer and Cindy Morgan.
   And for a horror flick, the chills are as lacking as the thespian
skills.
   Nonetheless, it is still an enjoyable romp as the the town's
cemetery residents climb out of their graves and munch, rip and
mutilate their way through the night, joining trick-or-treaters and
crashing a halloween party.
   The game then becomes how to get the baddies back in the grave
and the townsfolk back to normal. Along the way, there are a few
chuckles.
   And despite all its flaws, ``The Midnight Hour'' is an adequate
little horror flick for a rainy Saturday afternoon.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
