<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Telluride Sessions'' (MCA) _ Strength in Numbers
   
   Innovation and bluegrass are uneasy companions. But the all-star
band Strength in Numbers is proof that the banjo, dobro, bass,
fiddle and mandolin can break new ground.
   ``The Telluride Sessions'' combines bluegrass instrumentation
with New Age melodies and classical-music arrangements, and the
result is a pleasure to hear.
   These guys aren't just any pickers. Sam Bush on mandolin and Bela
Fleck on banjo are members of the New Grass Revival, one of the best
progressive bluegrass bands. Mark O'Connor (on fiddle, guitar and
mandolin), Jerry Douglas (dobro) and Edgar Meyer (bass) are also
terrific instrumentalists.
   But for their first record together, these inventive virtuosos
decided to emphasize ensemble playing rather than solos. Themes are
developed by unusual instrumental combinations _ two violins and a
bowed bass, for example, on the beautiful ``One Winter's Night.''
Counterpoint and dynamics, rarely important in bluegrass music, are
explored to great effect. The band has a lot of fun with
syncopation, too.
   ``The Telluride Sessions'' isn't without dazzling solos. O'Connor
(on guitar) and Fleck play with breathless speed on ``Slopes.''
O'Connor and Bush stage a mandolin duel on ``Macedonia.''
   But the star of record may be its most unheralded participant.
Meyer performs tricks on the bass that will leave listeners shaking
their head, and he had a hand in most of the strongest compositions,
including the good-humored ``Pink Flamingos'' and the pensive ``No
Apologies.''
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
