<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 7-9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Theme Parks May Become Museums of the Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REBECCA MARTIN EVARTS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Museums of the future will have to draw
more on Walt Disney than the Renaissance if they are to attract
visitors, ensure sources of funding and survive competition from
theme parks.
   ``Museums must change from self-centered to client-centered
environments,'' says George F. MacDonald, director of the Canadian
Museum of Civilization. ``They must market themselves not only as
educational but also as meaningful leisure-time activity.''
   MacDonald was one of half a dozen experts who spoke at a recent
symposium on museums sponsored by the Caixa de Pensions Foundation
and the Cultural Olympics, part of the 1992 Summer Olympics
organized by the city of Barcelona.
   People already spend more time on visits to theme parks than on
trips to museums _ an average of eight hours as compared to 50
minutes, according to statistics provided at the symposium.
   But interest in museums appears to be on the increase, said
Kenneth Hudson, director of the European Museum of the Year Award.
He added, however, that government and foundation funding, on which
so many museums depend, is shrinking as public budgets are tightened
and costs rise, forcing them to become more self-supporting.
   Museums of the future will have to borrow techniques from the
successful theme parks such as extensive sensory stimulation through
lights, graphics and color as well as live performances, constant
change and updating of attractions, film presentations on giant
screens and attractive boutiques selling related merchandise.
   But museums need not sacrifice their traditional role of
educating and providing well-researched and accurate information,
MacDonald said, when improving on attention to the needs and
interests of their visitors.
   Many museum curators would put up enormous resistance to such
changes, he acknowledged.
   ``They have comfortable niches there, and they don't like the
earth trembling under their feet,'' MacDonald said. ``But I think
the future is equally bleak if they don't respond because their
funding will shrink every year, and eventually they'll be running
empty museums with no operating budget.''
   Margaret J. King, a specialist in American popular culture at
Philadelphia's Thomas Jefferson University, said part of the change
will require museums to fuse popular culture with the elite culture
that has been their traditional domain.
   In order to attract visitors inside, the experts said, museums of
the future will have to offer greatly expanded leisure facilities
such as full-service restaurants, theaters, conference facilities
and reception rooms big enough to accommodate weddings or perfume
and other marketing launches.
   And they will have to be visually exciting and welcoming, rather
than monumental and intimidating.
   Visitors reared on television will be more readily drawn to
exhibits where information is displayed on TV screens than on
printed labels, and video-computer hookups will be used to allow
museumgoers to request additional information that is specifically
suited to their interests.
   Because visitors will be able to control the information, museums
will be able to present several interpretations of an exhibit or
object, permitting the viewer to come to his or her own conclusions.
   Science museums, maritime museums and museums of human
civilization have been among the first to make use of theme park
techniques.
   At Barcelona's Maritime Museum, housed in the 14th century Royal
Shipyards building on the Mediterranean waterfront, the 180 symposim
participants were able to see some of the principles of the modern
museum put into practice.
   For example, the recent remodeling is concentrating on
highlighting valuable but poorly lighted exhibits such as the
life-size replica of the Juan de Austria, Spain's flagship in the
1517 Battle of Lepanto, with halogen focus lamps or fluorescent
strip lighting that draws the visitor closer to the objects.
   The three-year-old City of Science and Industry in Paris' La
Villette neighborhood was billed by its president Roger Lesgards as
a ``cultural enterprise'' offering the visitor the opportunity to
simulate flying an Airbus jet, watch a living fetus as it develops
or climb inside the Ariane rocket.
   If this fails to hold one's interest, the visitor can stroll the
136 acres of park surrounding the museum, visit one of the four bars
or three shops, change money at the bank, play the
discovery-through-play Inventorium for children or do some research
with 190,000 reference works.
   But directors and curators of fine and decorative arts museums
have been slower to welcome the Disney-like atmosphere into their
marble halls.
   ``Art museums still contrive to make visitors feel that they are
studying for an examination or should be,'' said Hudson, who is no
friend of theme parks. He believes the museum of the future will
have to become a grassroots social center where the atmosphere
surrounding the objects may be more important than the objects
themselves.
   In MacDonald's view, the art museum of the future will have to
pay more attention to creating a context for the art and to
revealing the codes of meaning contained in the work of many
artists, especially contemporary ones.
   ``One of the most effective ways of doing that is to have
presentations that look through the eyes of the artist,'' he said.
   Ernest J. Hugh de Samper, senior director of government and media
relations for Colonial Williamsburg, said most museum people resent
the theme park as an interloper.
   ``For them, the real thing is the real thing,'' he said. ``But
like detente, it (the theme park) must be recognized. We must adapt
our activities to make the best of our assets while keeping up with
the competition.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 7-9</NOTE>
