<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 7-9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Bill Anderson Swears Off Songs Glorifying Drinking</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran TV and country music entertainer
Bill Anderson, whose wife was almost killed in a traffic accident,
says he will never again perform songs about alcoholic beverages.
   Becky Anderson, 43, suffered brain damage and was given just a
50-50 chance to live after her car was struck head on by a truck
driven by a drunken driver in 1984.
   Bill recounts the incident, and several other personal setbacks,
in his new autobiography ``Whisperin' Bill.'' The book, published by
Longstreet Press, takes its title from Anderson's nickname.
   The 461-page book marks another career milestone for Anderson,
who has been a Grand Ole Opry singer, award-winning songwriter, soap
opera actor, network game show host, record producer and businessman.
   Anderson said his wife's accident, from which she has almost
fully recovered, has made him realize the danger of drinking and
driving. He's sworn off performing songs about drinking, tunes that
are a mainstay of country music.
   ``This has really opened up my eyes to the fact it is very
real,'' he said. ``I don't think before this happened that I was as
sensitive to it as I am now. Before, I thought it was just something
you sang about and you kind of lived your life as you wanted to.
   ``Now, I will not sing a drinking song.''
   The Andersons filed a $4 million civil lawsuit after the
accident. A Nashville jury awarded them $1.2 million, but a judge
reduced the award to $825,000. At the time, the $1.2 million was the
largest amount ever awarded in Nashville.
   ``The whole thing that happened to her was so senseless,'' the
51-year-old Anderson said in an interview. ``It didn't have to
happen, yet it did. I can't blame it on anything other than the fact
he (the other driver, celebrating his 18th birthday) was drunk.''
   The accident happened after Anderson had enjoyed one of the most
successful and diverse careers among Nashville entertainers.
   Anderson had been co-host of the ABC game show ``The Better
Sex,'' had appeared periodically for three years on the soap opera
``One Life to Live'' and also acted in television's ``Alias Smith
and Jones'' and ``The Men.''
   He appeared frequently on other TV game shows such as ``Hollywood
Squares'' and ``The Match Game.'' Anderson had recorded more than 40
country music albums and won more than 50 awards for song writing.
He had appeared regularly on the Grand Ole Opry since 1961.
   But the accident wasn't the only tragedy faced by the Andersons.
Daughter Terri, now 28, was diagnosed as having cancer, he lost
millions as an investor in a restaurant chain and his own health
declined because of a debilitating back problem that kept him on
pain medication for months.
   ``These things kept happening and you wake up every day and hope
the last straw is on the camel's back and nothing else will
happen,'' Anderson said.
   Finally, life is looking up again. The accident and recovery
strengthened his strained marriage. The restaurant chain is on the
rebound and doctors are optimistic that the cancer in Terri was
caught in time.
   Anderson, whose best known songs are ``Still'' and ``City
Lights,'' said writing the book was therapeutic.
   ``When everything came down as hard and fast as it did, I had so
much built up it just had to come out,'' he said.
   Anderson said the adversity ``made me realize how blessed I had
been all my life, that I really had lived a charmed life up until
then. It made me thankful and more grateful for that. You take
things like good health for granted.
   ``I think the biggest effect overall was in my priorities,'' he
said. ``Things that I thought were important were not and things I
didn't think were important were more important than I had ever
realized, such as my family.
   ``I had put career ahead of family at times, but I don't think
I'll do that any more.
   ``I learned about determination, especially from watching what
Becky did (during recovery). There never has been a human being more
determined.''
   In writing the book, he learned quickly that it's more work than
composing a song. ``You write a song and you write one page and
you're finished. With a book, you're just getting started.''
   Anderson said he got some good advice from fellow Grand Ole Opry
star Jan Howard, who also recently wrote an autobiography.
   ``She said when you mention frying the onions, you have got to
make them smell the onions.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 7-9</NOTE>
