<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--OldandDrugged-Rules Adv29   06-26 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Old and Drugged-Rules, Adv 29,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Consumer Group's Rules For Safer Drug Use By The Elderly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-PRI--Old and Drugged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are 10 rules for safer drug use adapted
from ``Worst Pills, Best Pills: The Older Adult's Guide to Avoiding
Drug-Induced Death or Illness,'' by Dr. Sidney Wolfe and others at
the Public Citizen Health Research Group.
   (1) Have ``brown bag sessions'' with your primary doctor. When
you go to a doctor you haven't seen before or with whom you have
never had such a session, dump into a bag all prescription and
over-the-counter drugs you are using, have used in the last month or
are likely to use, and take them along.
   Discuss the reason each was prescribed, the dose and frequency,
how long you should take it, possible side effects, possible
interactions with foods or other drugs, and whether you can stop
taking any of them.
   (2) Contact your doctor if you have any of the following symptoms
after starting a drug: depression, hallucinations, confusion,
delirium, memory loss, impaired thinking, shaking or twitching,
dizziness upon standing, falls, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting,
abdominal pain, bleeding, constipation, diarrhea, difficulty
urinating and loss of bladder control.
   (3) ``Assume that any new symptom you develop after starting a
new drug might be caused by the drug.'' Report it to your doctor.
   (4) Make sure you really need the drug for your condition and ask
whether the side effects may be worse than the disease.
   (5) ``If drug therapy is indicated, in most cases it is safer to
start with a dose that is lower than the usual adult dose.''
   (6) When adding a drug, see if it is possible to stop another
drug.
   (7) Review with your doctor at least every three to six months
the need to keep taking each drug.
   (8) Before leaving the doctor's office or pharmacy, make sure you
and a family member or friend understand the instructions for taking
the medication.
   (9) ``Discard all old drugs carefully.'' Throw them away when
your therapy is over so you aren't tempted to use or give away
outdated drugs.
   (10) ``Ask your primary doctor to coordinate your care and drugs.
If you see a specialist and he or she wants to start you on new
medicines in addition to the ones you are on, check with your
primary doctor first.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
