<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Elderly-Profile Adv29   06-26 0930</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Elderly-Profile, Adv 29,0955</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elderly Growing in Number and Influence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When next year's head count is done Census
Bureau officials expect to report there are more people aged 65 and
over than there were Americans at the time of the Civil War.
   The 1860 Census found 31.4 million Americans. The 1990 count is
expected to find 31.6 million people 65 and older, 13.2 million of
those being 75 and older. The 1830 Census counted 12.9 million
people.
   ``There is no historical precedent for the aging of our
population. We are in the midst of a new social phenomenon,'' wrote
Beth J. Soldo and Emily M. Agree in ``America's Elderly,'' a study
for the private Population Reference Bureau. ``We cannot foresee all
the repercussions, implications, or social changes stemming from the
presence of so many older persons and the aging of society.''
   People born in 1900 could expect to live 47 years. Life
expectancy passed 50 in 1908, topped 60 in the 1930s and hit 70 in
the '60s. Americans born today can expect to live about 75 years,
thanks largely to better medical care.
   The elderly comprise about 12.2 percent of the population. Well
over half are women, 70 percent say they're healthy and
three-fourths own their homes. They also spend a greater percentage
of what are often fixed incomes on food, housing and health care
than younger people.
   But take a closer look.
   By definition the elderly are 65 and up, but the mix is changing.
In 1960, 6.1 percent of the population was 65 to 74 and 3.1 percent
was 75 and older. By 1987, 7.2 percent were 65 to 74 and 5 percent
were 75 or older.
   A half-century ago, men and women comprised equal numbers of the
elderly, but women began living longer in the 1930s as pregnancy-and
childbirth-related deaths began declining. Women now live an average
78.3 years, compared with 71.5 years for men, and comprise 59.2
percent of those age 65 and over.
   As of 1988, 10.3 percent of all American males were 65 or older,
compared with 14.3 percent of all women.
   ``The problems of old age in America are largely the problems of
women. Six out of every 10 older Americans are women,'' said Dr.
Robert Butler, a former director of the National Institute on Aging.
   ``In general, older women have fewer financial assets and,
because they typically outlive their spouses, are more dependent on
adult children and formal health care services,'' Agree and Soldo
wrote.
   And that poses a problem, with the need for home care for many
elderly rising just as social change threatens to undermine the
traditional source of that care, says researcher Alice T. Day. In a
1985 Population Reference Bureau report, she estimated 6.6 million
elderly people needed long-term care but only 1.4 million were in
nursing homes. The rest were helped by families. But small families
mean fewer young people to care for the elderly and most of them
face other obligations, including jobs.
   While elderly women tend to be widows, 80 percent of men aged 65
to 74 are married, as are 66 percent of those aged 75 and over.
   As people age, health is of increasing concern. ``Four out of
every five noninstitutionalized older persons have at least one
chronic condition and many have more than one,'' said Soldo and
Agree. ``The most common of these diseases are arthritis,
hypertension, heart disease and hearing impairments.''
   The National Center for Health Statistics reported in 1984 that
23 percent of the elderly had trouble completing at least one common
task like shopping, preparing meals and housework.
   Nevertheless, a survey by the center found that 70 percent of
elderly considered themselves to be in good or excellent health.
Those with higher incomes were more likely to list themselves in
excellent health.
   Since most elderly people are retired, they have lower average
incomes. In 1986, median income for families headed by someone 65
and older was $19,932, about 62 percent of that for families headed
by someone 25 to 64. The Senate Special Committee on Aging in 1985
reported a median income of $20,354 for families with a 65- to
74-year-old head, $16,412 for those headed by 75- to 84-year-olds,
and $15,111 for 85 and over.
   With less cash, the elderly tend to spend a bigger percentage of
it on food, housing and health care than do younger people. Even so,
business now views the elderly as a market segment of growing
importance, and has begun targeting products and advertising.
   Another place where the elderly have attracted attention is the
voting booth. More than one in five voters in the 1986 congressional
elections was 65 and over. While 46 percent of all eligible voters
went to the polls, 65.1 percent of those 65 to 74 voted, the most of
any population segment.
   The Senate committee found that most older people are adequately
housed, although some have problems finding affordable homes. In
1985, three-fourths of elder households owned their home and 25
percent rented. Males were more likely to own than were females, and
those over age 75 were more likely to rent.
   The elderly tended to occupy older homes, 36 percent living in
house built before 1940, compared to 21 percent of younger people.
The 1983 Annual Housing Survey found 10 percent of the homes
occupied by the elderly with some serious flaw in such areas as
plumbing, electrical, structure and heating.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--RetireeSkills Adv29   06-26 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Retiree Skills, Adv 29,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retiree Skills: Workers Go from Inactivity to Productivity</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY305 planned for June 26</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   James Walters worked for the AP as a reporter and
editor from 1947 until he retired in 1984.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JAMES E. WALTERS</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Bob Rheinhart needed to expand his
office recently, he didn't have to look far for expertise. The
architect and skilled craftspeople he needed all were on his payroll
_ and they all were retired.
   So are the office workers at Rheinhart's 11-year-old Retiree
Skills Inc., a temporary-help agency handling people over age 50.
Ads on buses, cabs and elsewhere say it offers employers
``Experience! Skills! Dependability!''
   ``I don't care how many age discrimination laws there are, age is
the main reason people over 50 aren't hired when they seek work,''
says Rheinhart, a 68-year-old retired stockbroker. ``We don't
guarantee we'll get anyone a job, but on the other hand we don't
charge them anything either.''
   Jack Shine and Roscoe Lacy, both 70, have been with Retiree
Skills almost from its start 11 years ago.
   ``I'd be lost without something productive to do, and with the
cost of living what it is the money don't hurt anything either,''
says Shine, who ran his own sporting goods store for years. Now he
paints houses, limits his work week to 24 hours and will continue
``as long as I can climb a ladder.''
   Lacy, who spent 30 years in the Navy, averages 24 hours a week,
filling in for school custodians who are sick or on vacation. ``I'll
do it as long as I can get around. When you're active it keeps you
young.''
   Retiree Skills offers workers in more than 200 job
classifications, including secretaries, engineers, accountants,
electricians, word processors, chemists, plumbers, carpenters,
mail-room personnel, equipment operators, masons, computer
programmers, auditors and laborers.
   ``There's even a professional clown,'' Rheinhart says.
   The National Council on Aging says it knows of no similar group.
Most temporary-help agencies specialize in categories like office
workers; most employment organizations for retirees are limited to
one type of professional.
   Workers remain on the payroll of Retiree Skills, saving the
temporary employer Social Security, sick pay, retirement, vacation
and insurance costs, which can total a third or more of the average
payroll. Employers are billed for actual time at a rate above what
workers are paid, which Rheinhart says is near the area's prevailing
wage for their skill. The minimum is $4 an hour.
   More than 300 companies have used Retiree Skills and Rheinhart
says he has found work for more than 2,500 people. About 800 now are
registered.
   ``Most came to us originally as a last resort. Can you believe
the morale boost for someone who's almost at the point of feeling
useless and then finding he's got talent that people are looking for
and are willing to pay for? And the flip side is that the people who
use them are getting genuine bargains. Aside from their skills,
their old-fashioned work ethic is so different from what's
fashionable today among younger people,'' Rheinhart says.
   ``I have a very positive reaction to Retiree Skills,'' says
Barbara Walker, office manager for Desert Analytics, a small testing
laboratory.
   Harold Koenig, a retired chemical engineer, did so well as a
temporary lab technician that he was hired as a regular, ``working
somewhat less than 40 hours a week because he wants Mondays off,''
Walker says.
   Another worker, a 58-year-old banker forced out in a corporate
realignment, was sent to a savings and loan and stayed eight years.
He had applied for work at 60 places, Rheinhart says, including the
one that finally kept him on.
   Retiree Skills keeps people on Social Security advised about how
much they may earn without penalties. Those 65 to 70 can make $8,800
this year and still receive all benefits. Under 65, it's $6,480.
Generally, $1 in benefits is lost for each $2 earned over the limit.
At 70, full benefits are available regardless of earnings.
   Rheinhart, who had started a life insurance company in Dayton,
Ohio, and a brokerage in Columbus, retired to Tucson to play golf.
``But you can play just so much golf without getting bored. Most of
the people I met were older and I was hearing two things from them _
they either didn't have enough to do, or, if they did have things to
do, they didn't have enough money to do them.
   ``About that time the National Council on Aging put on a TV
commercial that showed an empty rocking chair that was in motion,
with the suggestion it was time for the elderly to get off their
rocker.
   ``Those two things gave me the idea to start Retiree Skills.''
   He hopes eventually to franchise the Retiree Skill idea and has
trademarked its slogan: ``From Inactivity to Productivity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
