<SECOND>BC-PRI--Briefs, Adv 29 - 1st Add,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>BISMARCK, N.D.: from guardians.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Ohio</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Ohio's first guardianship changes in
more than 30 years, courts will be required to appoint investigators
to determine competency and to notify law enforcers of suspected
abuse or financial exploitation.
   The bill, approved by the House and returned to the Senate, also
provides for apppointment of limited and emergency guardians, and
for a competent but physically infirm person to name a conservator,
a provision that sponsor Rep. Katherine Walsh said lets a person
``design a guardianship for his own needs.''
   The bill also raises fees and requires guardians to file periodic
reports.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Oregon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature has approved a bill linking
auto insurance discounts for older drivers with a testing program
aimed at keeping unsafe drivers older than 55 off the road.
   Under the bill, the state Division of Motor Vehicles will develop
an accident-prevention course to help those people cope with the
effects of aging on their driving ability. In addition to brushing
up on laws, participants will be taught how to compensate for the
loss of some of their physical skills.
   Insurance companies would be required to offer discounts to
drivers who successfully complete the course. Drivers aged 55-70
would have to repeat the course at least every three years to keep
the discount; those over 70 would have to repeat it every two years.
   If signed by the governor, the bill would become effective Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Pennsylvania</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health-care providers would be prohibited
from charging more from a Medicare patient than the
Medicare-approved ``reasonable charge'' for services under a pending
Medicare Overcharge Measure.
   Medicare pays 80 percent of predetermined ``reasonable charges''
and patients are responsible for the remaining 20 percent plus any
difference between the reasonable charges and a provider's actual
charges. The bill would make it illegal for health-care providers to
charge Medicare patients more than the reasonable charge.
   Violators would be subject to public reprimand, orders to
reimburse the patient with interest, and fines of $2,000 and up for
second and subsequent offenses. For four or more violations, a board
may refuse to renew, or may revoke or suspend a provider's license.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>South Dakota</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Mickelson and the Legislature
have launched a campaign to provide more tax refunds to the state's
low-income elderly.
   Under the program, low-income disabled people or those older than
65 can apply for partial refunds of the sales tax or property tax
they pay.
   At Mickelson's urging, the Legislature in each of the past two
years raised the money available for the refunds. The 1989
Legislature set aside $1 million and increased the income limits to
$7,200 for individuals and $9,675 for families for refund
applications submitted after Jan. 1, 1990.
   Since the program was started in 1974, state officials in most
years have had trouble spending all the available money because many
eligible people don't apply. Mickelson has appeared on television to
urge people to apply.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Texas</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Board of Insurance is urging
lawmakers in special session to crack down on misleading and
high-pressure sales of Medigap insurance, designed to cover expenses
not paid by Medicare.
   Proposed regulations died during the regular legislative session
that ended May 29 and Insurance Board Chairman Paul Wrotenbery asked
Gov. Bill Clements to place the issue before legislators again
during the current special session.
   Clements gave no indication if he would put the measure on the
agenda.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
