<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-26 0787</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0826</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. boosted to $12.2
billion its hostile takeover offer for media giant Time Inc., which
is pursuing its own bid for Warner Communications Inc.
   Paramount said Friday it was raising its initial $175-a-share
offer for Time to $200 a share in cash.
   Time, which rejected Paramount's earlier $10.7 billion takeover
bid as inadequate, said its board will consider the new offer ``in
due course.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., the nation's oldest venture
capital firm, has agreed to buy Prime Computer Inc. in a friendly
merger valued at about $1.25 billion.
   Prime, a minicomputer maker based in Natick, had been searching
for a ``white knight'' to ward off a $1.13 billion hostile bid from
MAI Basic Four Inc. of Tustin, Calif.
   Prime's board of directors unanimously approved the merger with
Whitney on Friday, but MAI said it was preparing to boost its offer,
raising the possibility of a bidding war that could sink the deal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp.'s directors accepted
rival Tyson Foods Inc.'s $1.4 billion buyout offer and agreed to pay
ConAgra Inc. to drop out of the bidding.
   Under terms of the agreement, ConAgra will receive $50 million to
end a previous merger pact with Holly Farms. The Memphis-based
poultry processor will pay a $20 million termination fee; ConAgra
will receive the remaining $30 million when Tyson completes its
purchase of Holly Farms stock.
   ``It's a done deal,'' Jim Blair, chief legal counsel Springdale,
Ark.-based Tyson, said Friday of the $70-a-share cash offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-built cars and light trucks sagged
9.8 percent in the June 11-20 period compared with brisk mid-June
sales last year. Analysts said automakers' enticements were losing
their allure.
   U.S.-made cars and light trucks sold at an average daily rate of
39,392 during the period, according to reports Friday from the
automakers. That was down from a rate of 43,682 a day in the
comparable period in 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for big-ticket factory goods in May
plunged at the steepest rate in 10 months, the government said.
   The Commerce Department report on Friday raised the prospect of
layoffs at manufacturing plants.
   Orders for durable goods _ items ranging from washing machines to
tanks _ fell 4.2 percent last month, to a seasonally adjusted $124.0
billion, the department reported. That was the largest decline since
July 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending and income growth both slowed
in May to 0.3 percent, the slowest pace since the fall, the
government said.
   The gain in Americans' income to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $4.39 trillion was the slowest since September, the Commerce
Department said Friday. The rise in personal consumer spending to an
annual rate of $3.44 trillion was the weakest since October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court refused to shut down the
billion-dollar dial-a-porn industry, thwarting an attempt by
Congress to shield children from sexually oriented telephone
messages.
   The court said in its unanimous decision Friday that Congress
went too far last year when it passed a law banning all sexually
oriented phone message services.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shutdown of the Rancho Seco nuclear plant
in California _ the first forced by a voter initiative _ is adding
to the industry's ills, but analysts doubt it will set off a chain
reaction of plant closures.
   Rancho Seco began shutting down just hours after residents in the
Sacramento Municipal Utility District voted June 6 to pull the plug
on a 15-year-old plant that suffered a history of expensive
breakdowns and poor management.
   Anti-nuclear groups hailed the ballot result, and some suggested
it could prove a catalyst for citizen initiatives against other
nuclear plants. But early indications are that the fallout will be
much less dramatic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressmen from all 50 states asked the
U.S. Department of Agriculture to buy nearly 5 million boxes of
apples to help cut a huge surplus created by the Alar controversy.
   The request came Friday in a letter, signed by 114 members of the
House of Representatives, to Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter,
said U.S. Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash., who represents a region
growing half the nation's apples.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market swept ahead Friday to new highs since the 1987
crash as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 49.70 to
2,531.87, surpassing the previous closing post-crash high of
2,517.83 it reached on June 2.
   Bond prices rose sharply.
   The dollar continued its recent retreat against most major
currencies.
   Gold futures prices surged; silver, platinum, soybean and
petroleum futures all rose and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
