<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 0758EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GMBoycott     06-26 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Boycott,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Seek GM Boycott Over Bias Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights gains will be eroded further if a
federal judge approves General Motors Corp.'s proposed settlement of
a discrimination suit, says a spokesman for a group of disgruntled
black workers.
   The Concerned Black Salaried Employees of General Motors has
called on the black community, including co-workers, to boycott GM
products until a settlement it believes is more equitable is
reached, spokesman Napoleon Quick Jr. said Sunday.
   The group also hopes to fill a courtroom with angry workers
today, when U.S. District Judge John Feikens in Detroit is scheduled
to begin two days of hearings on GM's settlement proposal.
   The employee group spent the weekend rallying support for the
boycott it launched Wednesday, Quick said during a telephone
interview from his Detroit home. He said the group has draw up to
600 people at its meetings.
   ``We feel that if the settlement is forced down our throats by
Judge Feikens, then that will begin a new era of discrimination in
this country,'' said Quick, 52, a former GM salaried worker and
plaintiff in the suit.
   ``We feel our days in court have been just about snuffed out
because of the recent Supreme Court decisions'' involving racial
issues including reverse discrimination, he said.
   ``Passive resistance is the approach that we must now seriously
consider to make fair hiring practices a real part of good business
practice in general,'' Quick said.
   The suit, filed in 1983 by four black salaried GM employees, was
certified for class action in 1986 on behalf of 10,000 such workers
in Michigan, Ohio and Indiana.
   GM has offered to pay cash settlements to some workers and raise
the salaries of others. But the automaker does not admit to
discriminating against black workers in pay raises and promotions.
   If accepted, the settlement would amount to $20 million to $40
million over the next five years for the plaintiffs, their attorneys
said.
   GM also proposes to monitor the pay and promotion of black
workers for five years and to assess that information using computer
models for comparable white employees.
   ``We continue to believe that the proposed agreement is a win-win
settlement, and we will wait for the court's review'' this week, GM
spokeswoman Patricia Molloy said.
   But the settlement proposal falls short in several areas,
including payment for damages or lost wages, the Concerned Black
Salaried Employees said.
   The GM plan would make payments only to those workers whose wages
were most out of line, rather than compensate all black workers
whose salary fell below the norm, the group claims.
   It also said the company's proposal would be less binding and
enforceable than current policies under the U.S. Department of Labor.
   Not all of the suit's plaintiffs oppose the GM proposal. One of
the original four workers who filed the suit, the Rev. James E.
Kennedy of Flint, said he favors the proposed settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
