<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved higher against major currencies in
calm European trading this morning as the currency resumed its
upward trend. Gold moved down.
   ``The trend for the dollar remains bullish,'' one trader said.
   The dollar recovered in Asian dealings from its sell-off Friday.
   However, some light selling resumed after a quiet European
opening. Traders cited a slight decline in U.S. interest rates, the
perception that the U.S. economy was slowing and concern about the
U.S. trade deficit.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.17 yen to a closing 140.18 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 140.11 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.9525 West German marks, up from 1.9390; 1.6780
Swiss francs, up from 1.6690; 6.6235 French francs, up from 6.5790;
2.2003 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1850; 1,414.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,412.50; and 1.1947 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1910.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5543 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5675 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $374.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $377.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $375.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $375.40, compared with $370.00 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 42 cents to close at a bid
$376.26.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.31 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $5.26.
</TEXT>
