<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-26 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained
slightly.
   The dollar closed at 140.18 yen, down 0.17 yen from Friday's
close. It opened at 139.80 yen and ranged between 139.75 and 140.20
yen.
   The dollar now has fallen 4.77 yen in the last three trading
days. On June 15, it had climbed to 151.30 yen at the close, its
highest in nearly two years.
   Today's trading totaled $6.6 billion, down from $10.3 billion
Friday, when the dollar declined 1.05 yen.
   Dealers said the dollar was weak in the morning, reflecting
trading at the 138-yen level in New York in the previous session.
   The dollar, however, rose later as some institutional investors
bought it back following a Socialist Party victory over the
governing Liberal Democratic Party in a by-election for an upper
house seat on Sunday, they said.
   The election result left some political uncertainty that helped
the dollar, the dealers said.
   A dealer at the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of
anonymity, described the trading as mainly technical, with investors
buying the dollar when it rises and selling when it declines.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 95.11 points, or 0.28 percent, closing at 33,625.82.
It had gained 205.74 points Friday.
   An offical at Nomura Securities Co. said the slight gain resulted
from stability on the foreign exchange market and a firm stock
market in New York.
</TEXT>
