<FIRST>r f PM-LaborLeader 1stLd-Writethru f0020 06-26 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Labor Leader, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Union, Labor Lose an Unapologetic Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, His union's ..., to include Winpisinger's
age, that retirement began Friday and name of successor. A version moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Winpisinger, the unapologetic,
outspoken, liberal leader of the Machinists union, walked away
quietly last week in the middle of his biggest fight.
   From retirement, however, the labor veteran _ once referred to as
the labor movement's last angry man _ will surely be heard from
again.
   His union's strike against Eastern Airlines was nearing the
four-month point as Winpisinger, 62, took leave Friday of the union
he had joined 38 years ago as a high school dropout and led as
president for the past 12. He was succeeded by George Kourpias, who
had been a union vice president.
   ``I had hoped very much to have that as a retirement present,''
Winpisinger said last week when asked whether he believed the
Machinists would win their war with Eastern and parent Texas Air
Corp. ``But the strike continues. And I'll be more than a casually
interested observer for the most of the way.''
   To Winpisinger, the strike against Eastern and the bigger battle
with Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo is the manifestation of the
``anti-union animus'' of the Reagan years.
   ``There wasn't a single employer in the country that didn't get
that message loudly and clearly and tried to emulate it,'' he said.
``And we've had a wave of union-busting and everything else
reminiscent of decades long ago.''
   But Winpisinger believes the tide is turning, that better days
for the labor movement lie ahead _ if its leaders act responsibly.
   ``When that power comes back, and I view it as inevitable, it has
to be used more responsibly than ever before, so as to diffuse the
notion that we are a special interest, that we bargain only for
ourselves, that organized workers are somehow greedy by
definition,'' he said.
   He believes a new breed of labor leaders is emerging. ``Most of
them are younger, tested, battle-hardened and had to live through
all this evolution and discomfort afflicted by the Reagan years,''
he said.
   ``We've profited from that. We learned what we had to do with our
backs against the wall.''
   His liberal view has prompted some to label him a socialist, and
Winpisinger's criticisms of the Reagan defense buildup often seemed
odd coming from the president of a union representing thousands of
workers in defense-related industries.
   He blames the defense buildup for the decline of basic
manufacturing and research and development in the United States, and
he labels Reagan a hypocrite for making rallying cries for U.S.
industry to become more competitive.
   ``Where the hell do you get all the brains to do that when he's
already siphoned all of them into the defense complex,'' said
Winpisinger.
   His harsh words are not for Republicans alone.
   The Democratic Party, he said, needs to stop trying to imitate
Republicans and return instead to its traditional base.
   ``We have a lot of people who are running around masquerading as
Democrats who are pale imitations of the enemy,'' said Winpisinger,
who nominated Jesse Jackson for president at the 1988 Democratic
National Convention.
   Who will emerge as the party's future leader? Winpisinger's not
sure.
   ``If the American people showed any propensity at all to elect
high school dropouts president of the United States I'd go out and _
given the money _ I'd try it myself,'' he said with a grin, rolling
a fat cigar between his fingers.
   Retirement will take him away from the platform the nearly
million-member Machinists union gave him, but Winpinsinger promises
speak out ``when I perceive the need and perceive that someone will
listen ... I don't intend to be invisible.''
   He will freely assess others but not himself, refusing to discuss
his contribution to the labor movement. Besides, Winpisinger says he
has more important things to worry about.
   ``I have to catch up on 38 years of accumulated tasks,'' he said.
``And find out whether or not me and my wife can live under the same
roof on a daily basis or what kind of adjustments I have to make to
make that possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
