<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0346</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined slightly today as traders
cashed in some of the gains that carried the market to new
post-crash highs on Friday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 6.64 to 2,525.23
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 465 up, 481 down and 510
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.72 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The market's climb last week to new peaks since the debacle in
the fall of 1987 was spurred by accumulating evidence of a slowing
economy.
   As interest rates fell in the credit markets, rumors circulated
that the Federal Reserve might soon lower its discount rate, the
charge it sets on loans to private financial institutions.
   The Fed took no such step immediately, however, and traders began
the new week in a more cautious mood.
   Brokers also noted that the market was running out of support
from ``window dressing'' by money managers at investing institutions
readying their portfolios for midyear reports to clients.
   Time Inc. jumped 5~ to 171}. After the close on Friday Paramount
Communications, bidding to wrest Time away from a planned merger
with Warner Communications, increased its offer for Time from $175 a
share to $200 a share.
   Paramount dipped \ to 57} and Warner lost \ to 58].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .12 to 182.74. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .05 at 364.30.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 49.70 to
2,531.87, surpassing the previous closing high since the 1987 crash
of 2,517.83 it reached on June 2.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 1,065 up, 430 down and 474 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 198.72 million shares, against 176.51
million in the previous session.
