<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Slide On Wet Outlook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices were sharply lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade following
reports of heavy rains Sunday on the western edge of the Corn Belt.
   Wheat futures were trading higher on rumors of new Soviet
purchases of U.S. wheat and on assurances by the Agriculture
Department that grain trade with China would continue despite
international tensions.
   Rainfall amounts of up to 3 inches were reported in parts of
Nebraska with smaller amounts recorded in southwestern Minnesota.
   ``That's supposedly going to be coming right across here,
although we're not expecting anything of that amount,'' said Jerry
Gidel, research director with LIT America Inc., a commodities
brokerage firm in Chicago.
   The corn and soybean markets also were pressured by dry
conditions over the weekend in the eastern half of the Midwest,
where higher-than-normal spring rainfall left some fields too wet
for planting.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.99{ a bushel; corn was 4{ cents
to 8} cents lower with July at $2.57{ a bushel; oats were 2{ cents
to 5 cents lower with July at $1.50 a bushel; soybeans were 11{
cents to 20 cents lower with July at $7.19{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .18 cent higher with August at
69.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher
with August at 81.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent to .60
cent higher with July at 49.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .35 cent to .73 cent higher with July at 34.37 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures were
mixed.
