<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-ForeignBribe     06-26 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Foreign Bribe,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court To Consider Killing Suit on Alleged Bribe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
killing a lawsuit growing out of the development of an aeromedical
center in Kaduna, Nigeria.
   The court said it will review a decision requiring W.S.
Kirkpatrick &amp; Co., a New Jersey corporation, to defend itself
against allegations that it won the contract by illegally bribing
Nigerian government officials.
   Those allegations are raised in a suit filed by Environmental
Tectonics Corp. of Pennsylvania.
   A Justice Department investigation of the 1981 contract between
Kirkpatrick and the Nigerian government led to Kirkpatrick's
pleading guilty to one count of violating the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act.
   Kirkpatrick was fined $75,000.
   Environmental Tectonics, which had submitted a lower bid for the
Nigerian contract, then sued Kirkpatrick. Its lawsuit alleged that
Environmental Tectonics would have been awarded the contract but for
Kirkpatrick's payment of bribes.
   A federal judge dismissed the suit, relying on the so-called
``act of state doctrine.'' It precludes U.S. courts from inquiring
into the validity of a foreign government's acts committed within
its own territory.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, however, reinstated the
suit last year. ``The traditional justification for invoking the
doctrine _ avoiding a judicial determination of the legal validity
of a state's act within its own borders _ is not present in this
case,'' the appeals court said.
   Kirkpatrick then sought the Supreme Court's help.
   The case is Kirkpatrick &amp; Co. vs. Environmental Tectonics Corp.,
87-2066.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-EuropeanSummit 2ndLd-Writethru   06-26 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-European Summit, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Rejects Single European Currency, Central Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Britain concessions, disagreement
over currency, Mitterrand saying he might renege on agreement if Britain
holds up plan to unite; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain today rejected plans to create a
single European currency and a central bank but pledged to accept
some elements of a plan to form a united European market by late
1992.
   West Germany, however, urged the leaders of the 12-nation
European Economic Community to endorse the single currency and
central bank.
   French President Francois Mitterrand, also enthusiastic about a
sole currency and central bank, said he may renege on an agreement
to lift controls on the movement of the French franc if Britain
holds up the economic union plan.
   Under the plan being considered at an EEC summit in Madrid,
member states would gradually hand over economic policy-making power
to the EEC. Surrendering aspects of national sovereignty is a key
issue as the community heads toward dropping all trade barriers and
creating the single market in 1992.
   ``Decisions on these matters are simply not on the current
agenda,'' British officials quoted Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
as telling the closed-door summit meeting. ``We must stick to the
practical and go for what needs to be done now.''
   The leaders adjourned for lunch on the first day of the two-day
summit with aides seeking to draw up a compromise position.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl pressed the leaders to accept
the plan in its entirety, said his spokesman, Hans Klein.
   As part of endorsing the first stage of the plan, which would
begin in July 1990, Mrs. Thatcher pledged to link the pound to the
other major EEC currencies by joining the exchange rate mechanism of
the European Monetary System.
   But a British spokesman, who requested anonymity, said Mrs.
Thatcher said Britain would join the European Monetary system if
Britain's 8.3 percent inflation rate was ``reduced significantly,''
other EEC countries abolish exchange controls by July 1990 and the
community allows an open market in banking and financial services.
   Mrs. Thatcher argued that earlier membership of the currency
alignment by Britain could have shaken the entire system. Britain is
the only major oil producer in the EEC, and the pound is boosted by
oil price increases, which tend to depress the other currencies.
   Since Spain joined last week, only Britain, Greece and Portugal
are outside the system.
   Pedro Solbes, spokesman for Spanish Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez, said that despite the disagreement over monetary union,
``the atmosphere was positive in general.''
   ``But we shouldn't be led into fooling ourselves ... We're going
to have to work very hard ... There's only a slim possibility of an
agreement but it is worth making the effort,'' he added.
   Mrs. Thatcher remained isolated on the second major issue at the
meeting _ proposals for community-wide regulations guaranteeing
workers' rights, including representation on company boards.
   Earlier, Lord Plumb, president of the European Parliament, the
EEC's legislature, cautioned summit leaders in an opening address
that ``all these issues strike at the heart of national
decision-making.
   ``It is not surprising that in the past, the expressions of grand
aspiration have not always produced quick results,'' said Plumb, a
British conservative.
   Mrs. Thatcher, criticized within her Conservative Party for her
often-combative stance toward the EEC, has adopted a more
conciliatory tone in Madrid, stressing Britain's commitment to
Europe.
   Late Sunday, as the EEC leaders assembled for their semiannual
meeting, West Germany indicated that it will settle for a
declaration of ``political will'' as opposed to a firm commitment on
the two final stages of monetary union.
   ``I see possibilities that we will come to a common position,''
said Lutz Stavenhagen, a senior aide to Kohl. ``But we don't want to
go into the blue. We need the political will to come to an end.''
   Mrs. Thatcher's aides discounted reports that the prime minister
feels she is in a weaker position because of her party's defeat by
Britain's Labor Party in elections this month for the European
Parliament.
   The latest British opinion poll, by Harris, was published Sunday
and showed the Conservatives trailing Labor by 14 points.
   The other Common Market members are Belgium, Denmark, France,
Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
