<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stock Close Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on London's Stock Exchange shrugged off
further weakness in the pound to close higher Monday, paced by gains
in dollar-earning stocks.
   But trading activity was subdued in advance of Tuesday's release
of British trade figures for May. Also overshadowing the market was
suspense over the outcome of the European Community summit meeting
debate in Madrid on progress toward monetary union.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 12.1 points, or 0.6 percent, at 2,179.6.
   Volume was 369.9 million shares, down from 490.3 million shares
on Friday.
   The market was boosted from the outset by a favorable response to
Wall Street's strong gains on Friday. A lack of selling pressure
maintained the positive trend, even after the New York market opened
lower during the London afternoon.
   There was widespread caution, however, as traders speculated that
an adverse reaction by the pound to the British trade figures or to
the EC summit could trigger a sharp correction in share prices.
   ``The performance of sterling is by far the overriding
situation,'' one dealer said.
</TEXT>
