<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gave ground today as traders cashed
in some of the gains that carried the market to new post-crash highs
on Friday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 49.70 points Friday,
dropped 13.09 to 2,518.78 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 661 up, 744 down and 497
unchanged.
   The market's climb last week to new peaks since the debacle in
the fall of 1987 was spurred by accumulating evidence of a slowing
economy.
   As interest rates fell in the credit markets, rumors circulated
that the Federal Reserve might soon lower its discount rate, the
charge it sets on loans to private financial institutions.
   The Fed took no such step immediately, however, and traders began
the new week in a more cautious mood.
   Brokers also noted that the market was running out of support
from ``window dressing'' by money managers at investing institutions
readying their portfolios for midyear reports to clients.
   Time Inc. rose 2| to 168{. After the close on Friday Paramount
Communications, bidding to wrest Time away from a planned merger
with Warner Communications, increased its offer for Time from $175 a
share to $200 a share.
   Paramount dropped [ to 57~ and Warner lost { to 58[.
   Hasbro, traded on the American Stock Exchange, gained ] to 22].
The company was viewed as a possible takeover candidate after the
news of the death of Stephen Hassenfeld, its chairman and chief
executive.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .32 to 182.54. At the Amex, the market value index was off
.30 at 363.95.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 100.34 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
