<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-26 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Drop On Rain; Wheat Up On Soviet Buying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of corn and soybeans closed sharply
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rain forecasts.
Wheat futures finished mostly higher on signs of large Soviet
purchases of U.S. wheat.
   Most corn contracts plunged more than 9 cents a bushel following
a wetter-than-expected weekend in Iowa, Nebraska and southwestern
Minnesota.
   More moisture was expected in the Midwest as the cold front moved
east.
   ``Two-thirds of the Corn Belt is expected to get rain today and
tomorrow,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Talk circulated that the Soviet Union had bought at least 500,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat on the open market.
   Analysts said the buying indicated that the Soviets needed wheat
immediately, since they usually buy U.S. grain through a subsidy
program, which takes longer.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 3{ cents lower to 4{ cents
higher with the contract for delivery in July at $4.02 a bushel;
corn was 4{ cents to 9{ cents lower with July at $2.57{ a bushel;
oats were 3} cents to 5 cents lower with July at $1.48\ a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 12{ cents lower with July at $7.30 a bushel.
</TEXT>
