<FIRST>r f AM-MartinMarietta     06-26 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Martin Marietta,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta Names Young Executive Vice President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A. Thomas Young was named executive vice
president of Martin Marietta Corp. on Monday in anticipation of his
becoming president and chief operating officer when Caleb B. Hurtt
retires in December.
   Young's appointment as executive vice president is effective on
Aug. 14, the company said. His first assignment will be to refine
the company's long-range strategic plans.
   Young, 51, is currently Martin Marietta's senior vice president,
and is head of its Electronic and Missiles Group in Orlando, Fla.
   Allan Norton was named to succeed Young as head of the aerospace
and defense contractor's Electronics and Missiles Group. Norton, 53,
has been president of the company's Electronic Systems division
since July 1987.
   In other changes, J. Richard Cook, who has been vice president of
technical operations for Martin Marietta Aeronautics Group in
Denver, Colo., will move to Orlando, Fla., on July 5 to begin
transition as Norton's successor.
   Andrew J. Stofan, vice president of Martin Marietta's Advanced
Launch System program in Denver, will succeed Cook as vice president
of technical operations effective July 5.
</TEXT>
