<FIRST>u f AM-Sears Bjt   06-26 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears, Bjt,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Will Move 6,000-Employee Merchandise Group to Chicago Suburb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. will move its 6,000-worker
merchandising hub from downtown Chicago to suburban Hoffman Estates,
the giant retailer announced Monday in capping a bidding war between
Illinois and the Sunbelt for the facility.
   Illinois won the contest with the aid of a $61 million package of
incentives, which was backed by local tax incentives reportedly
totaling up to $178 million.
   ``We believe this Chicagoland location will serve the best
interests of our company and its shareholders for decades to come,''
Chairman Edward Brennan said at a morning news conference in the
downtown Sears Tower.
   Last fall, the nation's largest retailer announced a
restructuring plan that includes selling the 110-story Sears Tower _
the world's tallest building _ and shifting the Merchandise Group
hub to less costly quarters.
   The announcement set off a fierce competition between Illinois
and Sunbelt states, especially North Carolina and Texas.
   Illinois offered a $61 million package of incentives to keep the
Merchandise Group headquarters, said Gov. James R. Thompson, who
joined Brennan at the news conference.
   Jay R. Hedges, director of the state Department of Commerce and
Community Affairs, said Sears would continue paying taxes, but about
80 percent of the tax revenue would be used for development costs of
the Hoffman Estates project.
   Illinois will recoup its investment during the Merchandise
Group's fifth year in its new headquarters, Hedges and Thompson said.
   Hoffman Estates offered a 20-year plan of tax incentives. The
Chicago Tribute in Monday's editions quoted an unnamed source as
valuing the village's incentives at $178 million, although neither
state nor village officials would confirm the figure.
   Peter T. Burchard, village manager in the middle-class suburb of
45,000, said local taxing districts would get $67 million in revenue
over the life of the local plan.
   Sears estimates that building a campus-style facility on the 200
acres it plans to use in Hoffman Estates will cost about $220
million. The rest of the tract also will be commercially developed
and Sears hopes to draw other corporate offices to the site, Brennan
said.
   Brennan said Sears _ which began in Chicago in 1887 _ was
expected to begin moving the merchandising operation to the Hoffman
Estates site, about 30 miles northwest of Chicago, in 2{ to three
years.
   When the Merchandise Group move is completed, about 600 employees
of Sears corporate staff will remain in the downtown Sears Tower,
Brennan said.
   ``We understand the strong ties which Sears has to Chicago and
know that the people of that great city are pleased to have the
decision in their favor,'' said Carroll Gray, president of the
Charlotte Chamber of Commerce.
   ``We understood all along that Chicago was probably Sears' first
choice,'' Gray said.
   Brennan also said Chicago had been the company's first choice,
but he believed it was his responsibility to Sears shareholders to
look at other prospective sites.
   Thompson said the incentive package was the biggest the state has
ever put together to keep jobs in Illinois. Illinois offered $88
million to entice Diamond-Star Motors to Normal in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SearsMove     06-26 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears Move,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Move Has Sensible and Sentimental Sides</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sears Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears Chairman Edward Brennan has a reputation as
a numbers man, and his decision to keep the Sears Merchandise Group
in the Chicago area is backed by some persuasive figures.
   Local tax breaks that reportedly could total $178 million, for
starters.
   But it is possible that sentimental factors also came into play
as Brennan and his team weighed the pros and cons of 50 potential
sites before settling on Hoffman Estates, a suburb about 30 miles
northwest of Chicago.
   Less than a month ago, rumors had the 6,000 employees of the
retailing unit's headquarters packed up and ready to roll to
Charlotte, N.C.
   Dallas was also in the running.
   But the decision announced Monday suggests that Sears'
century-old Chicago roots may run deeper than the Sunbelt sun could
reach.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. grew up here.
   And Brennan grew up with it.
   His grandfather, father, mother and two uncles all worked for the
company at a rambling West Side complex that contained distribution
facilities and, until the completion of Sears Tower in 1974, the
company's headquarters.
   Brennan joined Sears as a clerk in Madison, Wis., in 1956, just
after graduating from college, and moved to the Chicago headquarters
as a buyer in 1959.
   His climb up the corporate ladder entailed a series of
out-of-state assignments from 1967 until 1980, when he was brought
back to Illinois as head of the Merchandise Group.
   In addition to the Merchandise Group, Sears owns the Dean Witter
Reynolds financial services group, Allstate Insurance and the
Coldwell Banker real estate concern.
   Brennan has no great love for Sears Tower, the world's tallest
building, which the company is selling as part of its cost-cutting
plan. Nevertheless, his office will remain on the 68th floor of the
110-story skyscraper, after the retail group moves out.
   The relocation of the retailing headquarters will recreate for
those workers the sort of working environment that Brennan found so
agreeable as a young Sears executive.
   ``When you are housed in a vertical structure, you have less
people interaction than when you are in a low-rise, campus-type
environment,'' he said in an interview late last year. ``You have a
more cohesive organization when there's more people interaction.''
   The sale of the tower may occur by the end of this year, said
analyst Monroe Greenstein of Bear Stearns &amp; Co., who said Sears
insiders had told him they were in no rush to sell the building.
   Greenstein said the decision to move the retailing group to the
suburbs satisfied three major criteria.
   First, he said, Sears will avoid major disruptions of its
retailing operations, a particularly sensitive point because the
company recently launched an ambitious effort to lure more consumers
to its stores by offering lower prices and more brand names.
   Second, in addition to the 200-acre building site, the deal
includes 700 acres along an expressway, including an outdoor music
theater called Poplar Creek. Sears said the theater will continue
operating and Greenstein said Sear's commercialization of the
remaining land will pay for the construction of the Merchandise
Group's new headquarters.
   Third, Sears got all those tax breaks.
   Illinois offered a $61 million package of incentives. Also, the
Chicago Tribune quoted unidentified sources Monday saying the
village's incentives were worth $178 million, although neither state
nor village officials would confirm the amount.
   Greenstein and others said Sears ruled out North Carolina because
it would not have been a convenient destination for foreign
visitors, especially Sears' suppliers from Japan and South Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890626-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Scotus-Glance 1stLd-Writethru f0113 06-26 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0113,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS punitive damages at end; No pickup; A longer version moved
on general newswires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court in business-related cases:
   
   FRAUD
   
   The court made it easier to use a key anti-racketeering law in
civil lawsuits against businesses accused of fraud.
   The court unanimously ruled that the law applies to more than
what is traditionally described as organized crime.
   The case is H.J. Inc. vs. Northwestern Bell, 87-1252.
   
   STRIKERS
   
   The court agreed to set guidelines on when employers may withdraw
recognition of a labor union after hiring new workers to break a
strike.
   The court said it will hear a Bush administration appeal of a
ruling favoring an employer in a case stemming from a 1979 strike
against a Texas laboratory supplies company.
   The case is NLRB vs. Curtin Matheson, 88-1685.
   
   LAWYER FEES
   
   The court rejected an appeal by an Illinois doctor ordered to pay
$254,000 in lawyers' fees to those who successfully challenged a
state abortion law.
   The court, consistent with a ruling by the justices last week in
an airline industry bias case, let stand a lower court ruling
stemming from a 1979 lawsuit challenging an Illinois
abortion-regulating law that included criminal penalties for
physicians who violated it.
   The case is Diamond vs. Charles, 88-664.
   
   AMOS `N' ANDY
   
   The court let stand a ruling that CBS Inc. no longer enjoys
trademark protection for the ``Amos `N' Andy'' radio and television
shows.
   The justices, without comment, refused to review a federal
appeals court ruling that CBS abandoned the trademarks when, under
pressure from civil rights groups, it suspended commercial use of
the shows.
   The case is CBS Inc. vs. Silverman, 88-1804.
   
   PUNITIVE DAMAGES
   
   The court ruled the Constitution's ban on excessive fines places
no limit on how much money can be won in personal-injury lawsuits.
   By a 7-2 vote, the justices refused to extend the prohibition
against the excessive fines to civil as well as criminal cases.
   But the justices left open the possibility that the
Constitution's due-process requirements could put a lid on punitive
damage awards. That issue was not raised properly in the case
decided today.
   The case is Browning-Ferris vs. Kelco Disposal, 88-556.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
