<DOCNO> AP890626-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-26 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher Monday against most major
currencies following last week's selloff.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
troy ounce of gold at $374 as of 4 p.m. EDT, down $3 from late
Friday.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's rebound largely to
technical factors following last week's decline, which some analysts
described as a correction in an otherwise bullish market.
   ``The market was inclined to buy,'' said Robert Ryan, senior
trader at Irving Trust Co.
   Dealers said there were reports of dollar-selling by the Federal
Reserve, but that had little effect on the market.
   The British pound, meanwhile, came under continued selling
pressure despite intervention by the Bank of England.
   Traders said there were no new factors pressuring the pound
Monday. But sterling has been depressed recently by worries about
industrial unrest, Britain's trade deficit and inflation, which is
currently running at 8 percent.
   In London, it cost $1.5450 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers
than $1.5675 late Friday. Later, in New York, sterling fetched
$1.5447, down from 1.5645.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.17 Japanese yen to a closing 140.18 yen. It was
quoted higher at 140.65 yen in London, and at 141.10 yen in New
York, up from 138.85 yen late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday,
included: 1.9590 West German marks, up from 1.9425; 1.6882 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6660; 1.1940 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1942;
6.6480 French francs, up from 6.6000; and 1,416.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,410.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Friday, included:
1.9552 West German marks, up from 1.9390; 1.6840 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6690; 6.6380 French francs, up from 6.5790; 2.2003 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1850; 1,414.00 Italian lire, up from 1,412.50;
and 1.1940 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1910.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $375.10 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $378.50
bid.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $375.25 an ounce, down
from Friday's $377.75. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold was higher,
closing at $374.25 an ounce, up from $370.00.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 42 cents to close at a bid
$376.26 an ounce.
   Silver prices finished mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.306 a troy ounce, down from
$5.330 Friday. Silver rose in London to a late bid price of $5.33 an
ounce from $5.26.
</TEXT>
