<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-26 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Sag To 11-Month Low On International Discord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices sagged to an 11-month low Monday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange amid growing pessimism about
the International Coffee Organization's ability to keep its grip on
price controls.
   On other markets, orange juice futures soared; corn and soybean
futures dropped while wheat advanced; livestock and meat futures
rallied; oil futures rose; and precious metals slumped.
   Green, unroasted coffee settled 1.63 cents to 6.05 cents lower
with the contract for delivery in July at $1.11 a pound, the
market's lowest close since Aug. 2, 1988.
   The sell-off was sparked by news Friday that Colombia, the
world's second-largest coffee producer, would move to abolish all
export quotas unless members of the International Coffee
Organization approve a new price-support agreement at their meeting
next Monday in London.
   The ICO, composed of 74 major coffee-producing and consuming
nations, attempts to control coffee prices by limiting the amount of
coffee that each producer country may sell to the consumers.
   Discord among the members has led to fears that the current
6-year agreement will expire Sept. 30 without a pact to succeed it,
leaving coffee prices open to free-market forces for the first time
since 1963.
   ICO members will consider two proposals next week, one to extend
the current agreement with no change in quotas and the other to
extend the agreement with changes to increase the availability of
mild arabica coffees, the type most in demand.
   ``The two proposals are expected to be voted on but both are
expected to be rejected,'' said Sandra Kaul, a coffee-market analyst
in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Traders fear that if Colombia introduces a motion to abandon all
quotas, other producer countries will approve it and coffee will
flood the market.
   Orange juice futures settled at or near the 5-cents-a-pound daily
limit on the New York Cotton Exchange despite a lack of fresh
supply-and-demand news. The market has been rising on supply
concerns linked to the slow pace of the Brazilian orange harvest.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice settled 3.85 cents to 5 cents
higher with July at $1.86 a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures fell steeply on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid rain forecasts for the Midwest, but wheat futures
finished mostly higher on signs of large Soviet purchases of U.S.
wheat.
   Talk circulated that the Soviet Union had bought at least 500,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat on the open market.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents lower to 4\ cents higher with July at
$4.01} a bushel; corn was 4\ cents to 9{ cents lower with July at
$2.57} a bushel; oats were 3} cents to 5 cents lower with July at
$1.48\ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 12 cents lower with July
at $7.31 a bushel.
   Frozen pork-belly futures leaped on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange following Friday's monthly cold-storage report from the
Agriculture Department, which pegged belly supplies much lower than
expected.
   Frozen pork bellies settled .90 cent to 2 cents higher with July
at 35.55 cents a pound; live cattle were .15 cent lower to .73 cent
higher with August at 70.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10
cent to .48 cent higher with August at 81.52 cents a pound; live
hogs were .05 cent lower to .60 cent higher with July at 49.97 cents
a pound.
   Crude oil futures surpassed $20 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange as the energy market rallied for the sixth
straight day on supply fears and technical factors.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled 9 cents to 54 cents higher
with August at $20.25 a barrel; heating oil was .13 cent to .22 cent
higher with July at 49.65 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .15
cent to .77 cent higher with July at 63.69 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures retreated on New York's Commodity Exchange following
strong gains last week. Analysts said a stronger dollar kept the
market under pressure.
   Gold settled $3.40 to $4 lower with August at $378.30 an ounce;
silver was 2.3 cents to 2.4 cents lower with July at $5.31 a troy
ounce.
</TEXT>
