<HEAD>Eds: SUBs 16th graf, The NYSE's... to CORRECT index and change to
182.20, down 0.66.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned downward Monday as traders
cashed in some of the gains that carried the market to new
post-crash highs last week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 49.70 points on
Friday, dropped back 20.49 to 2,511.38.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
630 up, 840 down and 498 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 143.60 million
shares, down from 198.72 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 171.38 million shares.
   The market's climb last week to new peaks since the debacle in
the fall of 1987 was spurred by accumulating evidence of a slowing
economy.
   As interest rates fell in the credit markets, rumors circulated
that the Federal Reserve might soon lower its discount rate, the
charge it sets on loans to private financial institutions.
   The Fed took no such step immediately, however, and traders began
the new week in a more cautious mood.
   Brokers also noted that the market was running out of support
from ``window dressing'' by money managers at investing institutions
readying their portfolios for midyear reports to clients.
   The dropoff in activity fit a recent pattern. Monday has been the
slowest session of each week so far in June.
   Time Inc. fell 1~ to 164 after trading early in the session as
high as 172\. Late Friday Paramount Communications, bidding to wrest
Time away from a planned merger with Warner Communications,
increased its offer for Time from $175 a share to $200 a share.
   Paramount gained 2] to 60] and Warner rose \ to 58~.
   Losers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, down 1| at
140~; Coca-Cola, down 1 at 58~; Procter &amp; Gamble, down 1[ at 113];
General Electric, down | at 54[, and USX, down 2\ at 34}.
   There was talk that financier Carl Icahn, often rumored to be
considering a bid for USX, might have cooled on that idea or decided
to pursue other ventures.
   Hasbro, among the American Stock Exchange volume leaders, gained
\ to 22\. The company was discussed as a possible takeover candidate
after the news of the death of Stephen Hassenfeld, its chairman and
chief executive.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $10.97 billion, or 0.34
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 0.66 to 182.20.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 1.76 to 373.30, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down 1.40 at 326.60.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped 1.07 to 447.29. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 364.01, down .24.
