<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-26 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures finished higher Monday, led by a
surge in crude oil prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, broke through
the $20 level, settling 54 cents higher at $20.25 a barrel. The
contract had traded as low as $19.78 during the session.
   September crude rose 47 cents to close at $19.42 a barrel, while
contracts for later delivery posted more modest gains.
   Among refined products, the July contract for unleaded gasoline
advanced 0.77 cent to finish at 63.69 cents a gallon and heating oil
rose 0.16 cent to 49.65 cents a gallon. Other contract months also
finished higher.
   With little economic news to drive prices, analysts attributed
Monday's advances mainly to technical factors and to OPEC-related
news.
   Two separate publications reported that Kuwaiti oil output, while
still above the quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, is declining. Kuwait at a meeting earlier this month had
rejected its OPEC-imposed production ceiling and set its own quota,
saying it needed to exploit its massive oil reserves.
   ``The reports came through, the market reacted briefly but the
impact wasn't lasting,'' said Michael Hiley, energy analyst with
Drexel Burham Lambert Inc.
   Kuwait's oil minister Sheik Ali Khalifa Al-Sabah also was quoted
as denying that Kuwait increased its oil sales after the OPEC
meeting in Vienna, Austria, earlier this month. The minister said
that the emirate's sales blitz, which started before the conference,
was halted within days of the meeting's conclusion.
</TEXT>
