<FIRST>r f AM-NorthropExecs     06-26 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrop Execs,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executives Leaving as Part of Previously Announced Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Northrop Corp. executives are retiring or
being reassigned as part of a streamlining program that includes the
previously announced elimination of 2,500 to 3,000 rank-and-file
jobs.
   The moves announced Monday come as the company faces
congressional efforts to cut spending on its premier program, the
B-2 stealth bomber, and as longtime chief executive Thomas V. Jones
transfers power to his successor.
   Retiring are two senior vice presidents: C.R. ``Bob'' Gates, 64,
who headed international marketing, and Joseph P. Gallagher, 52, in
charge of programs. Gallagher will leave active management but
continue as a consultant on fighter plane development, the company
said.
   Three vice-presidents' jobs under Gallagher are being cut, said
spokesman Tony Cantafio.
   The company has previously said that it would cut its workforce
by 2,500 to 3,000 by the end of the year. The main reason given for
the cuts is that the B-2 is moving from development to production,
and fewer workers are required.
   Jones, the chairman and chief executive who will pass CEO's
responsibilities at the end of the year to Kent Kresa, president and
chief operating officer, told stockholders earlier this year to
expect changes in management ranks.
   One industry analyst, John Simon of Seidler Amdec Securities Inc.
in Los Angeles, saw the changes as moves by Kresa to put his own
stamp on management.
   ``There's nothing unusual here,'' Simon said. ``These are the
kinds of things that happen when a new guy comes in.''
   Another analyst, Paul Nisbet of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
in New York, said elimination of foreign marketing hierarchy makes
sense since the company has less overseas business than in the past.
It is ending production of the F-5 fighter plane, sold to foreign
air forces, and electronics sales also are slower overseas than
previously.
   The three other executives leaving or being reassigned are: Jaime
Oaxaca, vice president of total quality management, retiring in
July; Robert D. Lovell, vice president of manufacturing, who will go
on special assignment to the B-2 division; and Lou Carrier, vice
president for program management, who will be transferred to the
aircraft division.
</TEXT>
