<FIRST>r f BC-ComputerCuts     06-26 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Computer Cuts,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wang, Honeywell, BBN Announce Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. said Monday it intends to cut 250
jobs at its semiconductor operation in Colorado Springs, Colo., and
Wang Laboratories Inc. said it plans to sell a personal computer
factory in Scotland that employs 239 people.
   Also, Bolt Beranek and Newman Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., said it
planned to phase out its BBN Communications AS unit in Denmark,
resulting in 200 employees eventually losing their jobs. The unit is
finishing work on an airline reservations network and has no new
jobs to sustain it.
   Honeywell said its cuts would be accomplished mainly by layoffs.
It said business shrank when Control Data Corp. closed its ETA
Systems supercomputer company and stopped buying chips for the
machines.
   Minneapolis-based Honeywell said it was going ahead with the sale
of the semiconductor operation to Atmel Corp., a privately held
company in San Jose, Calif. The cuts would reduce the operation's
staff about 24 percent.
   Wang, of Lowell, Mass., said it would consolidate the work being
done at its Stirling, Scotland, plant at a larger plant in Limerick,
Ireland. It said it hoped to sell the plant intact to some other
computer company but would also offer jobs in Limerick to some of
its Stirling employees.
