<FIRST>r f BC-GtechProbe     06-26 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gtech Probe,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Asks Probe of Gtech Stock Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commmission's
New England enforcement chief said Monday that he asked for an
investigation into whether insider trading in Gtech stock preceeded
the lottery-equipment company's announcement that it was preparing
for merger or buyout offers.
   Dennis Suprenant said he asked the National Association of
Securities Dealers to examine trading patterns in Gtech stock for
the two days before June 8, when Gtech announced it had formed a
special committee to investigate ``possible business combinations.''
   Trading volume during those two days jumped to 212,700 shares one
day and 253,200 the next, compared with an average of 41,800 shares
changing hands daily before then.
   The price also jumped $2 to $14 per share during those two days.
The stock is traded on the NASD's automated over-the-counter market.
   ``Typically, if we see that kind of price and volume movement, we
would ask the NASD to take a look,'' Suprenant said. ``We have a
method of inquiring who the market makers were, who was trading the
stock.''
   Enno Hodding, an NASD spokesman, confirmed the investigation was
under way and said it would take several months.
   Gtech makes computerized equipment used by state and federal
lottery systems worldwide.
</TEXT>
