<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Volkswagen-China     06-26 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Volkswagen-China,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese May Buy VW Plant Equipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW STANTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the equipment at Volkswagen of
America's closed Westmoreland County assembly plant may be headed to
China.
   A team of Chinese automotive engineers has been working at the
New Stanton plant to acquire old conveyor, body shop, painting and
other equipment, said Tom McDonald, a spokesman at VW's U.S.
headquarters in Troy, Mich.
   McDonald said Volkswagen is in ``contractural discussions'' with
First Automobile Works of China to buy the equipment, which he
described as obsolete.
   ``The assumption is that (negotiations) will be finished,''
McDonald said. ``They're here now to study the equipment and start
up some of the equipment ... and presumably they will be here for
the crating up of it and the shipping of it.''
   The 11-year-old plant, about 30 miles southeast of Pittsburgh,
closed last July after Volkswagen reported declining U.S. sales of
the Golf and Jetta models it made. It was the first plant built by a
foreign automaker in the United States to close.
   McDonald said Volkswagen has moved selected equipment from the
factory to its plants in Mexico, Brazil and West Germany. Both the
company and state officials have been looking for a buyer for the
plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
