<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GMBoycott     06-26 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GM Boycott,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black GM Workers Cry Foul In Bias Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people crowded into a federal courtroom
Monday to protest General Motors Corp.'s proposed settlement of a
discrimination suit.
   U.S. District Judge John Feikens told the black workers he would
consider their objections to the settlement and make a decision in
the case soon, said Napoleon Quick Jr., a spokesman for the
Concerned Black Salaried Employees of General Motors.
   The group last week called for the black community to boycott GM
products until it wins a more favorable settlement in the suit,
first filed in 1983 by four salaried black GM workers.
   The suit was certified in 1986 as a class action on behalf of
10,000 such workers in Michigan, Ohio and Indiana. If accepted, the
settlement would amount to $20 million to $40 million over the next
five years for the plaintiffs, their attorneys have said.
   ``The proposal is grossly inadequate and calls for setting up a
double-model standard to monitor black salaries versus white, which
represents a problem in itself,'' said Quick, 52, of Detroit, a
former GM personnel administrator.
   Quick said the automaker's proposal to monitor black workers' pay
and promotion for five years and to assess that information using
computer models for comparable white employees establishes a double
standard.
   GM also has offered to pay cash settlements to some workers and
raise the salaries of othes. But the automaker does not admit to
discriminating against blacks in pay and promotions.
</TEXT>
