<FILEID>AP-NR-06-26-89 2348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FordProduction     06-26 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ford Production,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Idles Two Plants An Extra Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said Monday that it will idle its
Chicago and Atlanta assembly plants for a third week after their
normal two-week summer shutdown this year.
   The week of July 17 will be added to both plants' normal two-week
shutdown for changeover from production of 1989- to 1990-model
automobiles, Ford spokesman Joel Pitcoff said.
   The extended shutdown resulted from a delay in obtaining parts
for 1990 models with new passive restraint systems and wasn't meant
to reduce inventories, Pitcoff said.
   The Chicago plant employs about 2,300 hourly employees and the
Atlanta plant employs about 2,150. Both produce the popular Ford
Taurus and Mercury Sable automobiles.
   Ford has about a 54-day supply of Taurus cars and a 59-day supply
of Sable cars on hand, compared with a normal 65-day inventory at
this time of year, Pitcoff said.
   Pitcoff was quoted by The New York Times in Tuesday's editions as
saying that the parts delay caused the company to delay the start of
1990 production by a week at each plant.
   Because of the delay, Ford asked its dealers to buy an extra
week's worth of 1989 models. But the dealers balked because the
company already had begun taking orders for the 1990 models. The
dealers' reluctance prompted the company to shut the plants for an
extra week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
